<FIRST>d a PM-BRF--HogAuction     08-21 0168</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Hog Auction,0172</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sale, Donations Bring $4,150 for Paralyzed Boy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KALISPELL, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A hog that normally would sell for about
$100 at auction brought $4,150 when bidders opened their hearts and
wallets to help an injured 12-year-old boy.
   Ted Ernst had hoped to show his hog at the Flathead County Fair.
But less than two weeks ago, he fell 60 feet from a tree and was
paralyzed from the waist down.
   Ted is in a Missoula hospital, learning to get around in a
wheelchair. His younger brother, Jesse, showed the hog instead.
   After explaining why Jesse was handling the animal for his
brother on Saturday, the auctioneer opened the bidding on the
240-pound hog at $2 a pound.
   The bidding finally stopped at $4 a pound _ for a total of $960.
   But then people in the crowd started yelling out donations to
help pay for Ted's medical bills. The donations kept rolling in for
about 20 minutes _ and the end result was $4,150.
</TEXT>
