<FIRST>u i PM-TargetPractice Bjt   08-21 0707</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Target Practice, Bjt,0729</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tamil Rivalry Claims Nightly Victims ... of `Target Practice'</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICK CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JAFFNA, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The power struggle within the Tamil
minority claims new victims every night as gunfire reverberates
throughout this war-battered town.
   ``We are now so brutalized that revenge, revenge and more revenge
is our credo. We are wiping out our own Tamil youth,'' said
Vellupillai Balakumar, general secretary of the Eelam People's
Revolutionary Organization of Students.
   Balakumar's group, known by its acronym EROS, is widely thought
to have close ties with the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam, the
most powerful Tamil guerrilla group.
   For the past 22 months, the Tigers have fought the Indian
peacekeeping troops who were sent to disarm them. But they also are
part of a shadowy war for supremacy within the Tamil community.
   Nights in Jaffna are shattered by gunfire and explosions.
   Visitors who ask the staff at the Gnanam Hotel, one of the few
Jaffna hostelries still open, what is going on receive a stock
answer: ``Nothing, sir. Somebody is doing some target practice.''
   The next morning the targets _ young Tamil men _ are found lying
in pools of blood in the streets of Jaffna and surrounding villages.
   ``We don't know who is killing whom, but the dead turn up almost
as a ritual every morning and the sounds of gunfires, explosions,
crying and wailing are part of our daily nightlife,'' a senior Tamil
newspaper editor said on condition of anonymity.
   ``The brutalization has reached such an extent that it is part of
our lives,'' he said. ``No one is interested even in knowing who a
dead corpse is.''
   Like many Jaffna residents, he blamed the bulk of the killings on
the Eelam People's Revolutionary Liberation Front, whose members are
permitted by the Indian troops to carry arms openly.
   The Liberation Front and two other Tamil groups support the
Indian presence and have the most to lose if the Indian soldiers
depart, leaving them to the mercy of the Tiger guerrillas. The
front, once a guerrilla organization, has entered politics and
controls the provincial administrative council.
   Tamil militants and civic leaders estimate at least 10,000 people
have died in predominantly Tamil northeastern Sri Lanka since July
30, 1987, when Indian troops arrived to enforce a peace accord
designed to give the ethnic minority a measure of autonomy. That's
far above the estimate from Sri Lankan and Indian government
sources, whose total since the Tamil revolt began in 1983 comes to
11,000.
   Tamil rebels initially accepted the Indian-sponsored peace plan,
but the Tigers soon reneged and began attacking the foreign soldiers
sent to disarm them. Score-settling and power struggles broke out
among the erstwhile Tamil guerrilla allies.
   The Tigers said they wanted a separate homeland, not autonomy.
Militants in the Tamil community said they needed a separate state
to preserve their Hindu faith, Tamil language and combat what they
said was discrimination by the island's Sinhalese majority.
   Tamils comprise 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16 million people.
Sinhalese, who are mostly Buddhist and control the government,
account for 75 percent.
   The violence that worries people in Jaffna, which used to have a
population of 150,000 but now suffers constant migration, is
reflected by the prevalence of bodies.
   Taxi drivers, when asked if they know where to find any victims
of the previous night's gunfire, tend to respond as Nadarajah
Sivagurunathan did when a passenger hopped in his 35-year-old Morris
Minor.
   ``There are two bodies in Kondavil, one near Nallur, two others
at Kokuvil, but one closer to Jaffna town near the railway line,''
Sivagurunathan said, reeling off a list of locations within five
miles of downtown Jaffna. ``Where shall we go?''
   By nightfall, in the courtyard of the Gnanam Hotel, a Tamil
crooner sings a love song.
   ``The night scares me because you are not here by me.
   ``Why do you expose my vulnerability to a cruel world?
   ``Come here and hold my hand, I am scared,'' he sings to the
hotel staff and a half-dozen guests.
   Suddenly, his Tamil-language song is punctuated by the
all-too-familiar sound of machine gunfire and screams.
   The singer pauses and reassures his listeners in English:
   ``Nothing sir, only target practice.''
</TEXT>
