<FILEID>AP-NR-08-21-89 0113EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Root-Radio     08-21 0695</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Root-Radio,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>Root Case Draws Attention to `New Breed' of Broadcasters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mystery pilot Thomas Root, who admits making
more than $1 million helping investors get radio station licenses,
represented a ``new breed'' of broadcasters who wouldn't know hi-fi
from hamburgers, a critic says.
   These would-be station owners are the offspring of Reagan-era
deregulatory policies that made it easier to acquire a radio station
license than grab a Burger King franchise, says Andrew Schwartzman,
executive director of the Media Access Project, a Washington public
interest group.
   The new rules _ which opened the way for building hundreds of new
stations under looser regulations _ have attracted investors who
would rather buy and sell broadcasting rights than serve the public,
Schwartzman says.
   And the licenses are free.
   ``As far as they're concerned the only difference between a
Burger King franchise and a broadcast license is the one from Burger
King is not free,'' Schwartzman said in an interview Friday.
   Schwartzman said he hopes new FCC Chairman Alfred Sikes, a former
Missouri broadcaster, ``will understand ... the error of the ways of
the past commission.''
   The commission has said it is considering using lotteries for
granting station licenses in the future.
   Root, a Washington communications attorney, drew public attention
to this new-age radio business when he crashed his small plane into
the Atlantic Ocean on July 13. He had been on his way to a
deposition in Rocky Mount, N.C., on behalf of an FM station
investment group he was representing before the Federal
Communications Commission.
   Root said he passed out at the controls and his plane ran out of
gas in the Bahamas after a six-hour flight from Washington. Doctors
in Florida later discovered he had been shot in the stomach _ Root
says he doesn't know how _ and federal authorities are investigating.
   Root missed the deposition and the application was dismissed _
one of many dismissals he is alleged to have caused while
representing more than 160 FM investment groups organized by Sonrise
Management Services of Columbus, Ga.
   Sonrise later broke off its relationship with Root and brought
suit against him for allegedly failing to perform work and
double-billing.
   Sonrise's former chairman, Ralph Savage, told reporters that some
7,000 investors pumped $25 million into Sonrise operations, although
only one Sonrise-related radio station has reached the construction
phase.
   The new era of buy-and-sell resulted from several FCC actions in
the early 1980s, including new rules that opened the way for more
than 700 new FM stations nationwide, Schwartzman said.
   ``These changes have brought in a new breed of broadcaster who is
not concerned with serving the public but profiting from obtaining
and selling licenses,'' Schwartzman said.
   Licenses are granted based on an applicant's standing in the
community and financial well-being, while consideration also is
given to those with minority or female ownership.
   But the commission decided to allow stations to be sold as often
as every year, dropping the previous three-year minimum period of
ownership. Only general partners must disclose financial
information, while limited partners do not have to make such
disclosure.
   Limits were lifted on how much money one applicant can pay to buy
out another applicant's bid for the same license.
   The FCC also temporarily repealed rules requiring applicants to
prove their financial qualifications, although that requirement was
reinstated in April.
   ``The combination of these things made it possible to set up
these deals where they were confident there wouldn't be intensive
scrutiny and where they were confident that they could sell a
license as soon as it was obtained,'' Schwartzman said.
   Sonrise _ advertising itself as offering ``Management With a
Christian Ethic'' _ brought together investors who wanted into FM
radio.
   Sonrise said Root was paid $1.9 million in advance, and Root told
The Washington Post he received $1.6 million.
   The FCC is investigating Sonrise for possible abuse of commission
rules and possible criminal conduct. Hearings are planned on whether
Sonrise illegally controlled some 40 partnerships, and any
information about possible criminal violations could be turned over
to the Justice Department, said agency spokeswoman Mary Catherine
Kilday.
   Sonrise officials have denied any wrongdoing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
