<FIRST>u a BC-EthiopiaQuake     08-21 0162</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Ethiopia Quake,0165</SECOND>
<HEAD>Strong Earthquakes Reported in Ethiopia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GOLDEN, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two strong earthquakes shook Ethiopia and
caused some damage in neighboring Djibouti, the U.S. Geological
Survey said Monday.
   The first quake registered 6.4 on the Richter scale and occurred
at 2:17 p.m. local time (7:17 a.m. EDT) Sunday about 320 miles
northeast of Addis Ababa and 100 miles northwest of Djibouti,
capital of the country of the same name, according to the survey's
National Earthquake Information Center.
   The second quake, registering 6.5 on the open-ended scale, took
place in the same area at 4:09 a.m. Monday (9:09 p.m. EDT Sunday),
it said.
   There were no reports immediately available from Ethiopia on
possible damage. The USGS did not elaborate on the damage in
Djibouti.
   The Richter scale is a measure of ground motion as recorded on
seismographs. Every increase of one number means a tenfold increase
in magnitude. A quake measuring 6 on the Richter scale can cause
severe damage.
</TEXT>
