<FILEID>AP-NR-08-21-89 0132EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-JeffersonDescendant     08-21 0583</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Jefferson Descendant,0606</SECOND>
<HEAD>Descendant Plays Part of Founding Forefather</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILARY APPELMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTESVILLE, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When you're the fifth great-grandson
of Thomas Jefferson and bear eerie resemblance to your famous
forebear, it's sometimes hard to remember which century you live in.
   Just ask Rob Coles.
   Coles, 36, is a living, breathing, spitting image of the man most
Americans know only from the pages of their history textbooks.
   The six-foot-two-inch, red-haired Virginian resembles Jefferson
right down to the freckles, and he has spent much of the last 10
years impersonating his illustrious ancestor in a one-man show
called ``Meet Thomas Jefferson.''
   He was hospitalized for three months earlier this year for what
he called a ``manic break,'' when he thought he really was
Jefferson. He said he takes lithium to help keep the delusion under
control.
   The similarities are remarkable.
   Coles hails from Jefferson's hometown of Charlottesville, where
he lives about four miles from the third president's Monticello
home. His lineage is impeccable: descended on his mother's side from
Jefferson's daughter Martha and on his father's side from
Jefferson's secretary, Edward Coles.
   He shares Jefferson's angular profile and speaks with the same
Virginia gentleman's accent.
   ``He's remarkably like images and descriptions of Jefferson,''
says Cinder Stanton, director of research at Monticello.
   But Coles isn't exactly like the man who penned the Declaration
of Independence.
   ``What's underneath the red hair is the big difference,'' said
Coles, who flunked out of the University of Virginia that his
forefather founded.
   ``Jefferson obviously was sort of a genius,'' he said. ``I never
did very well in school.''
   Coles said he would like to know if Jefferson shared any of his
less weighty traits.
   ``I would (like to) ask him about his college days,'' Coles said.
``How much of a rowdy he was, how much fun he had in college.''
   The other members of his family, whose resemblance to Jefferson
is limited to their ruddy hair, are little affected by their
prominent progenitor, Coles said.
   ``They're all normal people and have normal jobs.''
   Coles had never acted before he began playing Jefferson.
Depressed and looking for something to do after dropping out of
college at age 26, he took up on a professor's suggestion that he
capitalize on his resemblance to Virginia's favorite son.
   Coles' show, which he has performed around the country, includes
family stories about Jefferson that have been passed down orally
through the generations, as well as tales about Jefferson's
presidency and the years before his death.
   ``I try to emphasize just how completely alien Jefferson's
society is to our society,'' he said. ``There were only four million
people in the whole country, which is the size today of greater
Philadelphia. They're two different worlds.''
   Coles has spent enough time with his character that he sometimes
feels as if he is Jefferson.
   ``There are times you get so immersed in what you're doing you
forget what century you're in,'' he said. ``It's hard not to get
carried away with it.''
   But he says he has never thought of escaping his Jeffersonian
legacy by leaving Charlottesville or finding a different vocation.
   ``I think I'll do it for the rest of my life,'' he said. ``What
else can I do?''
   Even so, Coles admits that he sometimes gets tired of being
Jefferson.
   `It's just like anything else,'' he said. ``There are days you
wake up and you feel like Thomas Jefferson and days you want to roll
over and go back to sleep.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890821-0022 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-21-89 0141EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Poland-DifferenceYearMakes Bjt   08-21 0860</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland-Difference Year Makes, Bjt,0891</SECOND>
<HEAD>What a Difference Year Makes for Solidarity in Poland</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DRUSILLA MENAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A year ago, when striking miners demanded
restoration of Solidarity's legal status, the Communist government
rejected it right away. Today, not only is the independent union
legal, but one of its leaders has been nominated prime minister.
   ``I have been fighting for this for a long time, and even a few
days ago it was unrealistic,'' Solidarity leader Lech Walesa said
after his aide, Tadeusz Mazowiecki, was picked Saturday to lead the
government.
   What was once viewed as impossible has happened in Poland.
   For seven years, people risked arrest for even showing the
Solidarity logo. Now members of parliament wear it on their lapels,
shoppers bear it on their tote bags and everyone sees it on a banner
stretched across Warsaw's main square.
   Opposition activists jailed for daring to challenge to the
government now are legislators. All three of the men President
Wojciech Jaruzelski considered for prime minister were put behind
bars by his 1981 martial-law crackdown.
   Walesa is seen daily on state television, foreign broadcasts are
not jammed and there are legal independent newspapers. Poles can
legally buy dollars and private enterprise is encouraged.
   To be sure, there is much that has not changed. There is no
reason to believe the secret police have disbanded or the tapping of
telephones has ended. Indeed, Communists remain entrenched in
positions of political and economic power. And censorship exists,
though it is much relaxed.
   Perhaps most painfully, shelves are still empty not only of the
typical trappings of 20th century life, but basic commodities. Long
lines for staples such as bread continue. And Poland, with the
world's fourth-largest foreign debt at $39 billion, has worsened
economically.
   Despite the rapid pace of change, Mazowiecki's first words after
being nominated prime minister exhorted Poles to believe in the
future.
   ``I think the most difficult task will be to make people think
that it can be better,'' he said
   The trickle-turned-flood of change could hardly have been
imagined 12 months ago, let alone in the past 45 years since
Soviet-backed communists took power in post-war Poland.
   In January 1988, government spokesman Jerzy Urban dismissed
Solidarity as a ``historical monument'' and said Walesa no longer
``represents the millions of members of the former Solidarity ...
(who) do not expect the leaders of an outdated institution to
represent them.''
   On Aug. 26, 1988, less than a week after telling strikers that
legalizing Solidarity was unrealistic, the government _ pressed by
widening labor unrest and increasingly aware it was unable to
control the economy _ offered to negotiate with Solidarity.
   Five months later, the Communist Party completed a dramatic
political about-face and opened the way for restoring legal status
to the independent movement it had spent eight years fighting.
   Walesa, though watched in the West, went virtually unmentioned in
the official Polish press, except occasionally as a private person,
a former leader of a former union or a tool of foreign powers.
   When necessary, his face was edited out of group photos.
   Only in September did he enter newspaper pages and television
screens. He remained there during the ``round-table'' talks with
communist authorities that unleashed political and trade union
reforms.
   By June, Solidarity candidates were allowed to run for all 100
seats in the newly created, freely elected Senate and 161 of the 460
seats in the lower house, or Sejm. They won all but one.
   On July 4, Walesa and Jaruzelski were photographed sitting side
by side in the parliament chambers as the first elected opposition
delegation in the East bloc in four decades took its seats.
   The changes have touched many other aspects of Polish expression.
   Until April, the government controlled all publications and the
paper they were printed on. Independent thought was published in
microscopic print on scrounged paper by underground journalists.
Deliveries were made in secret.
   Now there are legal independent daily and weekly newspapers
produced on government presses with an approved paper allocation.
   In December 1987, when five demonstrators chained themselves to a
lamp post on a Warsaw shopping street chanting ``No Freedom Without
Solidarity,'' a crowd gathered to watch the protest that took
singular courage and was likely to bring serious trouble.
   Hardly a head turned in July 1989 when a banner proclaiming
``Jaruzelski Must Go'' hung on the same street for two days.
   Only in January did Poles receive the right to keep passports at
home.
   Political activists were not allowed to travel and as recently as
March 1988, Walesa was denied a passport to attend a trade union
congress in Australia. Since December, Walesa has been to France
twice, to Italy and Belgium.
   Not only is the long-taboo World War II massacre of scores of
Polish officers at Katyn now discussed openly, but the government is
pressing the Soviet Union to accept responsibility for the crime.
   In history books, Marshal Jozef Pilsudski, a hero for
establishing Polish statehood in 1918, was officially repudiated for
saying, ``I rode the red streetcar of socialism but got off at the
stop called independence.'' Now he is officially honored.
</TEXT>
