<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     08-21 0236</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0244</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tokyo Stocks Hit High, Dollar Off</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange's key index gained
moderately, closing at another high, while the U.S. dollar inched
down against the Japanese yen Monday.
   The dollar closed at 143.35 yen, down 0.17 yen from last Friday's
143.52 yen finish. It opened at 143.13 yen and moved between 142.95
yen and 143.40 yen. It had gained a total of 1.72 yen over the
previous two trading days.
   ``Trading was thin in the absence of market-affecting
incentives,'' said Mitsuhiko Kinugasa, a trader with Daiwa Bank.
   ``The majority of participants remained on the sidelines, trying
to figure out the direction of trading,'' he said.
   On the stock exchange, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average climbed
77.69 points, or 0.22 percent, closing at 35,140.83, a new high. On
Friday, it had declined 26.97 points.
   ``Although the market lacked a leading issue to direct trading in
a certain direction, participants bought a variety of issues,
pushing the index higher,'' said Yoshio Shimoyama, a senior dealer
with Nikko Securities.
   ``The index fluctuated nervously as participants started
arbitrage deals to make profits out of price gaps between the spot
and the futures markets,'' he said.
   A Nomura Securities dealer, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said investors bought issues of companies expected to show good
results for the first six months of fiscal 1989.
   Most Japanese companies report their half-yearly account
settlements in September.
</TEXT>
