<FIRST>r a PM-BRF--MissingSergeant     08-21 0150</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Missing Sergeant,0153</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Missile Inspector Missing in Utah</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Army investigators are searching for
an interpreter assigned to a Soviet missile inspection team who
disappeared earlier this month, a military spokesman said.
   Staff Sgt. Rasa M. Vasyliunas, an interpreter with the U.S.
On-Site Inspection Agency, called in sick for work Aug. 4 and has
not been seen since, Maj. Bill Auer, a spokesman for the 96th Army
Reserve Command and Fort Douglas said Sunday.
   The inspection agency was created in 1988 to monitor Soviet
arms-control inspectors in the United States, including those
stationed at the suburban Hercules Inc. plant.
   Auer said a display of Ms. Vasyliunas's photograph in the news
media had prompted tips to the Army Provost Marshal's office, but
none had proven solid.
   Vasyliunas, 48, has been with the OSIA for about a year. She
speaks German, Russian, Lithuanian and English.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
