<FIRST>r a PM-Savage-Media     08-21 0304</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Savage-Media,0313</SECOND>
<HEAD>Savage Calls for Black Boycott of Media</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Gus Savage, accused of sexually harassing a
Peace Corps volunteer in Africa, says the incident was
misrepresented by the white-owned media and urged blacks to boycott
local newspapers and television stations.
   Savage, 63, called Saturday for a black boycott of the Chicago
Tribune, the Sun-Times, most local television stations and their
advertisers.
   Joined by some black community leaders including Alderman Dorothy
Tillman, Savage spoke to about 300 people who crowded into the
Progressive Community Church in his predominantly black South Side
district.
   In an hour-long speech, he urged blacks to wage ``war on the
white-owned media.
   ``This meeting is about how to get respect from that white press.
We're going to teach them just a little R-E-S-P-E-C-T,'' he said.
   A flyer distributed at the event urged a boycott of WBBM-TV news,
the Tribune and the Sun-Times, calling them ``the most notorious
violators of fair media coverage of the black community.''
   Officials at the television station and the newspapers declined
to comment.
   Savage, himself a former publisher and broadcaster, defended his
conduct on a trip to Zaire in March, when he is accused of having
fondled a 28-year-old Peace Corps volunteer. The House ethics
committee is investigating the incident, and the State Department is
looking into Savage's conduct on that trip and at least one other he
made abroad.
   ``I've had my share of women, and I've never had to hit too
hard,'' Savage said. ``They're making all this noise that some grown
black man hit on a grown black woman ... too hard.''
   The five-term congressman has frequently rebuffed unfavorable
news accounts and criticism by saying they were racially motivated.
He has been able to win re-election easily in the district, which
contains some of the nation's most impoverished neighborhoods.
</TEXT>
