<FIRST>r i PM-China-Deng     08-21 0324</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Deng,0333</SECOND>
<HEAD>Deng's Selected Writings Splashed Across Chinese Newspapers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bold-faced newspaper headlines today trumpeted the
publication of new writings by senior leader Deng Xiaoping, adding
to the aging leader's growing prominence since the crackdown on the
spring democracy movement.
   The half-page article on the front-pages of China's major
newspapers was accompanied by a photo of Deng, who turns 85 on
Tuesday and is reported to be seriously ill.
   The photo taken July 2 is the newest available of Deng, said
officials of the government-run Xinhua News Agency, which released
the picture. Deng was last seen publicly on June 9 talking to
martial law troops in Beijing.
   The photo shows Deng, seated in an armchair, gesturing and
speaking, but does not show where he is or who he is talking with.
   The new volume of Deng's writings from 1938-1965 includes 30
previously unpublished articles and is one of two new publications
of his works since he ordered troops to crack down on student
protestors in Beijing on June 3-4, killing hundreds, perhaps
thousands, of people.
   The other book, ``Twenty-Eight Years of Deng Xiaoping,'' details
his life during the same period.
   Xinhua said it is about ``Deng's great courage, foresight, and
sagacity'' and describes ``Deng's brilliant contributions and
exceptional services to the revolution.''
   The two books are part of an emerging personality cult
surrounding a man who once condemned such adulation because of the
political extremism during revolutionary leader Mao Tse-tung's later
years.
   Chinese throughout the country have been ordered to study his
June speech to the martial law troops. The official press has given
prominent play to Deng's writings and speeches, including a
previously unpublished 1956 speech on suiting Marxism and Leninism
to China printed in major papers last week.
   This month, movie theaters throughout the country began showing a
film on how the 25-year-old Deng led communist forces in
southeastern China. It is the first Chinese movie solely about Deng.
</TEXT>
