<FILEID>AP-NR-08-21-89 0620EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-TropicalWeather     08-21 0188</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Tropical Weather,0193</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tropical Storm Erin Churns Up Atlantic</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The season's fifth tropical storm was churning along
over the open Atlantic today, posing no threat to land, forecasters
said.
   ``This is the kind we like, out in the middle of the Atlantic,
not affecting land,'' forecaster Max Mayfield of the National
Hurricane Center in suburban Coral Gables said.
   At 6 a.m. EDT, Tropical Storm Erin's center was located about
1,350 miles southwest of the Azores island chain, near 23.0 north
latitude and 41.8 west longitude.
   It would be very unusual for Erin to make landfall in the United
States from its present position, Mayfield said.
   The storm packed winds of 45 mph and was moving northwest at 15
to 20 mph. Erin's forward motion was expected to slow as its wind
speed increases during the next 12 to 24 hours, forecasters said.
   Erin became the season's fifth tropical storm late Sunday when
its sustained winds reached 39 mph. Hurricanes have sustained winds
of 74 mph or greater. There have been two hurricanes so far this
season, which runs from June 1 to Nov. 30.
</TEXT>
