<FILEID>AP-NR-08-21-89 0655EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-VietWriterShot     08-21 0433</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Viet Writer Shot,0443</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vietnamese Writer Gunned Down on Fresno Street</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRESNO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prominent Vietnamese author who was
seriously wounded by shots fired from a car as he walked near his
home had claimed that that anti-communists had threatened to kill
him.
   The wounding of Doan Van Toai was the latest in a number of
attacks in California in recent years against Vietnamese refugees
who advocate that the United States establish diplomatic relations
with Vietnam.
   Toai, 42, was shot Saturday morning four times in the head and
upper body by two men in a car, said Sheriff's Sgt. Oliver Moon.
   Toai was moved to an undisclosed location. Moon said his
condition was serious.
   He co-authored ``The Vietnamese Gulag'' and ``Portrait of the
Enemy'' with writer David Chanoff and is executive director of the
Institute for Democracy in Vietnam.
   In a 1986 interview with the Los Angeles Times, Toai said he
received threats after writing an article four years earlier
alleging that an anti-communist group was using funds fraudulently.
   In 1986, a former Saigon housing official, Tran Khanh Van, was
shot in Orange County's Little Saigon after saying he supported
relations with Vietnam. His assailant pleaded guilty and was
convicted. Author Long Vu suffered partial paralysis after a severe
beating in the same Westminster refugee community on April 30, 1988.
   Last January, an arson fire destroyed a Garden Grove travel
agency specializing in Vietnam tours. No suspects have been arrested
in that incident or the beating of Long Vu.
   Some Vietnamese activists believe Toai was shot by
anti-communists angered by his proposal that the United States open
relations with Vietnam, the writer had enemies on the other end of
the political spectrum, said Dam Phuong Tran, president of the
Vietnamese Committee for Human Rights in Washington.
   But he said the writer had enemies on the other end of the
political spectrum, and added that it was possible he was shot by
communist agents.
   Toai came to the United States as a refugee in 1978 after he was
released from a re-education camp in Vietnam, Tran said.
   ``A lot of Vietnamese accuse him of being a communist agent,''
Tran said. ``I think of him as a Vietnamese who tried to do
something good for the people of Vietnam and for the good of the
country itself. That doesn't mean he agreed with the present
political situation in Vietnam.''
   The writer was shot by two men described as Asian and driving a
station wagon, Moon said. Sheriff's investigators have not been able
to talk to Toai because of his condition, he added.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
