<DOCNO> AP890821-0044 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-21-89 0732EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Forbes     08-21 0479</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Forbes,0495</SECOND>
<HEAD>Millionaire Publisher's Birthday Ends With Fireworks, Pigeon Pie</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL GOLDSMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TANGIER, Morocco (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Publisher Malcolm Forbes was proclaimed
an honorary citizen of Tangier as his extravagant 70th birthday bash
drew to a close after a Moroccan feast, seaside fireworks and
nightlong dancing.
   Many of the nearly 1,000 guests, who included some of the top
names in business, industry, entertainment and the arts, rose late
on Sunday, just in time to attend a luncheon offered in their honor
by King Hassan II.
   The king didn't appear at the Saturday night party or at lunch,
but Tangier Gov. Mohamed Laalaj was on hand Sunday to proclaim
Forbes an honorary citizen.
   Most guests were flying home later in the day, having come for
the weekend on three jets provided by Forbes to bring guests from
New York to his Chateau Mendoub overlooking the Strait of Gibraltar.
   The royal luncheon was held at Tangiers Country Club, where
guests watched a display of horsemanship by some of Morocco's top
riders, who fired ancient rifles into the air while riding at top
speed.
   Traditional dancers and musicians were also on hand, as guests
arrived by the bus load at the country club to be served mint tea
from silver teapots.
   The king's sons, Crown Prince Mohamed and his brother Rachid,
were in the receiving line at the country club.
   A smiling Forbes was accompanied by actress Elizabeth Taylor, his
frequent companion since his 39-year marriage ended in divorce in
1985.
   Forbes' four sons _ Malcolm Jr., Christopher, Robert and Timothy
_ and his married daughter Moira Mumma, gave the party for their
father, but Forbes added teasingly, ``I'm paying for it.''
   The guest list featured the rich and famous. It included
billionaire Donald Trump, Fiat Chairman Giovanni Agnelli, opera
singer Beverly Sills, television personalities Walter Cronkite and
Barbara Walters, Spanish singer Julio Iglesias, publishers Katharine
Graham, Rupert Murdoch and Robert Maxwell, former Secretary of State
Henry Kissinger, former Kings Constantine of Greece and Simeon of
Bulgaria.
   They were feasted in Moroccan-style tents to pigeon pie, lamb
mechoui and chicken tadjine. Chief caterer Abdelkrim Tinsamani said
the food cost $750,000, with everything but the whisky and gin
obtained locally.
   There were a few snags.
   The music failed to come in on cue to Ms. Sills' rendering of
``Happy Birthday.'' Many of the guests complained there was no air
conditioning in their hotel and that their hair dryers could not be
plugged in.
   Some Tangier residents questioned the wisdom of such a lavish
display of wealth in a city where many live in poverty.
   But Forbes was unfazed by the criticism. ``I don't feel guilty
about it,'' he said. ``I'm grateful that we can do it.''
   Most guests seemed to agree.
   ``The greatest party I've ever been to,'' said Keith R. Garrity,
chairman of Fansteel Inc., based in Chicago.
</TEXT>
