<FILEID>AP-NR-08-21-89 0740EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Israel     08-21 0481</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel,0495</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bethlehem Mayor Files Complaint Over Killing of Palestinian</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bethlehem Mayor Elias Freij said today he has
filed a complaint with Israeli authorities over the alleged killing
of a Palestinian in the city by security officers disguised as
tourists.
   Freij said in a telephone interview that the shooting incident
Saturday allegedly involving disguised officers ``is a very serious
incident, and I think the government is required to give an
explanation.''
   The action, he said, could have a chilling effect on tourism in
the Holy Land, which already has been badly affected by the 20-month
uprising.
   There were conflicting reports on the incident in Bethlehem's
central market, near the Church of the Nativity that marks the
traditional location of Jesus' birth.
   Freij said Bethlehem residents who witnessed the incident said
two men and two women, wearing backpacks and carrying cameras,
opened fire on demonstrators in the market, killing Radi Mahmoud
Salah, 18.
   An army spokesman said soldiers opened fire after they were
attacked with stones, and that four Palestinians were wounded.
   The spokesman, who cannot be identified under military rules,
said the army was unable to locate any body or to confirm reports
that a Palestinian had died.
   A spokeswoman declined comment on the allegation that security
forces posed as tourists.
   Doctors at King David Hospital in Bethlehem said Salah was
fatally shot in the chest.
   ``As Arabs, we welcome tourists,'' Freij said. ``It is our
national duty to provide them with the best services. But when
elements with guns try to disguise themelves as tourists and kill
people, it could create suspicion among the Arab community over who
is a genuine tourist.''
   At least 540 Palestinians have been shot and killed by Israelis
since the start of the uprising against Israeli rule. Ninety-seven
Palestinians have been killed by fellow Arabs, and 38 Israelis also
have died.
   Freij noted Israeli security forces have disguised themselves in
the past, in some cases by putting press signs on their cars, but
that this was the first reported incident in which they pretended to
be tourists.
   Also today, both the Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip
were shut down by a general strike called to protest an arson
attempt on Jersalem's Al Aqsa Mosque two decades ago. Hospital
officials said troops wounded three Palestinian children in a clash
on the West Bank.
   Shops and schools were closed, and public and private
transportation ground to a halt, according to Arab reports.
   Al Aqsa Mosque, Islam's third-holiest site, was set ablaze Aug.
21, 1969, by a Christian fundamentalist from Australia who later was
judged insane and deported to Australia. Experts have spent years
restoring the shrine, and the work is still incomplete.
   Clashes erupted today between soldiers and stone-throwing
Palestinians in the Tulkarem refugee camp, and three children
suffered gunshot wounds, Arab hospital officials said.
</TEXT>
