<FIRST>r i PM-Ethiopia-Quake     08-21 0295</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ethiopia-Quake,0303</SECOND>
<HEAD>Earthquakes Reported In Ethiopia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Several strong earthquakes shook
Ethiopia and caused some damage in neighboring Djibouti, officials
said today.
   There were no immediate reports of damage or casualties in
Ethiopia.
   The first temblor registered 6.4 on the Richter scale and
occurred at 2:17 p.m. Sunday about 320 miles northeast of Addis
Ababa and 100 miles northwest of Djibouti.
   Subsequent quakes, registering up to 6.5 on the open-ended scale,
struck the same area today at 3:48 a.m., 4:09 a.m. and 4:50 a.m.,
said Dr. Gebre-Berhan Equba-Egzi of the University of Ethiopia's
geology department.
   The department is responsible for measuring seismic activity in
Ethiopia, but Gebre-Berhan said the quakes were too strong and too
near to be assessed by their equipment.
   The U.S. Geological Survey in Golden, Colorado, said the second
temblor this morning measured 6.5 on the Richter scale.
   In Djibouti, the Geophysical Observatory reported that although
the quake epicenter was in Ethiopia, minor property damage was
reported in the town of Yoboki, about 62 miles west of the capital
and close to the Ethiopian border. No injuries were reported.
   Gebre-Berhan estimated the worst affected area in Ethiopia would
be in the province of Wollo between Dubti and Serdo, where the
government runs five large commercial farms. The area is sparsely
populated and its flat, dry landscape is dotted with occassional
mountains.
   A source at the Ministry of State Farm Development said it did
not yet have any reports from the farms, but the highway to the port
of Assab had been blocked by rocks thrown off a mountain about 370
miles northeast of Addis Ababa.
   In 1961, an earthquake of similar severity hit the same region
causing several buildings to collapse in Karakore, near Serdo and
Dubti.
</TEXT>
