<FIRST>r a PM-ToppsAuction 1stLd-Writethru a0461 08-21 0279</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Topps Auction, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0461,0281</SECOND>
<HEAD>$1.6 Million Raised in Bubblegum Card Auction</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 5 grafs to UPDATE with final auction total, CORRECT
year Topps bought out rival to 1955 sted 1952 and CORRECT Topp's to Topps',
both in 5th graf pvs. Picks up 6th graf pvs, `A 4-inch...'.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sports fans and entertainment buffs spent nearly
$1.6 million during a two-day marathon auction of rare cards, proofs
and paintings by the Topps Co., an auction company official said
today.
   The biggest item was a 1953 Mickey Mantle original, which went
for $110,000.
   ``This sporting crowd has a lot of stamina,'' said Arlan
Ettinger, president of Guernsey's, after a 10-hour auction Sunday
that followed a 13-hour swap on Saturday. Today, Ettinger put the
final total at $1.58 million.
   The 2,250 lots auctioned by the house contained more than 25,000
paintings, drawings, and flexichromes.
   Many of the more valuable items were cards by Bowman, Topps'
archrival in bubblegum cards until Topps bought its competitor in
1955.
   A 4-inch by 6-inch Bowman portrait of Frank Gifford brought
$5,000, while line drawings of Wilt Chamberlain and Lew Alcindor
sold for $2,000, Ettinger said.
   Some of the lots strayed from the sports theme.
   A late 50's original of Elvis Presley from the ``Who-Z-At-Star''
card series brought $605. The 3-inch by 5-inch flexichrome photo,
extensively painted over, shows the King from the waist up, mouth
wide open in singing position, in what Ettinger described as ``a
very loud bathrobe with a velvet collar.''
   Uncut proof sheets of basketball and football cards, typically of
132 different athletes, sold in the range of $1500 to $2000,
Ettinger said.
</TEXT>
