<FIRST>r a PM-SpaceShuttle 1stLd-Writethru a0468 08-21 0316</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Space Shuttle, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0468,0317</SECOND>
<HEAD>Columbia Space Shuttle Departs California on Piggyback Ride</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede WARNER ROBINS, Ga.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to UPDATE with spacecraft's arrival in Florida.
Picks up 7th graf pvs, `Bad weather...'.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Boeing 747 carrying space shuttle
Columbia back to its launching base landed here today after bad
weather forced an overnight stop in Georgia, interrupting a flight
from California.
   The modified jetliner, with the 97-ton Columbia bolted on it
back, touched down at 11:44 a.m. after a flight of slightly more
than an hour from Robins Air Base near Warner Robins, Ga.
   The aircraft left Edwards Air Force Base, Calif., on Sunday,
stopping at Sheppard Air Force Base, in Wichita Falls, Texas, for
refueling. Thunderstorms in central Florida prevented it from flying
directly to Cape Canaveral from Texas and it was diverted to Georgia
in late afternoon.
   National Aeronautics and Space Administration officials say rain
poses a danger to the heat-resistant tiles that protect the shuttle
during re-entry to the earth's atmosphere.
   Columbia, the nation's oldest shuttle, landed in California's
Mojave Desert on Aug. 13 after a five-day secret military mission,
which reportedly included deployment of a spy satellite and
experiments related to the ``Star Wars'' anti-missile program.
   Bad weather in the Southwest delayed its piggyback ride back
East, which originally had been scheduled for Saturday, NASA
spokesman Don Haley said.
   Columbia sustained minor damage to its heat-shield tiles during
the mission this month, its first flight in 3{ years. A steering
thruster failed and the pilot's seat suddenly jerked backward during
launch, but none of the problems was considered serious, NASA
officials said.
   The next shuttle flight is scheduled for Oct. 12, when Atlantis
will carry the Galileo space probe into orbit so it can be launched
on a six-year voyage to Jupiter. Columbia's next mission is
scheduled for December.
</TEXT>
