<FIRST>r i PM-CanadianSailor     08-21 0228</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Canadian Sailor,0233</SECOND>
<HEAD>Missing Solo Sailor Found Close to Journey's End</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Canadian woman trying to sail alone across the
Atlantic Ocean was located southwest of England today, 10 days after
she was last heard from, the coast guard said.
   A passing cargo vessel, the Everglobe, contacted Jane Weber more
than 80 miles from Land's End on the southwestern tip of Britain,
said Mike Quinn of the Falmouth coast guard station.
   ``Jane wished to pass ashore that all was well on board, she was
safe and well and she hoped to make Plymouth in about three days
time,'' Quinn said.
   He said she was able to talk to the ship on her handheld radio,
which has very limited range.
   Weber left Halifax, Nova Scotia, on July 29 in a bid to be the
first Canadian woman ever to cross the Atlantic alone. She had hoped
to finish her 2,700 mile voyage by today.
   However, the 44-year-old sailor had not been heard from since
Aug. 11, when she reported problems with her electrical generator.
The device powers her communications and radar equipment.
   The coast guard had asked all commercial ships and air force
reconnaissance planes to watch for her 43-foot cutter, Tilley
Endurable.
   ``We're very pleased for her ... and she's relieved that she's
been able to let us know where she is,'' said Quinn.
</TEXT>
