<FIRST>r w AM:Hungary-Israel     08-21 0373</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM:Hungary-Israel,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Jews Begin Transiting Budapest On Way To Israel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hungary has begun allowing Soviet Jews to fly
to Israel through Budapest, becoming the second East European
country to permit the transit of such immigrants, the World Jewish
Congress said Monday.
   The Hungarian decision is a harbinger of the establishment of
full diplomatic ties between Israel and Hungary in the coming weeks
and of direct flights between the Soviet Union and Israel in the
future, said WJC sources.
   Establishment of Hungary as a third transit point, in addition to
Austria and Romania, is also expected to ease the processing of an
increasing flow of Jews being allowed to leave the Soviet Union
under the liberalized policies of Mikhail Gorbachev.
   The first group of Soviet Jews _ a couple with two children _
came through Budapest last Monday, and small groups have been
arriving from the Soviet Union every day since, said the sources,
who spoke only on condition they not be further identified.
   The recently opened office of the World Jewish Congress in
Budapest pays for the emigres' overnight stay, gives them an
orientation talk and puts them on a direct flight to Israel the next
day, said the sources. Direct flight from Budapest to Tel Aviv on
the two countries' national carriers, El Al and Hungary's Malev,
began several months ago.
   Some 50,000 people, most of them Jews, are expected to emigrate
from the Soviet Union this year, about 80,000 are projected for 1990
and larger numbers in the following years. More than 80 percent of
the emigres go to the United States.
   But an increasing number is going to Israel as they get turned
away from the United States because of a budget crunch that limits
refugee slots and a massive backlog in the processing of immigration
requests in Moscow.
   Romania, the only Eastern European country that did not break off
ties with Israel after the 1967 Arab-Israeli war, has been allowing
Soviet Jews to transit through Bucharest for several years.
   Hungary renewed ties with Israel last year at the consular level,
and is expected to become the first East European country to renew
full ties, probably in the fall.
</TEXT>
