<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--StuntTeam     08-21 0129</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Stunt Team,0131</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stunt Team Involved in Ramstein Accident Will Fly Again</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIVOLTO, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Italian air force stunt-flying team
involved in last year's Ramstein air show disaster will return to
the sky on Sunday, nearly one year after the fatal accident.
   The Tricolor Arrows will perform for the first time since the
Aug. 28, 1988, disaster in Ramstein, West Germany, when three jets
collided and one hurtled into a crowd of spectators. Seventy people,
including the three pilots, were killed.
   Col. Alberto Da Forno, an air force spokesman, said the
nine-plane team will fly far away from the crowd when it performs in
Charleroi, Belgium.
   The team, which has been training at the Rivolto airport near
Udine, northern Italy, will fly to Charleroi on Friday.
</TEXT>
