<FILEID>AP-NR-08-21-89 1244EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-EmptyProtest     08-21 0451</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Empty Protest,0463</SECOND>
<HEAD>Protesters Try to Picket Coal Company, But Find It Doesn't Exist</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY P. KISSEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HUNTINGTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A few dozen union protesters set out
Monday to demonstrate against the Chafin Coal Co., but quickly ran
into a problem. The company, they discovered, no longer exists.
   Undeterred, the demonstrators wound up marching in a drenching
rain outside a bank with ties to the defunct company's owner, who
was nowhere to be found.
   The demonstrators from the United Mine Workers, joined by about a
dozen members of the Communications Workers of America, were
protesting what they charged were unfair labor practices by Chafin.
   The company, they said, ceased mining operations in order to lay
off union mineworkers, and then subleased the mines to other
companies that hired non-union workers.
   The protesters arrived at the former headquarters of Chafin Coal
at about 9 a.m., but found the stone building abandoned and nothing
but a boat trailer in the parking lot.
   The demonstrators paraded single-file in front of the building
for a while, but eventually tired of that and moved on to the Chafin
Building in downtown Huntington. They were told the building is not
affiliated with Chafin Coal.
   The 30 or so protesters finally landed at Guarantee National
Bank, where Chafin's former president, John Chafin Sr., is on the
board of directors.
   There was no indication that Chafin was at the bank, or even in
Huntington. Calls to his home telephone went unanswered; a telephone
at the home of John Chafin Jr., a company vice president, had been
disconnected.
   Guarantee National Bank President Mark Sprouse was not in his
office, a secretary said, and could not be reached for comment. The
secretary said she couldn't figure out why the bank was being
picketed.
   Gary White, president of the West Virginia Coal Association, said
the Chafin Coal building first picketed was the last known address
for the company. He said he did not know what had happened to the
company.
   One of the demonstrators, Fred O. Hartman, a roof bolter who has
been out of work for two years, insisted that Chafin has opened new
mines but hasn't called back union workers.
   ``They say that they're not open anymore, but you call and every
time they answer the phone, they say `Chafin Coal Co,''' Hartman
said. ``Sounds like they are open to me.''
   However, callers trying to reach Chafin Coal on Monday were told
its telephone lines either have been disconnected or changed to
unpublished numbers.
   Hartman said local union presidents held a meeting Sunday night
and decided on the Chafin demonstration. ``They've subleased the
coal out but John Chafin's still responsible for it,'' Hartman said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890821-0063 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-21-89 1244EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Hungary-Economy     08-21 0229</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary-Economy,0235</SECOND>
<HEAD>Meat Prices Rise Despite Warning Strikes</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Meat prices rose Monday by an average of
6.5 percent despite recent protest strikes by hundreds of thousands
of workers, the official MTI news agency reported.
   The state-run meat industry stood firm in its decision to
increase prices although the government and the official trade union
federation SZOT jointly appealed against the move, MTI said.
   State-controlled industries have a great deal of autonomy in
Hungary, one of the most liberal Soviet bloc countries, and
sometimes make decisions independent of the Communist
Party-controlled government.
   Imre Mike, meat industry general director, told MTI the joint
appeal arrived at industry headquarters on Friday _ too late to
postpone the price increase. The news agency did not specifiy
whether the appeal would affect plans for a Sept. 4 price increase
of 6 percent.
   Opposition to the price increases resulted in widespread work
stoppages of up to one hour Friday. But MTI said only about half of
the 2 million people took part in the strike.
   Most of the strikers were steel workers, while food industry and
meat producers heeded an appeal by a newly established independent
trade union federation and kept working, said MTI.
   The meat industry has said the price increases were necessary
because increased feed and fertilizer costs led to a drop in meat
production.
</TEXT>
