<FIRST>r i AM-Honecker     08-21 0188</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Honecker,0193</SECOND>
<HEAD>East German Leader in Hospital Again for Surgery</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   East German leader Erich Honecker has been
hospitalized again following surgery to remove gallstones, it was
reported Monday.
   Honecker, who will be 77 on Friday, was also hospitalized last
month for treatment of health problems related to gallstones. That
illness forced him to leave the Warsaw Pact summit in Bucharest on
July 8, before its conclusion.
   The official news agency ADN said the Communist Party leader was
``on the road to recovery'' after an operation to remove gallstones
last week, but provided no other details of Honecker's condition.
   Honecker appeared in public last week for the first time in more
than a month, looking relatively fit. His absence had fueled rumors
he was in poor health.
   Although neighboring Hungary and Poland have instituted broad
democratic reforms of the type championed by Soviet leader Mikhail
S. Gorbachev, Honecker's leadership has made clear that it plans no
major change in the Communist Party's monopoly on power.
   That stance by the East Berlin leadership has disenchanted many
East Germans and prompted a recent exodus to West Germany.
