<SECOND>AM-BRF--Japan-Workers,0128</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japan Arrests More Than 2,700 Foreigners for Working Illegally</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan arrested more than 2,700 foreigners, mostly
from Bangladesh and Pakistan, this spring for working or living in
Japan illegally, the Justice Ministry said.
   Police and immigration authorities arrested 2,705 foreigners in
Tokyo, Osaka and Nagoya between May 29 and June 17, said a ministry
official, speaking on condition of anonymity. He said 308 other
foreigners surrendered voluntarily to police.
   Japan has deported 3,013 foreigners, including 749 Bangladeshis,
664 Pakistanis, 422 South Koreans, 360 Filipinos, 177 Malysians, 113
Thais, 77 Chinese, including Taiwanese, 66 Indians, 17 Ghanaians and
14 Nigerians.
   In 1988, Japan arrested and deported 17,854 foreigners, he said.
The total was up 26.4 percent from 1987, he added.
</TEXT>
