<FIRST>r a AM-People     08-21 0944</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People,0982</SECOND>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos NY44, NY28</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John F. Kennedy Jr. took the subway his first day
on the job Monday as an assistant district attorney and told
pestering reporters his goal was ``to get through the day.''
   The 28-year-old son of the late President Kennedy, and People
magazine's ``Sexiest Man Alive,'' rolled his eyes as he saw more
than 40 reporters, photographers and TV crew members waiting when he
arrived to be sworn in as one of 69 new assistants to Manhattan
District Attorney Robert Morgenthau.
   ``I felt more relaxed until I saw you guys,'' said Kennedy.
   His preparation for the day: ``I had breakfast.'' His reaction to
the media horde: ``I think it'll pass.''
   Kennedy, who graduated from New York University Law School in May
and took the bar exam last month, was assigned to the Special
Prosecutions Bureau, which handles low-level civic corruption.
   His salary will be $30,000 a year; if he passes the bar, he'll
get $1,000 more. When asked why he didn't go into more lucrative
private practice, Kennedy said, ``It's a great place to work.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Not everyone attending Willie Nelson's concert was
there just to hear the music. Two Georgia farmers also wanted to
shake his hand.
   ``I would like to thank Mr. Nelson for his help because without
him I wouldn't be farming,'' said Frederick J. Hall of Newton, who
along with Carl R. Whitehead of Unadilla met briefly with Nelson
backstage before the Sunday night concert at Chastain Park.
   Nelson is president of Farm Aid Inc., a non-profit organization
that has raised $10 million over the last four years for needy
farmers. Sunday's show was not a Farm Aid benefit.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Hearn, who played the flamboyant female
impersonator, Albin, in the Broadway hit, ``La Cage Aux Folles,''
will play the dignified father in the Broadway stage version of
``Meet Me In St. Louis.''
   Both Hearn and his co-star-to-be, Charlotte Moore, are originally
from St. Louis. Moore appeared recently in PBS' ``The Cheever
Trilogy.''
   The roles she and Hearn will play were originated by Mary Astor
and Leon Ames in the 1944 screen version of ``Meet Me In St.
Louis,'' an MGM movie classic.
   The new production opens Nov. 2.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oakland Athletics slugger Jose Canseco has
gotten in trouble with the law again over his car, this time because
the windows in his Porsche were too dark.
   Canseco was cited for the darkened windows, not carrying a
driver's license and having no proof of auto insurance.
   ``You can see inside,'' he said of the windows. ``They were that
way when I bought the car.''
   The incident Saturday marked the third time the 24-year-old
Canseco has been cited for not carrying his license and was one of a
