<DOCNO> AP890821-0075 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-21-89 1353EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon-Racetrack     08-21 0578</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon-Racetrack,0597</SECOND>
<HEAD>Landmark Racetrack a Battered Symbol of Unity</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Beirut-Past, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FAROUK NASSAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Beirut's battered horse track, frequented
by Christans and Moslems, is one of the few signs of unity in a
nation wracked by bloodshed.
   Old-timers say that when the mile-long circular track goes, it
will mean the end of Lebanon as a state.
   The racetrack, which is called the Palace of Peace and sits in
the no-man's land along Beirut's dividing Green Line, was until
recently still used for occasional private race meetings.
   In the summer of 1988, which was relatively quiet, there were
racing sessions every fortnight, with up to $1 million being
wagered. That encouraged the track committee to repair the
war-damaged gates, stands and betting counters, and set March 13
this year for reopening it to the public.
   But five days before the scheduled opening, fighting erupted
between Christian troops and the Syrian army. The track came under
fierce bombardment, trapping 40 Arabian horses in their stables.
   For nine days, trainers and stable hands tried in vain to reach
them from both sides of the Green Line that splits Beirut into
Moslem and Christian sectors.
   ``When we finally made it, we found two horses fatally wounded by
shrapnel and six dead in their boxes from thirst and hunger,'' said
trainer Sami Dabbour, a Moslem.
   He said the other 32 horses were barely able to stand when
rescuers got to them during a lull last week.
   ``We fed them and watered them and then got them out to safer
stables in west Beirut. I have 10 in my stables and they're doing
fine now,'' Dabbour added.
   Nearly 500 other Arabian horses, worth an estimated $2 million,
were brought out during previous lulls.
   In the old days, up to 10,000 people used to gather at the track,
founded in 1916 during Ottoman rule, every weekend for races.
Politics were never discussed.
   When the civil war broke out in April 1975, the track and its
stands were seriously damaged and it was closed for two years.
   It was reopened in 1977, after the Syrian army intervened to
snuff out the fighting, even though snipers from both sides still
fired from shell-pocked apartment buildings overlooking the track.
   The first race that year was won by a white Arabian named Simsam
_ Arabic for sword _ its neck in bandages because of a gunshot
wounded.
   His Moslem owner, Azmi Ghazi, was hugged and kissed by jubilant
Christians who had bet on his horse.
   The track repeatedly was caught in the crossfire after that. In
1979, when it was open for a while, gunmen opened up on the horses
lined up for the Christmas prize race, then raked the crowded
stands, wounding three spectators.
   When the Israeli Army invaded Lebanon in 1982, 120 horses were
killed and most of the surrounfing pine woods set on fire in the
fighting.
   Races resumed late in 1983. At the New Year's Day race in 1984,
one horse collapsed on the course, bringing down the four favorites.
A 92-1 longshot named Commodore romped home, causing an uproar.
   The committee canceled the result. One man, who had bet heavily
on Commodore, stormed off shouting threats. Minutes later a
rocket-propelled grenade hit the committee's glassed-in,
air-conditioned tower. No one was hurt.
   On Feb. 21, 1985, a militia commander fired three grenades in the
air over the stands because the committee refused to pay protection
money.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890821-0076 </DOCNO>
