<FIRST>r a AM-StreetExplosion     08-21 0287</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Street Explosion,0294</SECOND>
<HEAD>Harnessed Steam Restored At Site Where Blast Killed Three</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Steam service, interrupted when a high-pressure
steam pipe exploded beneath a street and killed three people, was
restored Monday to the Gramercy Park South neighborhood.
   Consolidated Edison Co. said it still was not sure what caused
the blast that released a scalding, roaring jet of steam on the
sedate residential block. It threw mud and chunks of pavement out
from a 20-foot-deep crater and broke windows.
   The power company's steam, piped at 400 degrees under pressure of
150 pounds per inch, heats buildings in winter and powers air
conditioners in summer.
   Utility spokeswoman Pat Richardi but she had no estimate of how
long it would take to repair the street and reopen it to traffic.
   Con Edison has said one possible explanation for the explosion
could be that cold water from a nearby leaking pipe hit the hot,
steel steam line and caused a stress fracture that blew open an
expansion joint.
   ``We don't even have all the pieces yet,'' Ms. Richardi said.
   She said the steam main dated from 1952, and the expansion joint,
which was stainless steel or a steel alloy, was installed in 1968.
   Before the blast, a Con Edison crew had closed off the steam line
while a city crew repaired the water leak and pumped water out of
utility tunnels beneath the street. The utility crew then turned the
steam back on and the explosion ripped open the street.
   One woman was killed while she napped in her third-floor
apartment in the building nearest the blast. Two Con Edison
employees working at the scene also were killed. Two other utility
employees were hospitalized with burns.
</TEXT>
