<DOCNO> AP890821-0087 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-21-89 1511EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Poland Bjt   08-21 0756</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland, Bjt,0784</SECOND>
<HEAD>Walesa Warns Communists: Don't Ask For Too Much</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa warned the
Communist Party on Monday not to demand too much of a role in the
new government, or it ``could lose everything.''
   ``If they play the fool they can lose even more,'' Walesa said in
an interview with The Associated Press at union headquarters in
Gdansk. ``They will be rejected.''
   The Communist Party Central Committee, in a resolution published
late Sunday, said it would not support the prime minister-designate,
Solidarity activist Tadeusz Mazowiecki, unless it was given a number
of government posts that ``correspond to its state and political
potential.''
   The party did not specify how many or what posts it demanded. But
the resolution made clear the Communists want more than just the
defense and interior portfolios _ posts Solidarity already has
offered them.
   Walesa insisted the Communists ``should not fight for keeping
their posts anymore.'' Rather, he said, they must ``abandon threats
and blackmail'' and earn public support by instituting needed
reforms.
   ``We need reforms. ... If the party does not understand that, and
starts provocations ... then it will lose everything,'' Walesa said.
   Walesa said Mazowiecki might, in the end, offer additional seats
to the communists because the government will need ``wise people.''
But he said Solidarity would not submit if the party tried to take
those offices ``by force.''
   Mazowiecki, charged with the delicate task of forming a
government, took a less confrontational approach in an interview
with state radio.
   ``I think we should be mutually open to each other and aim at a
situation that no relations of ... aggression take place between
us,'' he said.
   Mazowiecki was nominated Saturday by President Wojciech
Jaruzelski, who said he made the decision in order to start Poland
on the road of economic and social repair.
   The nomination of a Solidarity leader was made possible when
Walesa engineered a coalition between the union and two small
parties that previously had been allied with the Communists.
   The Communist candidate for prime minister, Czeslaw Kiszczek, was
forced to resign after Solidarity said it would not support his
government.
   The recent developments marked a once-inconceivable victory for
Solidarity, which was crushed in 1981 when Jaruzelski imposed
martial law, and banned the next year. Mazowiecki himself was jailed
for a year.
   Mazowiecki met Monday with various political leaders in Warsaw,
including Peasant Party leader Aleksander Bentkowski. The party is
one of Solidarity's two coalition partners.
   Communist First Secretary Mieczyslaw F. Rakowski, meanwhile, met
Jaruzelski to discuss the political situation and the weekend
communist plenum.
   In an interview in the party newspaper Trybuna Ludu on Monday,
Rakowski said he is looking for ways to ``strengthen the powers of
the party.''
   ``Hundreds of thousands of our comrades are waiting today all
over Poland for the voice of their Central Committee on the issues
most significant, not only for the party, but for the whole
country,'' he said.
   ``Do we capitulate or charge forward? Do we resign from the
values of socialism or are we ready to defend them?''
   He said the Central Committee resolution reflects the feelings of
those in the party who do ``not want to put up their hands'' in
surrender.
   Daniel Passent, editor of Rakowski's former newspaper, the
party-linked Polityka, told the BBC that the party probably would
ask for the powerful ministries of foreign affairs and finance in
addition to defense and interior, which oversee the army and police.
   Mazowiecki said Sunday he has made no final decision on the
makeup of his government but that it would be open to pro-reform
forces from all parties.
   Mazowiecki's nomination must be approved by the Sejm, the lower
house of the National Assembly. Sejm Speaker Mikolaj Kozakiewicz
confirmed Monday that the Sejm had received the nomination and it
would be considered Wednesday.
   Solidarity, the United Peasant Party and the Democratic Party
have enough Sejm votes to elect Mazowiecki without Communist support.
   The Communist resolution was critical of the two smaller parties
for switching allegiance to Solidarity, and accused Solidarity of
breaking the ``round-table'' accords of the past spring, which did
not anticipate such a rapid switchover in power.
   It warned Solidarity that it was taking a risk if it tries to
govern without Communist help.
   ``Neither of the country's main political forces, the PUWP
(Communists) or Solidarity, can independently _ or even more,
against one another _ face the dangers and pull the country out of
collapse,'' it said.
</TEXT>
