<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Azerbaijan     08-21 0236</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Azerbaijan,0242</SECOND>
<HEAD>Azerbaijani Workers on Strike</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Workers at 25 businesses in the southern republic
of Azerbaijan went on strike Monday to press for control over the
disputed territory of Nagorno-Karabakh and other demands, a
journalist said.
   Savinch Najafova, an editor for the official Azerbaijani news
agency Azerinform, said by telephone from Baku, the republic's
capital, that the strike was meant as a warning to Azerbaijani
officials.
   The strikers threatened to continue and expand the walkout, now
planned for just two days, unless authorities meet their demands.
   The walkout is organized by the Azerbaijani People's Front, a
grassroots group fighting for Azerbaijani control over
Nagorno-Karabakh, a mostly Armenian region taken away from
Azerbajain earlier this year. The region was put under the Kremlin's
direct control to settle a dispute over control between Armenia and
Azerbaijan.
   Najafova said a shoe factory and factories making petroleum
equipment and air conditioners were among the 25 businesses closed
because of the strike.
   The People's Front staged a one-day strike Aug. 14, and has been
sponsoring mass rallies in Baku. At a rally Saturday, speakers said
Azerbaijan's Communist Party chief had agreed to just one of their
demands, support for liquidating a special committee administering
Nagorno-Karabakh.
   The strike and demonstrations are also aimed at annulling the
results of this spring's legislative elections and the freeing of
People's Front militants detained during rallies in Baku in November
and December.
</TEXT>
