<FIRST>r w AM-GreatLakesPollution     08-21 0351</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Great Lakes Pollution,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>$3.4 Billion Needed For Cleanup Of 10 Sites, Report Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN FLESHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As much as $3.4 billion is needed to clean up
10 of the Great Lakes' dirtiest areas, according to a study billed
as a step toward putting a price tag on making the lakes safe for
wildlife and people.
   Because of the high cost, governments should explore creative
means of financing the cleanup such as establishing a trust fund and
suing polluters, said the study by the Northeast-Midwest Institute.
The institute does research for members of Congress from 18
Northeastern and Midwestern states.
   The report is significant because of its emphasis on solving the
problem, whereas earlier studies dealt primarily with what caused
the pollution and which areas were worse off, said Michael J.
Donahue, executive director of the Great Lakes Commission in Ann
Arbor, Mich.
   ``The real challenge right now ... is how to pay for the
cleanup,'' Donahue said. ``Any information that can put a number on
cleanup costs and give some ideas on financing would be very
valuable.''
   The 45-page report says experts have just begun assessing the
costs of cleaning up the lakes, where roughly 300 toxic chemicals
have been discovered in fish and some wildlife species are in
decline.
   A U.S.-Canadian commission has classified 42 separate areas as so
polluted they are unfit for swimming, drinking, fishing and, in some
cases, navigation. Rough estimates of cleanup costs have been made
for 10 of them.
   They include Fox River-Green Bay and Milwaukee Harbor in
Wisconsin; Waukegan Harbor, Ill.; Grand Calumet River-Indiana
Harbor, Ind.; Saginaw River-Saginaw Bay, Clinton River and Rouge
River, Mich.; Black River and Ashtabula River-Harbor, Ohio; and
Rochester Embayment, N.Y.
   The cost of cleaning up all 10 areas is roughly $2.9 billion to
$3.4 billion, the report said, adding that the estimate is probably
too low because cleanup costs have been set for only 19 of the 55
contamination sources identified at the sites.
   Contaminated sediments are the biggest pollution source, the
report said, followed by leaking landfills and hazardous-waste sites.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
