<DOCNO> AP890821-0091 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-21-89 1531EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Baltics     08-21 0577</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Baltics,0596</SECOND>
<HEAD>Some Latvians Want More than Sovereignty: Independence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RIGA, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The question among many Latvian activists
who gathered here Monday is no longer whether their tiny republic
will declare independence from the Soviet Union, but when.
   Activists at a conference on national self-determination said
sovereignty within the Soviet Union _ a radical goal just nine
months ago _ is no longer enough.
   ``We now have the strong belief that the large majority of the
Latvian nation favors only independence,'' said Ianis Freimanis,
chairman of the pro-democracy Latvian People's Front.
   As a result, Freimanis said in an interview, the 200,000-member
People's Front will vote in October whether to change the
organization's platform from sovereignty to full independence. ``I
believe this will be approved,'' he said.
   The People's Front asked Latvians on May 31 to make their
opinions known. Since then, three volumes of petitions containing
hundreds of thousands of signatures of people favoring independence
have poured into the People's Front office on a cobblestoned street
in the old town of Riga, he said.
   Although Latvia is barely half Latvian, ``Russians see the
catastrophic economic situation, and also don't believe they will be
better off inside the Soviet Union,'' Freimanis said.
   ``Their only question is `Can we be citizens of an independent
Latvia?' We say yes, and their questions are over.''
   The Lithuanian People's Front, called Sajudis, also is
considering a campaign for full independence, and its ruling council
will consider the issue Wednesday, the 50th anniversary of the
Molotov-Ribbentrop Pact.
   That agreement, signed on Aug. 23, 1939, by Nazi foreign minister
Joachim von Ribbentrop and his Soviet counterpart, Vyacheslav
Molotov, dealt most of Poland to the Nazis and the then-independent
Baltic republics of Latvia, Lithuania and Estonia to the Soviet
Union.
   In Latvia, the only reformers still promoting only sovereignty
within the Soviet Union are Communist Party leaders, activists said.
Among non-party activists, disputes are over tactics.
   The People's Front favors winning electoral control of the
Latvian parliament. The first multiple-candidate balloting for the
Latvian Supreme Soviet is scheduled in February.
   The National Independence Movement of Latvia, in contrast, wants
an alternative parliament.
   The group is signing up voters to participate in its own
balloting.
   When half of Latvia's 1.5 million residents are registered, the
Independence Movement plans elections of local councils and then a
parliament, said Alexander Kirsteins, a board member of the group.
   ``They will say they do not want Soviet citizenship,'' he said.
   But Freimanis fears such a strategy could cost activists control
of the existing parliament.
   Baltic activists have used President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's
reforms, as well as legal and parliamentary maneuvering to capture
most of the Baltic seats in the new Soviet parliament in Moscow,
giving them a national platform and credibility.
   Next, Latvian activists plan a petition drive to ask that a
parliamentary commission be set up to judge 1940 elections in the
Baltic states illegal, Freimanis said. Those elections, held with
the Soviet army occupying the Baltics, brought to power parliaments
that promptly pleaded for their nations to become absorbed by the
Soviet Union.
   Sen. Bob Kastens, R-Wis., told the activists from around the
Soviet Union and the Soviet bloc that ``Americans of all ethnic
backgrounds support your struggle'' because they defend freedom and
democracy for all.
   The United States has never recognized the Soviet takeover of the
Baltics, and representatives of Latvia, Lithuania and Estonia
maintain separate embassies in Washington.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890821-0092 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-21-89 1540EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Africa-Summit     08-21 0491</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Africa-Summit,0506</SECOND>
<HEAD>African Leaders Set Conditions for Talks in South Africa</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-South Africa</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANGUS SHAW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   African leaders declared Monday that
white-run South Africa should end emergency rules and lift bans on
anti-apartheid groups before talks to end racial discrimination.
   The leaders, seeking a new stategy toward South Africa,
conditionally adopted a policy document outlining six preconditions
for talks between the South African government and opposition groups.
   They said the conditions, long demanded by African National
Congress guerrillas, were needed to create a climate necessary for
negotiations. The congress drafted the summit declaration itself.
   The document said talks could ``create the possibility to end
apartheid through negotiations.'' It said the government of South
Africa had the ``urgent responsibility'' to accept such talks.
   The four-day African summit was attended by seven African heads
of state on its opening day Monday.
   Its declaration, adopted by the 16-member Organization of African
Unity ad hoc committee on Southern Africa, will be presented to the
next summit of the 101-member Non-Aligned Movement in Belgrade next
month.
   President Kenneth Kaunda of Zambia is expected to discuss the
prospects for talks in South Africa when he welcomes acting South
African President F.W. de Klerk to Zambia on Monday.
   Besides ending the emergency and lifting bans on anti-apartheid
groups and individual activists, the Harare summit's conditions
included the removal of all troops from South Africa's black
townships, releasing all political prisoners and ending political
trials and executions, and a government commitment to free political
discussion.
   Only then could the government and its opponents discuss a
cease-fire, the formation of an interim government, and a
constitution for a non-racial democratic South Africa based on
one-man, one-vote, the declaration said.
   ``We support the position of the majority of the people of South
Africa that these objectives, and not the amendment or reform of the
apartheid system, should be the aims of negotiation,'' the leaders
said.
   By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated
society in which the 28 million blacks have no vote in national
affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain
separate districts, schools and health services.
   African and Western diplomats, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said while the declaration was couched in conciliatory
terms, it did not represent a significant new departure by
guerrillas fighting in South Africa or African leaders.
   For its part, South Africa has long insisted the African National
Congress and the smaller, rival Pan Africanist Congress guerrilla
group renounce violence before any talks.
   The Harare declaration said South Africa's black majority
reserved the right to pursue armed struggle and stronger
international economic sanctions against South Africa.
   The 16-member ad hoc committee of the Organization of African
Unity, chaired by President Hosni Mubarak of Egypt, includes
Algeria, Angola, Botswana, Cape Verde, Congo, Ethiopia, Mali,
Mozambique, Nigeria, Tanzania, Zambia, Zimbabwe, the African
National Congress, the Pan Africanist Congress and the South-West
Africa People's Organization.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
