<FIRST>r a AM-LotsofTenants     08-21 0358</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lots of Tenants,0369</SECOND>
<HEAD>The Woman Who Had So Many Renters, She Didn't Know What to Do</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When five couples got together outside a house
they all wanted to rent they found they were getting a runaround
that landed the woman who owned the house in jail on charges of
grand larceny.
   The woman took security deposits from seven potential renters,
then tried to hang on to the money by giving them flimsy excuses,
according to a police report.
   The woman, who allegedly used names including Vickie Newton,
Victoria Alexander and Vickie Simpson, was jailed Monday in lieu of
10 percent of a $10,500 bond. The 35-year-old woman was charged
Sunday with three counts of grand larceny.
   The seven alleged victims, not knowing each other at the time,
put down hundreds of dollars apiece in security deposits to rent the
house on the city's west side. Then, according to the report, a
woman telephoned and gave them various stories including that the
landlord was missing, had died in another state or was traveling.
   ``I started to think all the voices sounded alike,'' said Wanda
Malone, who paid $500.
   Then things began coming together for the hopeful renters and
apart for the woman.
   Johnny Hale called state police in Virginia and West Virginia to
confirm that the owner had died as he was told. Neither agency knew
anything about it.
   Gail Rodgers and her husband said they went to the house and
talked to a baby sitter, who said Victoria Alexander was alive and
out on a date.
   Finally, late Thursday, several of the renters and their families
stopped by the house to find out more about the woman. That's when
the would-be renters got to know each other.
   ``We got there. Another couple said, `You supposed to rent this
place? We are too,''' Dellceia Peterson said. ``All of a sudden
there was five couples there supposed to rent this place.''
   As the renters started to leave, the woman came home.
   ``We all kind of jumped out of the car,'' Malone said. ``She came
in the house. We stood there screaming until the cops came.''
</TEXT>
