<FILEID>AP-NR-08-21-89 1641EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-China     08-21 0513</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China,0530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Deng Praised on Eve of 85th Birthday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Newspapers trumpeted the publication of a new
collection of new writings by senior leader Deng Xiaoping, who turns
85 on Tuesday, including a speech that says China doesn't need
Western-style democracy.
   Headlines on the front pages of all major newspapers Monday
intensified the spotlight that has been focused on him since he
ordered the June crackdown on dissent, and reinforced the image of
an emerging personality cult.
   The Xinhua News Agency said one speech in the collection,
originally delivered in 1957 and only recently made public, will
appear in full in Tuesday's People's Daily, the Communist Party
newspaper. The speech also was read on the radio Monday evening.
   In it Deng said implementing small democratic measures would make
Western-style ``big democracy'' unecessary.
   ``We do not support the idea of carrying out `big democracy,' in
China,'' he said. ``We can do without such democracy only if we have
`small democracy.'''
   Xinhua said that by ``small democracy,'' Deng meant that the
Communist Party ``should offer channels through which the masses can
make complaints, express their own views and appeal.''
   The democracy speech was published recently in the magazine
``Party Building'' but it has not appeared before in the popular
media.
   The new volume of Deng's writings from 1938-65 has 39 selections,
30 of them previously unpublished. It is one of two new books by or
about Deng since he ordered troops to crack down on student
protestors in Beijing on June 3-4, killing hundreds and perhaps
thousands of people.
   The other book, ``Twenty-Eight Years of Deng Xiaoping,'' details
his life during the same period.
   Xinhua said it is about ``Deng's great courage, foresight, and
sagacity'' and describes ``Deng's brilliant contributions and
exceptional services to the revolution.''
   Such lavish praise was unusual before the recent political
turmoil, but in the past two months, it has become increasingly
common, hinting of an emerging cult of personality that Deng
previously had shunned.
   Major newspapers also praised Deng for his triumphs.
   A photograph of Deng sitting in an armchair and gesturing while
speaking accompanied the article, and was identified as taken on
July 2. Officials at Xinhua's photo department said it was the most
recent available photo of the leader, who is believed to be
seriously ill.
   He was last seen in public on June 9 talking to martial law
troops in Beijing.
   The photo does not show where Deng was or who he was talking with.
   Chinese throughout the country have been ordered to study Deng's
June speech to the martial law troops. The official press has given
prominent play to Deng's writings and speeches, including a
previously unpublished 1956 speech on suiting Marxism and Leninism
to China printed in major papers last week.
   This month, movie theaters across the country began showing a
film on how the 25-year-old Deng led Communist forces in
southeastern China.
   A bronze bust of Deng was unveiled at the China Art Gallery last
month, part of an exhibit on the democracy movement that the
government calls a ``counterrevolutionary rebellion.''
</TEXT>
