<FIRST>u i AM-Poland-Walesa     08-21 0893</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Walesa,0919</SECOND>
<HEAD>Solidarity Leader: Communists Must `Catch Up With The Times'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GDANSK, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Solidarity leader Lech Walesa said Monday
there is a place for the Communist Party in Poland if it embraces
democratic reform, but it cannot try to hang on to power and
privilege by force.
   ``Fish begins to rot from its head. I am beginning from the head.
We need reforms ... If the party doesn't undertand that, and starts
provoking and only provoking _ and they are _ then it will lose
everything,'' he said.
   Walesa advanced his goal to end the Communist Party's 45-year
monopoly on political power when President Wojciech Jaruzelski
nominated Solidarity adviser Tadeusz Mazowiecki as prime minister
Saturday.
   The party Central Committee, after an emergency weekend meeting,
threatened to withhold support from the first East bloc government
without a communist at the helm if it does not receive a significant
enough role.
   In an interview with The Associated Press at Solidarity's
headquarters in Gdansk, Walesa said there is room in the government
for the Communist Party if its members accept democracy and
pluralism.
   ``They (the party) should not fight for keeping their posts
anymore. If they are wise, we ourselves will offer them those posts,
because we need wise poeple, no matter what membership they have,''
he said. ``But if they want to take posts by force, we won't give
them.
   ``We are not against the party, but we are against its monopoly
and stupidity. If this `nomenklatura' understands what the point is,
it will also be needed,'' he said, referring those given control of
key political and economic jobs virtue of their party membership.
   He said the party must ``catch up with the times'' to survive.
   ``If they play the fool they can lose even more,'' he said.
``They will be rejected. And if they understand what these times
mean, the party may rule for a long time because there are many
wonderful people there who are prepared for that. But they have to
change the system, their concept.''
   Asked why, after initial reluctance, Solidarity decided to forge
ahead and try to form a government so quickly, Walesa said the
independent movement's acheivements since April _ negotiation of
political and economic reforms, restoration of its legal status
after a seven-year ban, victories in historically democratic
elections with the promise of fully free voting in four years _ were
insecure as long as the party remained on top.
   ``We had wonderful uprisings in 1956, '68, '70 and '80. It was
beautiful. Society sprung up. Society got some things, sometimes
quite a lot. And then the party always revived itself and took away
whatever society had achieved,'' he said.
   ``The problems was bureaucrats. They were always arranged in such
a way that they could take away whatever society achieved, and it
was the same this time.''
   Despite its stunning election victory in June, Solidarity could
not control the government due to an April accord that guaranteed a
communist-led coalition the majority in parliament.
   When Jaruzelski went from party first secretary to president, the
prime minister became first secretary and the interior minister was
named prime minister, Walesa decided he could not wait.
   ``The worst combination for the rebirth of the monopoly had
emerged,'' he said.
   ``That is why despite that I wanted to do something big only in
four years, I couldn't wait. The monopoly of the party would have
been rebuilt so quickly that there would have been nothing in four
years. That is why we marched in.''
   By creating a coalition with two minor parties long allied with
the communists, Walesa put together a parliament majority and
proposed candidates for prime minister to Jaruzelski.
   Now Mazowiecki must put together a government that will secure
the help poland needs to reverse its economic decline, stop soaring
inflation, reduce a foreign debt of $39 billion, and fill the empty
shelves.
   Walesa said he is concerned by Poles' impatience with the failure
of the economy to improve, but that the political climate ``will be
for changes and reforms.''
   He said there is no rush for the West to come up with an aid
program, but it can expect help because of the tremendous steps
Poland has made toward democracy.
   ``It is not time for the West yet. First comes formation of the
government and its first moves, wise moves. Then it will be time to
really get into it, although even today we need help because without
it there will be no first movements.
   ``We ourselves did so much more than the West expected. If so, we
can expect more from the West, too. That's obvious,'' he said.
   Looking East, Walesa said Poland's Warsaw Pact neighbors need not
be concerned as long as they do not interfer.
   ``We have no aspirations to lead'' reform outside Poland's
borders, he said.
   ``If it (our concept) fits somebody in the bloc, we are not
claiming a monopoly. They can follow us, they can boycott us, as
long nobody disturbs us,'' he said.
   ``So far, nobody is disturbing us and that is very good. And we
hope to keep this status because we need it.''
   When asked if he thought Solidarity will succeed, Walesa smiled
and said: ``Of course. But it will be hard, because it is very
complicated.''
</TEXT>
