<FILEID>AP-NR-08-21-89 1643EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Israel-Boy     08-21 0694</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Boy,0716</SECOND>
<HEAD>Palestinian-American's Death a Mystery</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By G.G. LaBELLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   EL-BIREH, Occupied West Bank (AP) _ At 14, Amjad Jibril Tawil
liked reading mysteries and wanted to be a technician when he grew
up.
   He was born in Denver, but died in this town where his
Palestinian family has its roots.
   Mystery and controversy surrounds his death. Accusations by
Tawil's family that he was tortured and then shot in the chest by
soldiers have involved U.S. consular officials in the case and led
the army to exhume the body and perform an autopsy Sunday.
   The Israeli army said Monday that based on a reconstruction of
events by an army investigator and a government autopsy, ``the
conclusion is that the death of the boy was not caused by the
Israeli security forces.'' The statement did not say who was
suspected of killing Tawil, nor did it give details of the autopsy.
It said police were investigating.
   The tall, thing youth left home Wednesday to go to prayers at the
Al-Ein Mosque. His body was found Friday by a shepherd in the
mountains outside this town nine miles north of Jerusalem.
   What happened in between is uncertain.
   Ayman Tawil said his cousin got caught up in a protest outside
the mosque in which youths threw stones and the army responded with
gunfire, a frequent occurence after Moslem prayers in West Bank
towns and villages.
   ``Maybe he was participating or he just happened to be in the
area,'' Ayman said.
   Other relatives described Tawil as not interested in politics and
not active in the 20-month-old Palestinian uprising. They said he
spent much of his time reading or raising birds.
   ``We used to talk all the time, but it was only about our pigeons
and our chickens,'' said Nabil Amreh, 14, another cousin.
   Ayman Tawil said his cousin's friends saw him run away from the
protest toward the mountains, where Palestinian youths from El-Bireh
and neighboring Ramallah usually hide when chased by soldiers.
   When Tawil did not return Thursday, the family thought he was
arrested. A woman relative, who would not give here name, said she
shouted to Palestinians jailed at Ramallah military headquarters,
who shouted back that Tawil had been there but was taken away.
   Ayman Tawil told reporters he had seen the body before it was
buried by Palestinian youths. ``There were burns on his body, some
of his teeth were knocked out, and there was a bullet in the
chest,'' he said.
   The family believe the burns and broken teeth are signs of
torture. They hired an Israeli lawyer, Leah Tzemel, who said Sunday
that authorities violated an agreement to delay an autopsy until an
independent pathologist came from abroad.
   ``They didn't wait for our doctor to arrive although there was a
promise,'' she said. ``There are results, but they refuse to give
them to the family.''
   Ms. Tzemel noted that autopsy results often are kept from
Palestinian families, and said she was trying to get a second burial
delayed until the foreign pathologist arrived.
   Amal Arafat, an English teacher at the Friends School in
Ramallah, said his pupil spent much of his spare time reading
novels, especially ones with plots of intrique or suspense.
   A week before his death, Ms. Arafat said, the boy wrote a paper
about his future hopes.
   ``He want to be a technician,'' she said. ``He had an uncle in
Jordan, a technician, who really liked his job. Amjad thought the
pay would be good too.''
   Tawil recently switched from English to Arabic curriculum. His
family is a large clan with many connections to the United States.
Amjad's father, Wathak, works in Miami and was flying home Sunday.
The boy returned to his mother's hometown in 1983. In the United
States the family was known by the last name Jibreen.
   An uncle, Walid Amreh, works in Minneapolis. His children switch
effortlessly from Arabic to American-accented English.
   Amreh, at home on a visit, was asked Sunday why the children were
brought from the United States back to the occupied West Bank.
   ``Our family is here, all our relatives,'' he replied. ``It is
where our roots are.''
</TEXT>
