<FIRST>r a AM-Bakker'sEx-Supporter     08-21 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bakker's Ex-Supporter,0296</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Bakker Supporter Hopes to Profit Off Trial</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bakker Trial, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CH2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS PATTERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Williams once contributed to Jim
Bakker's PTL ministry, but on Monday he was just trying to make an
honest buck off it.
   The 22-year-old Williams set up his lunch truck, called the
``Tummy Taxi,'' in a parking lot next door to the federal courthouse
where Bakker went on trial on conspiracy and fraud charges. From
that strategic location, he sold coffee and food to journalists and
passers-by.
   ``I thought I would try to get a little bit of my money back,''
Williams said. ``I gave money to him regularly right up until he
resigned _ even a little after he left.''
   Williams said he bought his parents a lifetime partnership, for
$1,000, in the PTL ministry and planned to give it to them for
Christmas in 1987.
   ``But they never got to use it,'' he said. Bakker quit the PTL
ministry in March 1987 in a sex-and-money scandal. Soon after, the
ministry went into bankruptcy and later was sold to a Canadian
developer.
   Williams, who lives in Charlotte, operates the lunch truck and a
copy toner recovery business. He said he comes from a Methodist
background but ``developed the charismatic mindset'' when he went to
Oral Roberts University in Oklahoma.
   He said he knew the Bakkers spent lavishly but wasn't concerned
about it in the years before Bakker resigned.
   ``I knew they had a more luxurious lifestyle than any other
minister I knew,'' he said. ``But that really didn't bother me until
I found out how much better it really was. When you're talking
millions of dollars, that's a different story.''
