<FIRST>u i AM-German-Refugees     08-21 0550</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-German-Refugees,0566</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands of East Germans Flee to the West</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TEDDIE WEYR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of East Germans are escaping
through Hungary in the largest flow to the West since the Berlin
Wall was built in August 1961.
   More than 1,000 East Germans have reached Austria since Saturday,
officials said Monday, and the Red Cross has opened an emergency
facility near the border in anticipation of more.
   The exodus of East Germans began after Hungary, one of the most
liberal Soviet bloc nations, began in May to dismantle barbed wire
and other barriers on the frontier. It said freer Hungarian travel
regulations made a fortified border obsolete.
   East Germans have difficulty getting permission for travel to the
West from their strict communist government but can visit Hungary
with ease. More than 2,000 East Germans are thought to have crossed
illegally into Austria from Hungary since May.
   MTI, the official Hungarian news agency, quoted Capt. Istvan
Szoke of the border guard Monday as saying 15,000 people had been
caught crossing Hungary's borders illegally in 1989 and the number
was expected to reach 20,000 by year's end.
   Another dispatch from the agency said five citizens of Romania,
an East-bloc country that has rejected liberal reforms, made it into
Hungary after one was seriously wounded in a struggle with a
Romanian border guard. It said they crossed the frontier early
Sunday.
   The last time so many East European refugees fled over the
Hungarian border to Austria was in 1956, when Soviet troops and
tanks crushed the anti-Stalinist Hungarian uprising.
   West Germany automatically grants citizenship to East Germans.
The current tide has prompted it to urge the government in East
Berlin to adopt political and economic reform being promoted by the
Soviet Union.
   Many of the East Germans arriving in the West say they left
because of the regime's resistance to change.
   Officials said 350-450 East Germans entered Austria from Hungary
on Monday.
   On Saturday, hundreds pressed through a border gate that normally
is closed but was opened for a Hungarian-Austrian event to promote
European unity.
   Dieter Graf von Bruehl, the West German ambassador, told Austrian
television Sunday his embassy took in 660 East Germans on Saturday
and another 160 on Sunday. He said the average had been 50 to 80 a
day for three weeks.
   Officials say the true numbers are higher because many refugees
travel on with friends or relatives from West Germany without
stopping at the embassy.
   Manfred Kersten, spokesman for the West German resettlement camp
in Giessen, where most refugees go, said 1,400 East Germans arrived
over the weekend.
   More than 65,000 East Germans emigrated or escaped to West
Germany in 1989. Kersten said 10,000 had arrived since the beginning
of August.
   The Red Cross emergency facility is at Moerbisch on Lake Neusiedl
near Austria's border with Hungary. It provides East Germans with
food and medical attention.
   Heinrich Unger, a Red Cross official, appealed on state radio
Monday for contributions of clothing, shoes and towels.
   Witnesses at the border said most Hungarian and Austrian border
officials appeared sympathetic to the refugees. The Hungarian daily
Magyar Hirlap quoted a witness as saying an East German woman
dropped her baby and a Hungarian guard helped her pickup the child,
then waved her across the frontier.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890821-0104 </DOCNO>
