<FIRST>r w AM-Dingell-Poland     08-21 0373</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dingell-Poland,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Openings Seen For U.S. Businesses In Poland</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN FLESHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Poland offers enormous investment opportunities
for U.S. businesses if it can survive its political crisis and
achieve stability, Rep. John Dingell, just returned from a trip to
Eastern Europe, said Monday.
   ``They really want American investment, and they'll take almost
anything that will help them,'' said Dingell, D-Mich. The chairman
of the House Energy and Commerce Committee returned Saturday from a
nearly two-week trip to Eastern Europe with 11 other members of the
panel.
   The congressmen spent four days in Poland and met with leaders of
the Solidarity labor movement, including Lech Walesa.
   The Polish leaders showed more enthusiasm for U.S. investment,
joint ventures, and technical assistance than for loans, Dingell
said. But American businesses are hesitant to join such ventures
while the political situation is unsettled, he said.
   ``American business has to know there is stability,'' he said.
``They've got to know their money will be protected while it's
there, that it won't be ... subject to chaos.''
   Dingell said the banking, food processing and transportation
industries could tap vast markets in Poland. ``There's a crying need
for consumer goods all over the Iron Curtain,'' he said.
   Poles do not trust their country's banking system but would be
eager to invest in U.S. banks, Dingell said. ``Walesa thinks there's
$5 billion stuffed in mattresses and pillows all over Poland that
people would ... put in the banks if they had any confidence in
them,'' he said.
   The U.S. is sending $119 in direct aid to Poland while pushing a
multinational effort to provide Poland with nearly $1 billion in
extra cash this year by pressuring Western banks and governments to
reschedule the $39 billion debt it owes.
   Dingell said that help is fine so far, but should be expanded as
Poland's new government shows it is ready to implement economic
reforms, he said.
   ``This country has got to recognize that that our economic,
political, diplomatic and military self-interests ride on the
success of the Poles,'' he said. ``If they succeed in what they're
doing, we'll have moved more toward world peace and ... economic
progress than anyone can imagine.''
</TEXT>
