<FILEID>AP-NR-08-21-89 1734EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Pope     08-21 0390</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pope,0399</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pope Ends Visit to Spain With Blessing for a Border-Free Europe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY BETH SHERIDAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COVADONGA, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II on Monday gave his
blessing to a border-free Europe as he ended a three-day visit to
Spain.
   After a 30-minute meeting with Prime Minister Felipe Gonzalez at
the Asturias airport the pontiff left for Rome and arrived back in
Italy shortly befsore 9 p.m. (3 p.m. EDT).
   Gonzalez told reporters after the meeting that he had discussed
with John Paul the conflict in Lebanon and the political situation
in Eastern Europe, especially the pope's native Poland.
   The pope on several occasions during his visit appealed for a
cease-fire in Lebanon where more than 775 people have been killed
since fighting broke out in March between Syrian troops and their
allies and Lebanese Christian forces.
   ``I confidently place the project of a Europe without borders at
the feet of the Virgin of Covadonga and pray that such an entity
will not turn its back on its Christian roots,'' John Paul said
during a Mass at the shrine of Covadonga high in the Picos de Europa.
   Covadonga, in the mountains near Spain's northern Atlantic coast,
is the site of a victory in 722 of Christian forces over a Moslem
army. The province of Asturias in which the shrine is located is
considered the birthplace of the Spanish nation and monarchy.
   John Paul spoke of European unity several times after arriving in
the medieval pilgrimage city of Santiago de Compostela Saturday. He
spoke of the role of Christianity in breaking down borders and
bringing together people of different languages and cultures.
   But his principal theme was the need to reject materialism and
return to spiritual values, particularly on the part of young people.
   At an outdoor mass in Oviedo Sunday, the pope said man's
increasing technical domination over the material world has left him
``disoriented by the great technical advances that don't permit the
flowering of the essential principles of dignity and solidarity.''
   Felipe, the 21-year-old heir to the Spanish throne, also known as
the Prince of Asturias, accompanied the 69-year-old pontiff during
his stay in Covadonga. It was the pope's third visit to Spain in
seven years.
   King Juan Carlos and Queen Sofia greeted the pope on his arrival
in Santiago de Compostela.
</TEXT>
