<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890821-0108 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-21-89 1926EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Sununu-Seabrook     08-21 0257</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sununu-Seabrook,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Aide Defends Seabrook Payments</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   White House chief of staff John
Sununu on Monday defended payments made to New Hampshire officials
by the owners of the Seabrook nuclear plant while he was governor,
calling it a ``Catch-22'' situation.
   Sununu said the payments were made under a 1981 law that ``was
not the best-crafted piece of legislation.'' Under it, Seabrook's
owner, Public Service Co. of New Hampshire, was charged by the state
for work done on emergency evacuation plans for the area around the
reactor.
   The presidential aide, briefing reporters covering vacationing
President Bush, was asked about news stories that several prominent
Republicans, including his former deputy chief of staff, David
Carney, had been paid by Seabrook's owner.
   ``The fund was created under a law passed in 1981, two years
before I became governor,'' Sununu said. ``The law was a law that
carried a Catch-22 in it.''
   It was a reference to the title of Joseph Heller's 1961 book
about World War II. The phrase the book popularized refers to a
regulation or law containing a contradictory or nonsensical
``catch.''
   ``The Catch-22 is, if the state did work (on) reviewing the plan,
without those funds being charged, the state would be accused of
supporting financially activities that were to the benefit of the
company,'' Sununu said.
   Sununu, who became Bush's chief of staff in January after three
terms as governor, said he and Carney ``worked very hard to make
sure that we met both the letter and spirit of that law.''
</TEXT>
