<FILEID>AP-NR-08-21-89 1941EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     08-21 0560</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0578</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALPINE, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sandy Tribble and Dorothy Brinckerhoff are
students of the force of habit.
   By now, they've seen it often enough. A car pulls onto the dusty
gravel parking strip in front of their country store in Alpine, a
crossroads about 25 miles northwest of Eugene. The driver gets out
and shoves a coin in the lone parking meter out front.
   ``It makes you wonder,'' Brinckerhoff says. ``Some of them never
stop to notice that it's the only meter there. And they never even
ask why there would be a meter in a place like Alpine.''
   OK, why? After all, Alpine is an unincorporated town unsullied by
sidewalks, a City Hall, a police force or parking enforcers.
   The idea surfaced a couple of years ago when Tribble and
Brinckerhoff were at a meeting of the Alpine Community Center, the
name given to a group that raises money to maintain the town's park.
   At the meeting, discussion turned to the recently erected stop
signal at Alpine's downtown intersection. That was progress, it was
agreed, but maybe more was needed. Someone suggested a parking meter.
   ``It started out as a joke, but we kept talking about it,''
Tribble says. ``We said we could take the money from a meter and use
it to maintain the park.''
   Someone called the town of Corvallis, which had a meter to spare.
And so the parking meter came to Alpine, where it sat for a couple
years in a back room of the store. It was erected out front a few
weeks ago.
   ``Most local people think it's a good joke and then they put
money in it anyhow,'' Brinckerhoff said. ``But a few people have
been kind of indignant. `A parking meter in Alpine?' They act like
they moved to Alpine to get away from things like that.''
   Ironically, the owners of the meter have no way to get to the
money. Corvallis officials wouldn't part with the special key that
opens the meter because they still have similar models on the
streets of their city.
   But meter technician Ray Baylor has volunteered to stop by every
couple of months to empty the till.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Clouds over southern Florida blocked the view of
last week's total lunar eclipse, but maternity wards from Miami to
West Palm Beach reported a dramatic rise in births during and after
the celestial phenomenon.
   At Miami's Jackson Memorial Hospital, where an average of 40
births are handled a day, 61 babies were born early Thursday within
hours of the eclipse. And 17 babies _ about twice the daily average
_ were born at Plantation General Hospital during the same period.
   At Mount Sinai Medical Center in Miami Beach, nine mothers gave
birth shortly after the moon slid through the Earth's shadow. That
was triple the normal daily average.
   Births nearly doubled at South Miami Hospital, and St. Mary's
Hospital in West Palm Beach reported about seven more than usual.
   ``They always say the tide has something to do with births,''
said Pat Jamason, a nursing supervisor at St. Mary's. ``So maybe the
eclipse is responsible.''
   Some doctors were skeptical.
   ``I don't know where these things get started,'' said Dr. Debra
Kenwood, a South Miami gynecologist and obstetrician. ``As far as I
know, there's no scientific proof to support it.''
</TEXT>
