<FIRST>r w AM-Obit-Bolger     08-21 0311</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Bolger,290</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Postmaster General Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Postmaster General William F. Bolger
died Monday, the Postal Service announced. He was 66.
   Bolger died at a hospital in suburban Arlington, Va., where he
had been transferred after suffering a heart attack on July 28 in
Omaha, Neb.
   The first career postal employee to lead the service and the 65th
in a line that started with Benjamin Franklin, Bolger served as
postmaster general from 1978 to 1984. The service achieved its first
surplus in 34 years during Bolger's tenure.
   Bolger started as a clerk in the Washington headquarters in 1941
and rose to managerial positions in the New England region before
becoming deputy postmaster general and then postmaster general.
   ``He was a leader of great stature and boundless energy who
brought a spirit of innovation and vision to this organization
during critical times of change and challenge,'' said Postmaster
General Anthony M. Frank.
   Always checking on detail, Bolger was known to pick up a stack of
complaint forms and call Post Office customers himself to straighten
out their problems.
   Bolger struggled with electronic mail, touchy labor-management
relations and a growing volume that led him to push the nine-digit
ZIP code. ``Nobody like numbers,'' he said about the nine digits.
``I don't. But we have a choice. We can do without them and have our
mail service more expensive.''
   And, he admitted, ``We don't handle mail as well as we did 40
years ago.''
   Jim Syers, president of the National Association of Postmasters,
said, ``History may record him as the outstanding postmaster general
of all time.''
   After leaving the service, Bolger founded T-COM Systems Inc., a
business mailing system. Among other directorships and trusteeships,
he served as president of the Air Transport Association of America.
   Bolger is survived by his widow, Marjorie, and two daughters.
Funeral services were not announced.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
