<FIRST>u i AM-Czechoslovakia 1stLd-Writethru a0564 08-21 0722</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czechoslovakia, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0564,0746</SECOND>
<HEAD>Czechoslovak Police Detain Dozens at Anniversary Protest</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS through to ADD new details, protest in Poland, Quotes
from State Department. No Pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of riot police used
truncheons to disperse more than 4,000 protesters who defied a ban
on demonstrations Monday marking the 21st anniversary of the
Soviet-led invasion of Czechoslovakia.
   Police detained dozens of demonstrators who marched through the
center of old Prague calling for democratic reform and the
withdrawal of Soviet troops.
   The two-hour rally started when a group of Hungarian youths told
a cheering crowd they disagreed with Hungary's participation in the
1968 invasion and then unfurled a banner reading, ``The Bolsheviks
came with tanks, we come with flowers.''
   Many protesters were beaten by police but it was not known
whether any were seriously injured. It could not be determined how
many demonstrators were detained.
   Austrian television said police cut one of its camera cables and
then felled a crew member with what the correspondent described as a
``karate stroke.''
   The rally was smaller than a demonstration by 10,000 people on
Aug. 21 last year, but occurred despite warnings by Czechoslovak
authorities that force would be used to break up any protests.
   Fearing bloodshed, activists had warned against street protests.
   The official CTK news agency said 1,500 people took part in a
``provocation'' organized ``by hostile centers from abroad.'' It
said those detained would be ``punished according to Czechoslovak
law.''
   Police sirens sounded through the area for hours after the
protest began as vanloads of helmeted riot police and regular
uniformed forces moved in to downtown Prague.
   The protest began at about 5 p.m. _ the hour appointed by six
dissident groups for a two-minute silent protest against the
invasion.
   The crowd gathered around the Hungarian activists at the lower
end of Wenceslas Square _ a long boulevard in central Prague _ and
shouted mockingly ``Gorbachev sees this!'' as riot police moved in.
They referred to Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   ``You must know that Hungarian youth never agreed with the
invasion!'' Hungarian activist Gyorgy Kereniy shouted to applause
and chants of ``Long live Hungary!''
   Plainclothes police barged through the crowd and detained Kereniy.
   As they moved from Wenceslas Square to Old Town Square and the
federal government headquarters, where they were turned back by
police, the demonstrators chanted ``Long live Poland!'' and
``Russians go home!''
   They also shouted support for Alexander Dubcek, the leader of the
``Prague Spring'' reforms crushed by the 1968 invasion.
   Dubcek, who was ousted as party leader in April 1969 and expelled
from communist ranks in 1970, has called for fresh reforms and
rehabilitation of the half a million communists expelled after 1968.
   Prague's Communist leadership has resisted mounting pressure at
home and from East bloc reformers for the political changes under
way in Poland, Hungary and the Soviet Union.
   Authorities had warned against demonstrations this year,
harassing and detaining leading dissidents and mounting a tight
security operation for the past two days in Prague.
   Most well-known dissidents were warned weeks in advance to stay
out of Prague and other big cities for the anniversary. Two who
stayed in the capital, Charter 77 spokeswoman Dana Nemcova and her
son, David, were placed under house arrest on Sunday.
   Activists recommended Czechoslovaks sign a petition for
democratic reforms instead of holding street protests, fearing
police would shoot demonstrators.
   On Monday, the state-run media ran no commentary of their own on
the invasion anniversary, limiting their reporting to comments from
other Warsaw Pact states that participated in the intervention.
   A Polish parliamentary resolution said the invasion was a
violation of international law, and on Monday, lawmakers from
Poland's Solidarity movement led a rally in the border town of
Cieszyn.
   ``Never Again Brotherly Help,'' read a banner carried by
protesters, according to Poland's state PAP news agency.
   Leaders of Hungary's Communist Party said last week they did not
agree with the invasion. On Sunday, Hungarian Premier Miklos Nemeth
said his country has initiated steps within the Warsaw Pact to make
military interference impossible in the future.
   In Washington, the State Department issued a statement saying,
``It is our hope that ... Czechoslovakia will recall the events of
1968 and ... will display a greater tolerance for freedom of
expression and assembly.''
</TEXT>
