<FIRST>u w AM-Morgan-Custody     08-21 0370</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Morgan-Custody,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Keeps Morgan in Jail</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The full District of Columbia Court of Appeals
on Monday overturned an appeals panel's order to end the nearly
two-year jailing of Elizabeth Morgan for refusing to reveal the
whereabouts of her daughter in a bitter custody dispute.
   The full court, in an order issued shortly after a three-judge
panel ruled 2-1 that Morgan should be released, called for a new
hearing on her appeal of the civil contempt of court citation that
has kept her at the city jail.
   The court did not explain its one-page order.
   The prominent plastic surgeon has been jailed since Aug. 28, 1987
by Superior Court Judge Herbert Dixon for failing to produce her
daughter Hilary for visits with Eric Foretich, her former husband
and the girl's father.
   Ms. Morgan said she hid the girl because Foretich had sexually
abused the child. Foretich, who is also a doctor, denies the charges.
   Hilary, whose seventh birthday was Monday, remains hidden.
   In Monday's majority opinion by the three-judge panel, Judge John
M. Ferren said Dixon's attempt to coerce Ms. Morgan into divulging
the girl's whereabouts had failed.
   ``Irrespective of context, once the civil contempt power is shown
to have failed in its intended purpose ... the court must release
the contemnor from jail,'' Ferren wrote.
   Elaine Mittleman, attorney for Foretich, said new arguments have
been scheduled for Sept. 20.
   Earlier Monday, Foretich was joined on the Capitol steps by about
a dozen relatives and supporters to mark his daughter's seventh
birthday.
   Foretich said he decided to hold the ceremony because he is upset
about legislation pending in Congress which would lead to Morgan's
release even if she doesn't bring the child out of hiding.
   Meanwhile, Foretich has filed a $220 million suit against the CBS
television network and six other defendants in connection with the
program ``People Magazine on TV'' broadcast Aug. 16, which carried a
story about the custody dispute.
   The suit filed Friday claims Foretich was defamed, subjected to
emotional distress, suffered an invasion of privacy and was
portrayed in a false light, according to Ms. Mittleman.
   CBS spokeswoman Anne Morforgen said she had not seen the suit and
could not comment.
</TEXT>
