<FILEID>AP-NR-08-21-89 1954EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Iran-Cabinet     08-21 0549</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iran-Cabinet,0568</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cabinet Candidates Announce New Policies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANWAR FARUQI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Several candidates for the Cabinet of
Iranian President Hashemi Rafsanjani announced new policies Monday
while waiting for Parliament to confirm their appointments.
   Iran's official Islamic Republic News Agency said Iranian
newspapers had published the programs of 14 of the 22 ministerial
candidates.
   Confirmation debate is to begin Saturday in the 270-member
Majlis, Iran's parliament.
   Rafsanjani appointed a French-trained former justice minister,
Hassan Habibi, on Monday as his first vice president. He chose a
former deputy prime minister, Ataollah Mohajerani, as vice president
for judicial and parliamentary affairs.
   Habibi is among a small group of Western-oriented officials
selected by Rafsanjani to help rebuild the economy and restore ties
with the West.
   The new president is trying to promote moderate, educated
technocrats and remove hard-liners from key positions where they
could block his policies.
   Among the hard-liners are Interior Minister Ali Akbar Mohtashemi,
Prime Minister Hussein Musavi and Intelligence Minister Mohammad
Rey-Shahri, none of whom is included in the Rafsanjani Cabinet. The
job of prime minister was abolished in the new constitution, which
created a strong presidency.
   Rey-Shari, who declined to serve in Rafsanjani's government, was
named prosecutor-general Monday by the head of the judiciary,
Mohammad Ali Yazdi. He selected Morteza Moqtadai as chief justice.
   Mohsen Nourbakhsh, who was educated in the United States and has
been chosen as economy minister, wants a ``complete review'' of
Iran's foreign exchange policies, the official news agency reported.
   It said Nourbakhsh, a former Central Bank governor, would
increase exports other than oil, which now provide only 10 percent
of foreign currency earnings, in order to reduce a chronic trade
deficit.
   Imports have contributed to soaring inflation, which has made
Tehran one of the world's most expensive cities.
   While at the bank, Nourbakhsh held inflation to a 20 percent
annual rate by tight controls on the money supply. He resigned
because of opposition to his plans, however, and inflation quickly
rose to 50 percent.
   Nourbakhsh also called for a stable tax policy that would
encourage medium and long-term investment in industry, IRNA said.
   Abdolhassan Vahaji, Rafsanjani's choice as commerce minister,
hinted at a larger role for the private sector. The agency quoted
him as saying he planned to revive ``traditional'' supply networks
and ``hand over the unnecessary part of the government's
responsibilities in distribution affairs to other sectors.''
   Vahaji also promised to stabilize government-subsidized prices of
basic goods.
   Virtually all trade has been conducted by the government,
creating a bureaucracy with little regard for market factors.
   Another of Rafsanjani's priorities is to convince skilled
Iranians driven abroad by the Islamic revolution's excesses to
return home.
   Mostafa Moin, candidate for higher education minister, said he
would attract ``prominent world scholars'' to Iranian universities
by offering ``material and spiritual'' incentives, IRNA said.
   It quoted Moin as saying he would build more universities and
improve standards.
   Standards at Iranian universities have fallen in the 10 years of
the fundamentalist Islamic regime. Entrance requirements reflect
ideology as much as academic achievement.
   Iraj Fazel, proposed minister of health, wants to improve medical
training by bring top-quality academics back from exile, the agency
said. Fazel also said he would revive the pharmaceutical industry by
rebuilding factories and encouraging private investment in new ones.
</TEXT>
