<FIRST>r w AM-OAS-Colombia     08-21 0382</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-OAS-Colombia,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>OAS Declares Solidarity with Colombia</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bush, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARY MOLEON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Organization of American States on Monday
declared its ``solidarity with Colombia in the face of a criminal
aggression'' by drug lords.
   The OAS Permanent Council acted three days after the
assassination Friday of Luis Carlos Galan, a leading candidate in
next year's presidential election in Colombia.
   Latin American diplomats said they regarded Colombia's request
for a special meeting of the OAS as aimed at pressuring the United
States for more action to crack down on drug use.
   It also was seen as intended to neutralize any potential
criticism for the declared ``state of siege'' under which the
Colombian government has rounded up 10,000 people suspected to have
links with the drug cartels.
   Leopoldo Villar Borda, the Colombian representative to the OAS,
called the situation ``extremely serious,'' but ruled out any
request for U.S. troops to help in countering the drug cartels
accused of engineering Galan's killing.
   The Colombians have long held that if the U.S. market were to dry
up, the cartels' production and influence would decline.
   The resolution appoved by the OAS pointedly reversed the usual
word order and condemned ``the use, traffic and production'' of
drugs, stressing the need for the United States to reduce
consumption.
   Current U.S. estimates indicate Colombia produces some 85 per
cent of the $110 billion in drugs used in the United States a year.
   Colombian President Virgilio Barco Vargas said in Bogota that
``whoever consumes drugs should remember that he is helping those
who assasinated Galan.''
   In his speech before the OAS, Villar Borda said of Colombia that
``no country has paid so high a price for the traffic created by an
insatiable demand for drugs.''
   Villar Borda reacted with incredulity when asked by reporters if
Colombia was prepared to ask for U.S. troops to crack down the drugs
cartels. He bushed aside the question with a firm no.
   John Sununu, White House chief of staff, said that there has been
no specific request by Colombia for the use of U.S. troops.
   The issue was raised Sunday by Attorney General Dick Thornburgh
when he said the United States should consider sending troops, if
requested, to help Colombia, in its fight against the drugs cartels.
</TEXT>
