<FIRST>u i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0571 08-21 0665</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0571,0684</SECOND>
<HEAD>Army Says It Wasn't Involved in Death of Palestinian-American</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout to update with new deaths, Arab editor detained,
comment from human rights group; Edits to trim; no pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The army said Monday its soldiers were not
involved in the death of a 14-year-old Palestinian-American whose
body was found last week near Ramallah in the occupied West Bank.
   The family of Amjad Jibril Tawil claimed he was in army custody
after a stone-throwing incident Wednesday and that his body was
found Friday with bruises, burn marks and a fatal bullet wound in
the chest.
   Bethlehem Mayor Elias Freij said he had filed a complaint with
Israeli authorities about the death of another young Palestinian,
allegedly was shot and killed Saturday in the biblical town by
security forces masquerading as tourists.
   The army declined comment on Freij's allegations.
   Arab reports said three Palestinians were killed Monday in
confrontations with soldiers.
   Fourteen Palestinians were shot and wounded in stone-throwing
clashes with Israeli troops during a general strike called by
leaders of the 20-month-old uprising in the occupied West Bank and
Gaza Strip, hospital officials said.
   The army confirmed two deaths and four wounded.
   The deaths raised to at least 543 the number of Palestinians
killed by Israeli troops and settlers since the uprising against
Israeli rule began in December 1987. Ninety-seven Palestinians have
been killed by fellow Arabs, and 38 Israelis have died.
   Based on a reconstruction of events by an investigator and a
government autopsy of the Tawil case, the army said, ``the
conclusion is that the death of the boy was not caused by the
Israeli security forces.''
   The statement did not say who was suspected of killing Tawil, who
was born in Denver, Colo., nor did it give details of the autopsy.
It said police were investigating.
   The family filed a petition Monday with the Supreme Court
demanding the Tawil's body not be reburied until an independent
autopsy could be performed. The body was exhumed over the weekend
for the Israeli autopsy.
   Lawyer Leah Tsemel, who filed the petition, said the action was
taken after the government reneged on an earlier pledge to allow an
independent pathologist to observe the government's autopsy.
   Ms. Tsemel said she also asked the court to order the army to
lift its blockade of the Tawil home. Only family members and
representatives of the U.S. consulate have been allowed in the
house, she said.
   His family reported the boy missing Thursday. They said he went
to pray at a Ramallah mosque Wednesday and a stone-throwing incident
developed after the prayer service.
   Relatives said they were told by other Palestinians that he was
in army custody, but the army denied he ever was held.
   The human rights group Al-Haq, based in Ramallah, issued a
statement saying there was the ``possibility of official involvement
in the youth's death'' and asked for an independent investigation
into the youth's death.
   A military source, who insisted on anonymity, said the fatal
bullet apparently was from a pistol fired at close range.
   In the West Bank, two Palestinian teen-agers were shot to death
in a stone-throwing clash with Israeli troops in the village of El
Ram near Jerusalem, hospital officials said.
   Doctors at Mukaseed Hospital in Arab East Jerusalem identified
them as Wadia Mahmoud Salah, 15, and Hussein Adnan Herbawi, 14.
   In Tekua, near Bethlehem, an 18-year-old Palestinian was fatally
shot in the chest, Arab reports said. Israel radio said he was fired
on from a passing car, but Arab witnesses later said the youth was
shot after a clash with troops. They identified him as Sani Mahmoud
Atwa Sabbah.
   In Jerusalem, the managing editor of the Arabic-language
newspaper al-Fajr newspaper was arrested and placed under a
six-month administrative detention, said Israel television and
reporters from the newspaper.
   They said it was the third time Hatem Abdel Qader was arrested
and jailed without charges since the uprising began.
</TEXT>
