<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon 2ndLd-Writethru a0578 08-21 0847</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0578,0872</SECOND>
<HEAD>Christian Commander Offers Talks on Ending War</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with quotes, Syrian, Saudi statements.
Edits to trim. No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RODEINA KENAAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gen. Michel Aoun proposed peace talks
Monday, but a Syrian-backed Moslem militia rejected the offer to
negotiate an end to the 5-month-old artillery duel with Aoun's
Christian forces that has killed hundreds.
   There was no response to Aoun's proposal from the Syrian forces,
in Lebanon since 1976.
   ``I am ready any time to discuss Lebanon's future at a
round-table with leaders of the other side,'' Aoun said in an
interview published by the Paris-based Arabic magazine Koll el-Arab.
His press office confirmed the quote was accurate.
   Aoun made no mention of his previous condition that
Christian-Moslem negotiations on political reforms could not be held
until Syria pulled its 40,000 troops out of Lebanon.
   Druse leader Walid Jumblatt's Progressive Socialist Party
dismissed the offer as ``a trick to allow Aoun a breathing spell to
rearm and remartial his forces.''
   In a statement, Jumblatt said Aoun would never be accepted as a
negotiator, asserting that a Moslem-Christian dialogue ``can begin
only after the butcher is overthrown and brought to trial for his
crimes.''
   The statement also condemned the arrival of French warships off
Lebanon, and said President Francois Mitterrand's government wants
``to kindle a new Crusaders' war in Lebanon.'' France ruled the
country from the end of World War I till independence in 1943.
   Syrian Vice President Abdul-Halim Khaddam reiterated his
country's determination ``to take all measures to guarantee the
unity'' of Lebanon but made no reference to Aoun's offer.
   Khaddam told a meeting of Syria's ruling Baath Socialist
Party,``National entente is the safe way to end the Lebanese
crisis.... Syria will assist all patriotic Lebanese ... to estabish
a democratic system in which all Lebanese have equal rights and
duties.''
   He did not criticize France by name but spoke of Western
involvement that had ``negative repercussions of further
complicating the Lebanese crisis.''
   Saudi Arabia's King Fahd said Monday that Lebanon's Christian and
Moslem leaders must start cooperating if a settlement is to be
reached in Lebanon's civil war that began in 1975. Syria sent its
troops into Lebanon, originally as a peacekeeping force, in 1976.
   Fahd's statement ended speculation that he was about to resume a
mediation bid he undertook along with King Hassan II of Morocco and
President Chadlin Bendjedid of Algeria. The Arab League negotiators
announced on Aug. 1 their efforts were deadlocked over Syria's
refusal to withdraw its troops.
   Aoun calls the Syrians an occupation army and has declared a
``war of liberation'' against them.
   All radio stations broadcast Aoun's offer as his 20,000 soldiers
exchanged sporadic artillery and tank fire with the Syrians across
divided Beirut and in the hills above the capital.
   Police reported one person killed and 14 wounded.
   By police count, 785 people have been killed and 2,140 wounded
since the latest fighting began March 8 between Aoun's soldiers and
an alliance of Syrians and Moslem militias. Most casualties have
been civilians.
   The artillery and rocket fire has abated since the U.N. Security
Council passed a resolution on Aug. 15 calling for a cease-fire.
   Many stores were open Monday and traffic was heavy. The money
market reopened and banks were operating for the first time in 10
days.
   By early afternoon, however, stores closed their shutters and
long convoys of automobiles headed back to south Lebanon.
   Only 150,000-200,000 of Beirut's 1.5 million people are still
living in the city.
   Police said the Syrians hit the Christian-held coast around
Byblos with 100 shells and rockets overnight to turn back three
ships carrying food to the 310-square-mile Christian enclave.
   Aoun's forces have been receiving weapons from Iraq, Syria's main
Arab foe.
   In Sidon, south Lebanon, a freighter that had smuggled food to
the Christians was blown up by three bombs at dawn Monday, police
said. Three other freighters were wrecked by similar explosions in
June.
   Beirut media said Monday the French warships were intended to
break the Syrian siege of the Christian heartland.
   An-Nahar, an independent newspaper, quoted sources as saying the
flotilla would ensure that arms and fuel supplies reached the
Christians.
   Last week, the French sent an aircraft carrier, a destroyer, a
hospital ship and a fuel tanker, ostensibly to help evacuate French
citizens if necessary. About 7,000 French nationals live in Lebanon.
   The An-Nahar report quoted a ``high-ranking source'' as saying:
``France is just giving a humanitarian excuse for its upcoming
military intervention.''
   Rene Ala, the French ambassador, said Monday he assured acting
Prime Minister Salim Hoss that France is not contemplating
intervention. Hoss heads a Moslem Cabinet that competes with a
Christian government led by Aoun.
   Hezbollah, the pro-Iranian organization believed to sponsor
groups holding Western hostages in Lebanon, threatened anti-French
suicide bombings if France takes military action.
   Sixteen foreigners are missing in Lebanon, including eight
Americans. The hostage held longest is Terry A. Anderson, chief
Middle East correspondent of The Associated Press, who was kidnapped
March 16, 1985.
</TEXT>
