<FIRST>r a AM-PhoneStrike     08-21 0532</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Phone Strike,0549</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pacific Telesis Settlement Raises Hope in Other Phone Strikes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The settlement of a telephone strike in California and Nevada
appeared to give new impetus Monday to efforts to resolve similar
strikes elsewhere around the country.
   A Communications Workers of America union leader in Indianapolis
said he was optimistic that the Pacific Telesis agreement would lead
to a settlement at Ameritech, which serves five midwestern states.
   There also were hopeful signs in Philadelphia, where negotiations
continued between workers and management at Bell Atlantic, which
covers the mid-Atlantic states and Washington, D.C.
   Mary O'Hara, an adminstrative assistant for the CWA, said union
officials ``have still got hope'' of meeting a deadline to resolve
the issues with Bell Atlantic by midnight Tuesday. Both sides agreed
to the deadline.
   More vandalism was reported in the strike against NYNEX, which
serves New York and the Northeast. A judge in Albany, N.Y., issued a
temporary injunction ordering strikers not to engage in mass
striking or interfere with operations at New York Telephone, a NYNEX
subsidiary.
   The three continuing strikes involve more than 150,000 workers.
About 42,000 strikers returned to work Monday at San Francisco-based
Pacific Telesis after negotiators reached agreement over the weekend.
   The Pacific Telesis agreement will raise salaries by 11 percent
over three years, according to Jessie Wilson, president of CWA Local
9415.
   Some tension was reported Monday as strikers returned to work
alongside those who had remained on the job during the two-week
strike.
   ``They're not talking to us,'' one directory assistance operator
said of the returning strikers. ``I'm a very mild-mannered person. I
just ignore them.''
   In Indiana, CWA spokesman L. Keith Dooley said he thought the
Pacific Telesis contract could serve as a guide for negotiations
betwee the union and Ameritech.
   ``I haven't seen their package yet, but I think that could have
some affect on what goes on here,'' Dooley said.
   Both CWA and Ameritech officials said they were willing to go
back to the bargaining table, although neither side expressed a
willingness to pick up the telephone.
   ``If we get a call from the company we're certainly available,''
said Dooley.
   ``We are ready, willing and eager if the call comes,'' said Estel
Gibson, a spokesman for Indiana Bell, one of Ameritech's
subsidiaries.
   In Albany, Judge Lawrence Kahn issued a restraining order that
instructs the CWA to have no more than 10 pickets at an entrance to
a New York Telephone building. In addition, pickets must remain at
least 15 feet away from company vehicles and employees and cannot
vandalize company equipment, he said.
   But striking union members said they had been advised by their
attorneys that Kahn had no jurisdiction over the matter and that
they could carry on with their picketing as usual.
   ``Essentially it means nothing,'' said William Sullivan,
president of Local 1126 in Utica, N.Y.
   There were at least 13 incidents of vandalism to New York
Telephone lines last weekend, causing phone service outages to more
than 4,000 customers, company spokesman Peter Muller said.
   Muller said three severed telephone lines were discovered Monday,
bringing to 125 the number of lines cut around New York state in the
past two weeks.
</TEXT>
