<FIRST>u i AM-Colombia-Cartel     08-21 0461</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombia-Cartel,0473</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drug Cartel's Leaders Are Rich and Ruthless</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Colombia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN NOBLET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The rich and ruthless leaders of the
cocaine underworld often have shown they will go to any lengths to
protect their billion-dollar business.
   Last week's killing of Sen. Luis Carlos Galan, the top
presidential candidate and acknowledged leader of a new political
generation, was the latest example.
   The government's reaction was vigorous, but again illustrated its
inability to catch the drug lords. Soldiers and police raided their
estates and arrested thousands of employees and underlings but did
not find the bosses.
   Their names are well known: Pablo Escobar, Gonzalo Rodriguez
Gacha and the brothers Jorge, Fabio and Juan David Ochoa Vasquez,
said to lead the Medellin cartel based in the northwestern
industrial city.
   Escobar is on Fortune Magazine's list of the world's 20 richest
men, said to have more than $3 billion.
   In Cali, a southwestern city, a rival cartel operates under the
leadership of Gilberto Rodriguez Orejuela and Hernan Santacruz
Londono, according to authorities.
   The two groups are reported to be warring over the New York City
drug market. About 200 members of the rival cartels have been
reported killed in 18 months and scores of properties in Medellin
and Cali have been bombed or shot up.
   Profits from New York drug sales are estimated at $35 billion a
year, said Gen. Jaime Ruiz Barrera, who spent two years as the
military commander of Medellin.
   Ruiz Barrera recently was sent to Washington as military attache
in an effort to protect him from killers hired by the cocaine
barons. Assassinations attributed to them have occurred as far away
as Baton Rouge, La., and Hungary.
   Colombian drug cartels are said to have financed the training of
2,000 hired assassins in association with extreme right-wing groups.
The assassins are blamed for the deaths of Galan and many before him.
   Cartel killers have terrorized the courts. They are blamed for
the deaths of a justice minister, an attorney general and 220 judges
and judicial aides since 1981, said Judge Antonio Morales, president
of the national judicial employees' association.
   Such bloody intimidation has kept the cartel bosses out of jail
and shielded them from what they fear most _ extradition to the
United States.
   Only one top dealer, Madellin cartel partner Carlos Lehder, has
been captured and shipped to the United States. Handed over in 1987,
he was convicted by a Florida court last year and sentenced to life
in prison.
   Military and police forces occasionally deliver a painful blow to
the dealers, destroying expensive laboratories and seizing fortunes
in drugs. So far this year, authorities have confiscated 26 tons of
cocaine, but that is considered only a small part of total
production.

</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890821-0124 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-21-89 2018EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-CoupleAdrift     08-21 0519</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Couple Adrift,0535</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sharks Circled Raft of Americans Adrift 66 Days</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUAN MALTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Florida man said Monday that he and
his wife who survived 66 days adrift on a life raft menaced by
sharks tried to signal more than three dozen passing ships before
one spotted them.
   William Butler, 59, said he and his wife Simone, 56, of Miami,
survived on raw fish and purified water until a Costa Rican coast
guard boat picked them up in the Pacific Ocean, 12 miles off the
coast, on Saturday.
   ``We were surrounded by sharks practically all the time and we
felt a lot of panic but thanks to God they never attacked us,''
Butler, an electrical engineer, said by telephone from a hospital in
the port of Golfito.
   He said he and his wife set sail from Panama on May 24 for Hawaii
in their 40-foot sloop, the Siboney. They had been drifting east in
the life raft since June 15, when whales attacked their boat about
1,200 miles southwest of Costa Rica, he said.
   ``In no more than 15 minutes, our boat was destroyed,'' he said.
``But God, always present in our prayers, helped us because we
carried a life raft and we got in it immediately, taking all the
things we would need.''
   They had eight cans of food, some cookies, a water purifier and a
fishing hook, Butler said.
   ``After 20 days adrift all the food was gone,'' he said. ``Then
we started to fish. Thanks to God we always had food and with the
filter we drank fresh water.''
   Before they got in the raft, he said, he sent three distress
messages over the radio but no one heard them.
   ``At least 40 ships passed and didn't see us and every night we
thought we could die,'' he said. ``But the next day, in the morning,
we prayed again.''
   Egbert Vallecillo, a U.S. Coast Guard spokesman, said Butler told
him by telephone that the sharks punctured the raft several times
and the couple sealed the holes with a repair kit.
   Vallecillo said he spoke to Butler from the U.S. Coast Guard's
Pacific Command headquarters in Alameda, 10 miles east of San
Francisco.
   In San Jose, Butler said he and his wife were praying again
Saturday afternoon when they saw the Costa Rican coast guard boat.
   ``But they saw us first,'' he said.
   They were picked up 20 miles off Punta Burica, at the border with
Panama and near Golfito, 200 miles southeast of San Jose.
   Butler lost 49 of his 175 pounds and his wife dropped from 150
pounds to 92, he said.
   ``But we are in pretty good shape because we had food all the
time and the doctor at the hospital in Golfito said we can return to
Miami next Monday,'' he said.
   Butler, a Cuban-American, came to the United States from Cuba in
1960. He has two children who live in Miami.
   ``It was a happy ending,'' he said. ``I'm going home to Miami.
I'll buy another boat and will sail again.''
</TEXT>
