<FIRST>r a AM-TunaEmbargo     08-21 0473</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tuna Embargo,0485</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S., Industry Warn Against Dolphin Observer Requirement During Tuna
Fishing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. government and the tuna fishing
industry warned Monday that U.S. trade would be hurt and dolphins
would gain little if observers were required to monitor
dolphin-killing by every foreign tuna boat.
   A lawyer for environmental groups told a federal judge that U.S.
law requires foreign-owned tuna boats selling to the United States
to meet the same standard as domestic boats _ an observer on every
boat to monitor and prevent needless killing of dolphins during tuna
fishing.
   But lawyers for the government and the domestic industry
disagreed.
   ``Congress recognized that immediate compliance for the foreign
fleets would be impossible,'' Justice Department lawyer Charles
Brooks told U.S. District Judge Thelton Henderson.
   Brooks contended the law allowed Commerce Secretary Robert
Mosbacher to determine that only one-third of the foreign boats had
to carry observers this year. Federal law forbids the United States
to buy tuna products from any nation that violates the observer
standards.
   If 100 percent coverage were required, foreign fleets would
simply stop selling their tuna to U.S. companies and trade instead
with other nations that do not regulate dolphin-killing, said David
Burney, lawyer for the U.S. Tuna Foundation, an industry group.
   Such a requirement ``would precipitously cause these nations to
abandon their participation in the only program that exists'' to
protect the dolphins, Martin Hochman, lawyer for the National
Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration, told reporters.
   Henderson said he would rule in several days on whether the law
requires every foreign boat to carry an observer.
   In January, the judge issued an injunction requiring all U.S.
tuna boats to carry observers, rejecting the government's argument
that a budget shortage justified a reduction in observer coverage.
Hochman said Congress later approved the money needed for complete
coverage.
   The dolphins, which swim above yellowfin tuna, are killed when
caught in nets cast to catch tuna below the surface. The observers
are there to see that boats comply with a law requiring use of the
best available technology to avoid needless killings.
   Brooks, the government's lawyer, agreed with environmental groups
that foreign boats kill more dolphins. But he said not enough money
and trained observers are available for 100 percent coverage of the
foreign boats. Brooks argued that one-third of the boats was a large
enough sample to tell whether the fleet was complying with U.S. laws.
   However, Joshua Flom, lawyer for the Earth Island Institute and
the Marine Mammal Fund, said Congress had rejected the same argument
as a justification for less than 100-percent observer coverage of
U.S. tuna boats.
   ``Boats behave very differently if they have an observer on
board,'' Flom said. ``Why would Congress require something more
extensive for the domestic fleet than for the foreign fleet?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890821-0126 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-21-89 2013EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Thornburgh-Leaks     08-21 0396</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Thornburgh-Leaks,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressmen ``Deeply Disturbed'' Over Anti-Leak Drive</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two congressmen said Monday they are ``deeply
disturbed'' by Justice Department plans to crack down on leaks by
prosecuting government officials and subpoenaing reporters'
telephone records.
   ``You are invoking the statute on theft of government property
which really has nothing to do with leaks,'' Reps. Don Edwards,
D-Calif., and Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., said in a letter to Attorney
General Dick Thornburgh.
   ``Congress has not adopted a criminal statute for leaks, and
certainly never intended the theft of property law to be used in
this way,'' they wrote.
   Edwards is chairman of the House Judiciary subcommittee on civil
and constitutional rights and Schumer chairs the subcommittee on
criminal justice.
   Thornburgh on Sunday said subpoenaing reporters' telephone
records was constitutional. He had said on Aug. 3 he wouldn't
prosecute reporters who obtain news leaks about criminal
investigations but could charge federal officials who are their
sources with stealing government property.
   ``The statute clearly calls for prosecution of those involved in
misusing sensitive information that comes to them in an official
capacity,'' said Thornburgh.
   The department's reversal of an 11-year-old policy that was
intended to protect whistleblowers and reporters from prosecution
was announced the previous day in testimony submitted to Congress.
   The congressmen said they were ``deeply disturbed by the
department's decision to seek criminal sanctions against government
employees who leak information,'' and were ``opposed to forcing
reporters to disclose their sources, through compulsory process or
subpoenas for reporters' telephone records.''
   A source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Monday that
the department had considered subpoenaing the telephone records of
CBS-TV reporter Rita Braver, who reported earlier this year that an
FBI investigation involved Rep. William Gray, D-Pa.
   Stories about Gray abounded during the House Democratic
leadership election and the Justice Department took the unusual step
of announcing he was not the subject of an investigation. Gray was
elected House Democratic Whip.
   FBI agents interviewed department officials about the leak and at
least one official testified before a grand jury.
   CBS learned several weeks ago about the plan to subpoena Braver's
phone records before it happened, and confronted the department,
said the source.
   Tom Goodman, a spokesman for the network in New York, said the
records had not been subpoenaed.
   Justice Department spokesman Dan Eramian declined to comment on
the issue.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
