<FILEID>AP-NR-08-21-89 2115EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Battleship-Crew     08-21 0548</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Battleship-Crew,0564</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Says Iowa Crew Untested Before Explosion</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWPORT NEWS, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Navy failed to properly qualify the
sailors who worked in the battleship USS Iowa's No. 2 turret when it
exploded last April, a newspaper reported Monday.
   Navy regulations require that all sailors and civilian Navy
employees who work with explosives must first be certified by a
Qualification Board at their posts. Sailors who lack board
certification are permitted to handle the weapons only in the
presence of a supervisor.
   Michael Drowns, one of 11 sailors who escaped turret No. 2 after
the April 19 explosion, told the Daily Press of Newport News that a
Qualification Board was never convened on the Iowa during his three
years on the ship.
   Drowns left the ship Aug. 1 in preparation for leaving the Navy
with a dishonorable discharge Aug. 11.
   Other Iowa sailors and a Navy officer familiar with the Iowa
investigation confirmed Drowns' statements to the Daily Press, but
they asked that they not be identified for fear of retribution by
the Navy.
   Adm. Richard Milligan, who headed the Navy's probe of the
explosion, said no records of a Qualification Board had been found
on the Iowa, one of the sources told the newspaper. Milligan has
declined to comment publicly on the probe.
   Lt. Kevin Wensing said Monday the report on the explosion is in
the hands of Navy officials, but has not been released to the
public. Wensing said he could not comment further.
   Although many of the sailors who worked in the No. 2 turret had
completed basic technical training in a school, none had been
qualified by a Qualification Board, Drowns and other sources said.
   Drowns and another turret No. 2 survivor, Gunner's Mate 2nd Class
John Mullahy, said that before the explosions the turret's senior
enlisted man, Senior Chief Gunner's Mate Reginald O. Ziegler, was
concerned about the lack of qualification booklets.
   Ziegler, one of the 47 sailors who died in the blast, had given
photocopied pages of the Performance Qualification Standard booklets
to some sailors. Navy regulations require that sailors have the
books.
   Mullahy and a third Iowa survivor, Gunner's Mate 3rd Class
Kendall Truitt, said one of the sailors who lacked a book was
Gunner's Mate 3rd Class Robert W. Backherms, the rammerman of the
center gun where the explosion occurred. Truitt said Backherms
joined the ship shortly after Christmas, was inexperienced and may
have caused the blasts by ramming the bags of explosives into the
gun too fast.
   Last month, NBC News reported that Navy investigators believed
the explosion was the result of suicidal sabotage by Gunner's Mate
Clayton Hartwig. Navy spokesman Lt. Greg Smith said July 19 the
conclusion of suicide was not based on official Navy reports.
   Retired Rear Adm. Eugene Carroll Jr., told the Daily Press he
suspected that a decision on whether to convene a qualification
board depends on the commanding officer.
   Carroll, deputy director of the Center for Defense Information, a
private think tank in Washington, said the regulation probably is
followed as much as a regulation requiring paperwork on preventive
maintenance.
   ``The degree of adherence ranged from very, very low to very,
very strict,'' Carroll said. ``I would almost expect you could say
the same thing about the performance qualification process.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
