<FIRST>r i AM-Salvador-Wounded     08-21 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador-Wounded,0381</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eight Wounded Guerrillas Occupy Cathedral</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eight invalids who said they
were guerrillas suffering from war wounds have occupied the Roman
Catholic cathedral to press their demand for the evacuation of rebel
casualties.
   A dozen civilian supporters accompanied the invalids who remained
in the cathedral after Sunday's service.
   Carlos Chavez, who said his right leg was amputated after he was
wounded in combat last year, spoke with The Associated Press Monday
on the cathedral steps.
   Draped across the main entrance was a banner reading ``FMLN.''
   Those are the initials of the Farabundo Marti National Liberation
Front, a coalition of leftist guerrillas groups that have battling
the government for nearly 10 years.
   ``We intend to stay here until evacuation is arranged for us and
for all the FMLN war wounded,'' said Chavez.
   President Alfredo Cristiani said Monday the issue of the
evacuation of rebel wounded could not be resolved until peace talks
are held.
   ``Evacuation of wounded is a subject that must be dealt with in
the overall dialogue,'' Cristiani told journalists.
   Both the government and the FMLN have declared in recent weeks a
willingness to join in another round of peace talks but no
arrangements have been made.
   There have been four rounds of negotiations since 1984 but none
produced progress towar ending the war that has taken the lives of
an estimated 70,000 people, with most of the victims civilians.
   Chavez said he did not know how many wounded rebels were awaiting
treatment.
   Last May the previous government of President Jose Napoleon
Duarte authorized the transfer out of El Salvador of 109 wounded
guerrillas.
   But that evacuation was not carried out because of disagreements
between Duarte's centrist Christian Democrats and Cristiani's
right-wing Republican Nationalist Alliance, or Arena.
   Nearly 350 wounded guerrillas have been evacuated since 1984,
with most taken to Cuba via Mexico. The last evacuation occurred in
May 1988.
   Monsignor Arturo Rivera Damas, the archbishop of San Salvador,
told reporters that evacuation of the wounded ``was one of the
elements of humanizing the conflict that should be resumed.'' He
said the church was willing to mediate arrangements to conduct
evacuations.
</TEXT>
