<FIRST>r a AM-PornCase     08-21 0265</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Porn Case,0271</SECOND>
<HEAD>Citing FBI Agent's Mental Problems, Court Orders New Porn Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court ordered a new trial Monday
for a defendant in a 12-year-old pornography case that fell apart
when an FBI agent became mentally unbalanced.
   The 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals upheld a lower court's
ruling that Theodore Rothstein was entitled to a new trial on
federal pornography and obscenity convictions arising from a 1977
FBI undercover operation in Miami, Fla.
   According to court documents, FBI agents Patrick Livingston and
Bruce Ellavsky posed as pornographers in 1977. Their efforts netted
indictments against 16 people, including Rothstein.
   After Rothstein was convicted in June 1981, Livingston was
arrested on a shoplifting charge and gave Miami police his
undercover name.
   ``The government indicated that Livingston had psychiatric
problems involving an inability to distinguish between his real and
undercover identities,'' the 11th Circuit said in its opinion.
``Upon further investigation, it was revealed that concerns for the
mental health of Livingston had been voiced by his superiors as
early as March 1980.''
   Since Livingston's testimony was a key to the convictions of
Rothstein and his co-defendant, Robert DiBernardo, their guilty
verdicts were vacated and the indictments against them thrown out.
The 11th Circuit, however, ruled in 1985 that the indictment could
stand.
   A federal judge then ordered new trials for both Rothstein and
DiBernardo.
   DiBernardo, whose conviction also had previously been reversed,
has been missing since June 1986 and no longer falls under the 11th
Circuit's jurisdiction. The court said he could deserve a new trial
if he surfaces.
</TEXT>
