<FIRST>r a AM-AttorneyGeneralResigns 1stLd-Writethru a0648 08-21 0630</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Attorney General Resigns, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0648,0641</SECOND>
<HEAD>W.Va. Attorney General Resigns to Halt Criminal Investigation</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to CORRECT that Forbes' office first proposed
agreement, sted Brown, UPDATE with Brown spokeswoman's comment, Forbes
comment that grand jury was to vote on charges, ADD background on treasurer
resigning; picks up 8th graf pvs, `Brown, a Democrat ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JONATHAN GILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West Virginia Attorney General Charlie
Brown resigned Monday as part of an agreement to halt the second
criminal case against him since he took office in 1984, a prosecutor
said.
   Kanawha County Prosecutor Bill Forbes said he agreed to drop a
grand jury investigation into Brown's campaign finances and reports
that he lied under oath during a child custody hearing.
   ``The attorney general agreed to resign and we agreed not to
continue the investigation,'' Forbes said Monday night. ``It was in
the best interest of the state, the best interest of Mr. Brown, and
the best interest of all concerned.''
   Forbes said his office worked ``very intensely'' on the
investigation for four weeks. He said Brown's attorney called his
office about noon Monday and agreed to the arrangement, which
Forbes' office proposed a week ago.
   The agreement was reached at 4:30 p.m. and Brown, 39, submitted
his resignation to Gov. Gaston Caperton at 5 p.m., effective
immediately.
   Under the agreement, Brown cannot talk to reporters about his
guilt or innocence in the grand jury investigation.
   Telephone calls to Brown's home Monday evening were not answered.
His spokeswoman, Carrie Webster, said he would have no comment until
a news conference Tuesday.
   Brown had testified Thursday, Friday and Monday before a county
grand jury that was investigating both the attorney general's
campaign financial records and an allegation that he had lied under
oath during a child custody hearing.
   ``We were going to ask for a vote on charges sometime this
afternoon or early tomorrow,'' Forbes said.
   Brown's resignation marked the second time this year a major
state official had quit amid allegations of misconduct. Treasurer A.
James Manchin, who was accused of mismanaging a state investment
fund that lost an estimated $279 million and was impeached by the
House, resigned last month just before his Senate trial was to begin.
   Brown, a Democrat, was elected in 1984 and re-elected without
opposition in 1988.
   In 1986, Brown was acquitted on charges that he shook down his
staff for campaign contributions. He contended that because he had
solicited the contributions after the 1984 election to help pay off
his campaign debts, the actions did not fall under a state law
prohibiting state officials from soliciting campaign funds from
their staffs.
   The latest grand jury investigation centered on Brown's testimony
in a child custody hearing involving his ex-wife, Alice Sue
Hypes-Brown, and their 5-year-old girl.
   Forbes confirmed that the grand jury was looking into a report
that Brown had denied writing a note introduced as evidence in the
hearing, then later admitted writing it.
   Brown acknowledged that he denied writing the note but said he
realized his mistake almost immediately. He said he requested a
brief recess, and when the hearing resumed he corrected his
testimony.
   The Charleston Gazette reported two weeks ago that the note
involved a request for $50,000 from Brown's former secretary. The
paper said she had been impregnated by Brown, had had an abortion
and demanded the money to keep quiet. The secretary, Brenda K. Simon
on Columbus, Ohio, has filed a $3 million libel suit against the
paper, denying the allegations.
   A native of Mansfield, Ohio, Brown is a graduate of Denison
University and the Yale Law School. He served as a staff attorney
for the Federal Trade Commission and as a deputy state attorney
general from 1978 to 1982.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
