<FIRST>r a AM-People-Polonia 1stLd-Writethru a0654 08-21 0317</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-Polonia, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0654,0323</SECOND>
<HEAD>Yankees Baseball Player Convicted on Sex Offense</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 7th graf, `Polonia made...,' with 2 grafs to UPDATE with
Polonia comment. A longer version also moving on some sports wires.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MI1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HARTZELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York Yankees outfielder Luis Polonia pleaded
no contest Monday to having sex with a 15-year-old girl last week,
but the judge postponed sentencing until after the baseball season.
   Polonia, 24, entered his plea to the misdemeanor charge before
Milwaukee County Circuit Judge Thomas Doherty. While not an
admission of guilt, a no-contest plea is treated as a guilty plea
for sentencing purposes.
   Polonia faces up to nine months in jail and a $10,000 fine.
   In an interview after the hearing, Doherty said he delayed
sentencing until Oct. 2 to provide enough time for a presentencing
report to be completed. ``The baseball season was not a factor,'' he
said. The regular season ends Oct. 1.
   Polonia's bail was continued at $5,000, and prosecutors said he
would not have to return to Milwaukee until the next hearing.
   The incident took place at a downtown hotel Wednesday. Under
Wisconsin law, an adult may not have intercourse with a child under
the age of 16 even if the child consents.
   Polonia, who made no comments during the hearing except to answer
the judge's questions, returned to New York later and was in the
lineup against Boston on Monday night.
   ``After the season I'm going to be nervous just like I was
today,'' Polonia said of the pending sentencing. ``But it's
something I'm going to have to deal with.''
   Assistant District Attorney John DiMotto urged Doherty to
sentence Polonia immediately, citing the trauma inflicted on the
girl's family.
   Polonia's attorney, Dennis Coffey, issued a statement Thursday
that the player accepted full responsibility and wanted to apologize
to the girl, his team and professional baseball.
</TEXT>
