<FILEID>AP-NR-08-21-89 2227EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Panama     08-21 0395</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Panama,0413</SECOND>
<HEAD>Panama Accuses United States Of Treaty Violation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Panamanian government on Monday
accused the United States of violating the Panama Canal Treaties by
conducting military exercises in Panama.
   Also Monday, talks between the opposition and government broke
off with no agreement on who will run the country after Sept.1. The
opposition wants to take power based on its victory in May 7
elections, which were annulled by the government.
   Spokesmen for both sides said they would wait for Wednesday's
meeting of regional foreign ministers at the Organization of
American States' Washington offices before deciding how to proceed.
   Meanwhile, Foreign Minister Jorge Ritter made the accusation to
diplomats after a presentation of Panamanian government film clips
showing U.S. military exercises.
   ``All these maneuvers have been performed outside of the military
zones, and outside of the areas under joint military control,''
Ritter said.
   Ritter said he wanted the diplomats to be ``absolutely sure''
that the maneuvers violate both the treaties and Panama's
territorial integrity.
   Ritter said that the treaty obligates the U.S. government to
coordinate with Panama its maneuvers, air traffic and convoys. He
said the U.S. has not done this in the military exercises.
   U.S. President Jimmy Carter and Panamanian President Omar
Torrijos signed the Panama Canal Treaties in 1977.
   ``The U.S. government has repeated again and again its arbitrary
interpretation of the treaty, saying that all the maneuvers fall
within the treaty limits,'' Ritter said.
   The presentation included clips from 12 recent U.S. military
exercises.
   Ritter said the ``disproportionate presence'' of U.S. military
equipment in Panama was one of the factors impeding an agreement
between the Panamanian government and the political opposition.
   The United States has stepped up its pressure on military
strongman Manuel Antonio Noriega since the May presidential
elections, which international observers say the opposition won.
   Washington has been pressuring Noriega to step down since
February 1988, when he was indicted on charges of drug trafficking
and money laundering by a Florida grand jury.
   OAS foreign ministers proposed on July 20 that a provisional
government be installed Sept. 1, when the term of acting President
Manuel Solis Palma expires, and that new elections follow.
   The government, military and government political parties agreed,
but the opposition has refused, demanding that Noriega resign as
chief of the Defense Forces. The government says Noriega will not
step down.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
