<DOCNO> AP890821-0137 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-21-89 2246EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-AIDSReport 1stLd-Writethur a0662 08-21 0450</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS Report, 1st Ld-Writethur, a0662,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>GAO Report: Staff Shortages Hurt AIDS Education Efforts</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: SUBS 2nd graf, The arm, to CORRECT year to 1988; picks up 3rd
graf, But CDC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHERINE RIZZO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   America's AIDS education efforts have been
impaired by staff shortages at the Centers for Disease Control, the
General Accounting Office said Monday.
   The arm of CDC that handles education programs, the Center for
Prevention Services, requested additional staff four times in 1988,
said a report from GAO, the congressional investigative body.
   But CDC was unable to provide the additional employees ``because
of agencywide staffing contraints,'' the report said.
   This year, the center sought 65 additional employees but money
was available for only 35. As of May 31, the center had 93 staff
members working on AIDS programs and funds to hire 33 more by the
end of the fiscal year, Sept. 30. The center believes it will need
30 additional employees above that, GAo said.
   The report was requested by Sen. John Glenn, D-Ohio, chairman of
the Senate Governmental Affairs Committee.
   ``We must make sure that every dollar spent on (AIDS) prevention
counts, and this report raises serious questions in my mind as to
whether this investment is being managed wisely,'' Glenn said in a
statement.
   Health administrators and Congress have been at odds for some
time, each accusing the other of failing to do enough to control
AIDS.
   Earlier this month Dr. James O. Mason, assistant secretary for
health in the Department of Health and Human Services, complained to
Congress that it too often has authorized programs but failed to
provide money.
   His example was an AIDS treatment program. Congress said the
government could spend $15 million to help pay for treatments with
the drug AZT, but lawmakers didn't come through with a new
appropriation. That meant administrators had to find the $15 million
somewhere else if they wanted to run the program.
   The same situation looms for the next fiscal year, when $30
million is authorized for the AZT program, Mason said.
   ``The only place I can find that is to take it out of prevention
or biomedical research,'' he told a House oversight subcommittee.
``Someone has to make a priority decision.''
   AZT costs are expected to rise sharply, whether through Medicaid
or other programs, because of recent dramatic findings that the drug
can delay the onset of harm to the immune system among people
carrying the AIDS virus.
   A course of AZT treatment costs $8,000 a year, which some experts
have said might be halved.
   Last month the number of Americans diagnosed as having AIDS
surpassed the 100,000 mark. More than 58,000 of them have died.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
