<FIRST>r i AM-Flight103     08-21 0260</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Flight 103,0266</SECOND>
<HEAD>Relatives of Flight 103 Victims Meet Transport Heads</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British transport chiefs rebuffed a demand Monday
by relatives of victims of the Pan Am Flight 103 crash for a public
inquiry into gaps in airline security that allowed a bomb to be
placed aboard the plane.
   The disagreement came at a meeting between Transport Secretary
Cecil Parkinson and relatives of some of the 259 people aboard the
jetliner that exploded over Lockerbie, Scotland, on Dec. 21. All of
the passengers and crew perished.
   Transport Minister Michael Portillo, one of Parkinson's deputies,
said there was ``a really very frank exchange of views.''
   Bert Ammerman, U.S. president of the Victims of Pan Am Flight
103, said he told Portillo that ``we are definitely at odds with
some of the statements and the approach'' of his department.
   ``Mr. Portillo is well aware that we are not pleased with his
statements and we were not reassured,'' Ammerman said. ``We are not
satisfied with the position that the Department of Transport has
taken regarding the inquiry and regarding airport and airline
security.''
   Portillo told reporters that the relatives ``were pushing very
hard for a public inquiry into what happened before Lockerbie.''
   ``I said to them that we didn't rule that out but that our main
concern was the criminal investigation and we didn't want to
prejudice that by having matters delved into in public,'' Portillo
said.
   Investigators have said the main suspect in the bombing is an
Arab terrorist group, the Popular Front for the Liberation of
Palestine-General Command.
</TEXT>
