<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kim Dae-jung, the leader of the largest
opposition party, surrendered to prosecutors Tuesday for
interrogation involving a legislator's secret trip to communist
North Korea.
   For the second time in three weeks investigators called Kim, head
of the Party for Peace and Democracy, for questioning about the
illegal trip to North Korea by National Assemblyman Suh Yung-won.
   Kim arrived at the Seoul prosecutor's office by car escorted by
12 national legislators from his party. After a nod to dozens of
photographers he went inside with aides.
   Prosecutors said questioning would center around allegations that
Kim knew of the banned trip to North Korea by Suh well before the
case was made public and that he received $10,000 from Suh who had
received the money from North Korean agents.
   Kim has denied the charges.
   Suh, who was arrested June 28, has been charged with espionage,
violating a ban on travel to North Korea and with receiving $120,000
from communist agents.
   Prosecutors claim Suh has admitted he received $50,000 after
meeting North Korean President Kim Il Sung in Pyongyang in August of
1988 and that he gave $10,000 to Kim Dae-jung after returning to
Seoul.
   Lawyers who also belong to Kim Dae-jung's party visited Suh
Saturday and said he had been forced to make a false confession to
incriminate Kim.
   Kim Dae-jung said recently, ``l've never received a penny of
money from him (Suh). The prosecutor's disclosures are 100 percent
untrue.''
