<FIRST>a a BC-History Adv28   08-21 0468</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-History, Adv28,0488</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv28</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Monday, Aug. 28</HEAD>
<HEAD>Today In History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Monday, Aug. 28, the 240th day of 1989. There are 125
days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   On Aug. 28, 1963, 200,000 people participated in a peaceful civil
rights rally in Washington, where Dr. Martin Luther King Jr.
delivered his ``I Have a Dream'' speech in front of the Lincoln
Memorial.
   On this date:
   In 1609, Henry Hudson discovered Delaware Bay.
   In 1749, German author Johann Wolfgang von Goethe was born in
Frankfurt.
   In 1774, Mother Elizabeth Ann Seton, the first American-born
saint, was born in New York City.
   In 1828, Russian novelist Leo Tolstoy was born near Tula.
   In 1916, Italy's declaration of war against Germany took effect
during World War I.
   In 1917, ten suffragists were arrested as they picketed the White
House.
   In 1922, radio station WEAF in New York City aired the first
radio commercial. The Queensboro Realty Co. paid $100 for 10 minutes
of air time.
   In 1968, police and anti-war demonstrators clashed in the streets
of Chicago as the Democratic National Convention nominated Hubert H.
Humphrey for president.
   In 1973, more than 520 people died as an earthquake shook central
Mexico.
   In 1978, Pope John Paul I became pope, following the death of his
predecessor, Pope Paul VI.
   In 1981, John W. Hinckley Jr. pleaded innocent to charges of
attempting to kill President Ronald Reagan.
   In 1983, Israeli Prime Minister Menachem Begin, reportedly
despondent over the death of his wife and the casualty toll of
Israeli troops in Lebanon, announced his resignation.
   In 1986, retired U.S. Navy Warrant Officer Jerry A. Whitworth,
convicted for his role in a Soviet spy ring, was sentenced by a
federal judge in San Francisco to 365 years in prison.
   Ten years ago: Soviet ballerina Lyudmila Vlasova, whose husband,
Alexander Godunov, had defected to the U.S., arrived in Moscow,
telling interviewers the 73{-hour standoff at New York's Kennedy
International Airport had been ``madness.''
   Five years ago: Former Wall Street Journal reporter R. Foster
Winans Jr. and two others were indicted in New York in an alleged
stock fraud scheme based on insider trading.
   One year ago: Seventy people were killed when three Italian stunt
planes collided during an air show at the U.S. Air Base in Ramstein,
West Germany, sending flaming debris into a crowd of spectators.
   Today's birthdays: Actress Nancy Kulp is 68. Actor-dancer Donald
O'Connor is 64. Actor Ben Gazzara is 59. Actor Richard Sanders is
49. Actor David Soul is 46. Senator William Cohen, R-Maine, is 49.
Former New York Yankees manager Lou Piniella is 46. Skating champion
Scott Hamilton is 31.
   Thought for today: ``Where all think alike, no one thinks very
much.'' _ Walter Lippmann, American journalist and author
(1889-1974).
</TEXT>
