<HEAD>For Release Friday, Sept. 1</HEAD>
<HEAD>Today In History</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Today is Friday, September 1, the 244th day of 1989. There are
121 days left in the year.
   Today's highlight in history:
   Fifty years ago, on September 1, 1939, World War II began as Nazi
Germany invaded Poland. Great Britain and France declared war
against Germany two days later.
   On this date:
   In 1807, former Vice President Aaron Burr was found innocent of
treason.
   In 1878, Emma M. Nutt became the first woman telephone operator
in the United States, for the Telephone Despatch Company of Boston.
   In 1905, Alberta and Saskatchewan entered Confederation as the
eighth and ninth provinces of Canada.
   In 1923, the Japanese cities of Tokyo and Yokohama were
devastated by an earthquake that claimed some 150,000 lives.
   In 1932, New York City Mayor James J. ``Gentleman Jimmy'' Walker
resigned following charges of graft and corruption in his
administration.
   In 1945, Americans received word of Japan's formal surrender,
ending World War II. (Because of the time difference, it was
September 2 in Tokyo Bay, where the surrender took place.)
   In 1951, the United States, Australia and New Zealand signed a
mutual defense pact that came to be known as the ANZUS treaty.
   In 1961, the Soviet Union ended a moratorium on atomic testing
with an above-ground nuclear explosion in central Asia.
   In 1969, a coup in Libya brought Moammar Gadhafi to power.
   In 1972, American Bobby Fischer won the international chess crown
in Reykjavik, Iceland, by defeating Soviet player Boris Spassky in
their final match.
   In 1976, U.S. Rep. Wayne L. Hays, D-Ohio, resigned in the wake of
a scandal in which he admitted having an affair with secretary
Elizabeth Ray.
   In 1983, 269 people were killed when a Korean Air Lines Boeing
747 was shot down by a Soviet jet fighter after the airliner entered
Soviet airspace.
   In 1983, Henry ``Scoop'' Jackson, a 30-year Senate veteran known
for his liberal views on social issues and a hawkish stand on
national defense, died in Everett, Wash., at age 71.
   Ten years ago: Hurricane David tore across the Dominican
Republic, leaving hundreds of dead in its wake, before slashing
across the Windward Passage into the mountains of eastern Cuba. The
Pioneer 11 space probe survived two crossings through debris
circling the ringed planet Saturn.
   Five years ago: The astronauts aboard the shuttle Discovery
launched their third commercial satellite in three days.
   One year ago: Shipyard workers at Gdansk, Poland, ended an
eleven-day strike, acting with some reluctance on the advice of
Solidarity leader Lech Walesa.
   Today's Birthdays: Former Defense Secretary Melvin Laird is 67.
Actress Yvonne De Carlo is 65. Country singer Conway Twitty is 56.
Conductor Seiji Ozawa is 54. Comedian-actress Lily Tomlin is 50.
Singer Barry Gibb is 43.
   Thought for Today: ``The right of conquest has no foundation
other than the right of the strongest.'' _ Jean Jacques Rousseau,
French political philosopher (1712-1778).
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Advance for Use Friday, September 1</NOTE>
