<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Nashville Sound: Shenandoah Hangs in ``Like Hair in a Biscuit''</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Marty Raybon, lead vocalist for the
rising country music band Shenandoah, offers this description of the
group's promising career:
   ``We're hanging in there like a hair in a biscuit.''
   The five-member vocal band has had two straight No. 1 hit records
on the country charts: ``Sunday in the South'' in August and
``Church on Cumberland Road'' in April.
   By the end of the year, the group's album, ``The Road Not
Taken,'' may yield six hit singles. After just two years of
recording with a major label, Shenandoah has become one of the most
successful new bands in a crowded country field.
   ``I'd say our progress has been wonderful,'' Raybon said. ``We're
slap tickled to death.''
   The group, from Muscle Shoals, Ala., has been playing together
four years. They were a house band at a nightclub in Muscle Shoals
when they signed with Columbia Records.
   ``Church on Cumberland Road'' was a spirited up-tempo song while
``Sunday in the South'' was a graphic recounting of Dixie culture.
Among their other hit records, ``Mama Knows'' focused on parental
wisdom and ``She Doesn't Cry Anymore'' was tions, Sept 1-3
</TEXT>
