<DOCNO> AP890821-0178 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-21-89 1358EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e BC-WKD--RecordReviews Adv00   08-21 0660</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-WKD--Record Reviews, Adv 00,0685</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   ``5:01 Blues'' (Epic) _ Merle Haggard
   
   Country great Merle Haggard is batting .500 on ``5:01 Blues,'' an
album that succeeds with its more traditional material but falters
when the singer stretches out stylistically and ventures near
crossover land.
   When the album works, Haggard remains as vital as the younger
generation of country stars for whom he has been a major influence.
   The best songs are all on the first side of the album, which
opens with the rolling barroom piano of ``Broken Friend,'' a lament
about a relationship that falls apart when two friends become lovers.
   One could be forgiven for groaning at the title of ``Losin' in
Las Vegas.'' Who needs another song about hitting the skids in
Vegas, right? But this is a gem, with a world-weary Haggard singing
over a mournful guitar about a failed attempt to settle down (!?)
and make a home in Glittertown.
   The song ``5:01 Blues'' differs from the usual workingman's tale.
The guy in this song watches the clock, but he dreads quitting time
because he's got ``no one to go home to.''
   Haggard's rich voice and excellent backup musicians also shine on
the ballad ``Someday We'll Know'' and the mid-tempo ``Wouldn't That
Be Something.''
   The album takes a turn for the worse on the second side, an
aimless collection of songs redeemed by the bluesy ``A Thousand Lies
Ago.'' Haggard can do better than the lightweight boogie of ``If You
Want to Be My Woman'' and ``Sea of Heartbreak,'' an odd attempt to
incorporate a pseudo-reggae beat into his bag of tricks.
   Also, with only about half an album's worth of good material, it
seems appropriate to note the record's entire length is barely more
than 30 minutes.
   _ By Marc Rice, Associated Press Writer.
   
 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Diamond Mine'' (Atlantic) _ Blue Rodeo
   
   Knocking one band to praise another is usually a cheap way to do
business, but sometimes the comparisons are too good to resist.
   The virtually unknown band Blue Rodeo has perfected the languid
country-rock sound sought by ballyhooed Canadian cousins Cowboy
Junkies. But unlike the Junkies, Blue Rodeo's work is neither
affected nor boring.
   ``Diamond Mine'' is just as its title suggests, a record where
treasures are regularly unearthed.
   With nearly every song, there's the nagging sense that you've
heard it somewhere before but can't quite place it. And while there
are hints of Bruce Springsteen, the Band, Jackson Browne, Johnnie
Cash and dozens of others in the music, it's not strictly derivative.
   Common themes are dealt with succinctly and without cliche. The
Toronto-based band quickly undresses Oliver North on ``God and
Country.'' ``You call this justice,'' sing Jim Cuddy and Greg
Keelor. ``I call this self-service.''
   While ``Love and Understanding'' tackles the problems of war and
drug abuse with a hopelessly '60s approach _ ``Love and
understanding are the best answers I've heard yet'' _ it somehow
doesn't sound naive.
   Blue Rodeo mixes country twang and rock drive adroitly, with
Cuddy's relatively sweet voice offering a good counterpoint to
Keelor's sinister growl. The instrumentation is first-rate, with
inspired drumming by Cleave Anderson on ``Love and Understanding''
and duty on the piano, accordion and organ by Bob Wiseman.
   They mix brief instrumental interludes with titles such as
``Swells'' and ``Percussive Piano'' on the hour-long disc. The
approach gives a relaxed pace that accentuates the finer songs.
   The one miscalculation here is a whopper. The title cut's killer
hook rightfully makes it the centerpiece of the record, but a
meandering solo passage stretches the song to a grueling 8:18. Throw
out the Doors records from this group's collection!
   Even this mistake gives notice this is a band with a strong and
stubborn view of itself. Throughout ``Diamond Mine,'' this
self-confidence consistently rewards listeners.
   _ By David Bauder, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
</DOC>
