<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--Mature:Exercise     08-21 0321</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Mature: Exercise,0331</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Mature Years: Exercise</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   As you age, you need to exercise as much as ever, say health
experts. Regular exercise can help you maintain flexibility and
endurance.
   At the same time, you should be wary of of potential injury,
according to Dr. Gil Allen, vice president of the New York State
Chiropractic Association. He offers these tips to maximize the
benefits of exercise and minimize the possibility of getting hurt:
   _ Check with your doctor before starting any exercise program,
especially if you've been inactive for a while.
   _ Choose an exercise that you can do and will enjoy.
   _ Take it slow and steady. Remember, your body isn't 20 years old
any more, so allow time for your muscles to adapt to the added work
you're giving them. First try working out on alternate days, then
gradually increase intensity and duration.
   _ Consider your body type when choosing an exercise. People with
slender, angular frames usually don't have sufficient muscle mass
for high-strength exercises but do well in endurance activities such
as long-distance running or cross-country skiing. Overweight people
should be wary of putting too much pressure on joints or risk stress
injuries by running; they're better off with moderate aerobic
activities like biking, swimming and walking.
   _ Warm up and cool down. Exercise slowly at first to limber up
and get blood flowing into muscles and joints. This will increase
muscle elasticity and help prevent injury. Cool down for five
minutes by stretching; stretches should be slow and not painful.
   _ Pain signals injury, so pay attention to it. Be alert for pain
in bones, joints, or muscles; spasms or swelling; joint stiffness;
restricted motion; or numbness or tingling in a hand or foot. Use
the R-I-C-E (Rest-Ice-Compression-Elevation) treatment as first aid
and continue until pain and swelling are gone. Sprains are serious
and require immobilization of the injured part.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
