<DOCNO> AP890821-0191 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-21-89 0200EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--Mature:Dental     08-21 0482</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Mature: Dental,0490</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Mature Years: Dental</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Fewer people now lose their teeth as they age, thanks to greater
knowledge about dental hygiene, fluoridation, and more sophisticated
skills used by dentists.
   You can increase your chances of saving your teeth with proper
care and awareness of the types of problems that can develop as you
age, according to Pamela Parker Brangan, associate professor of
dental hygiene at Old Dominion University in Norfolk, Va. She offers
these tips:
   _ Fight tooth decay _ which most often occurs in the root at the
gum line _ by limiting sweets and brushing near the gum line with a
soft brush. Ms. Brangan points out that the roots are not covered by
enamel and are especially vulnerable to rapid decay. She notes that
hard toothbrushes are not only ineffective at cleaning at the gum
line but can abrade the root surface, sensitizing teeth to hot and
cold.
   _ Be alert to signs of gingivitis such as red, swollen and tender
gums that may bleed when brushed or flossed. This form of
periodontal disease, which develops slowly and progressively, causes
more tooth loss in people over 40 than any other problem, says Ms.
Brangan. Gingivitis can be prevented or reversed with daily care,
along with consultation with a dentist or dental hygienist. They can
recommend a proper cleaning routine and determine if hard deposits
need to be removed or fillings re-filled. The advanced form of this
disease is called periodontitis and is characterized by loose teeth,
receded gums, bad breath or bad taste in the mouth, and pus between
gums and teeth. Left untreated, periodontitis usually ends in tooth
loss.
   _ Offset dry mouth by trying a saliva substitute or consulting
with your doctor about changing medications, which can contribute to
the problem. Saliva production decreases with age, and because it
helps protect teeth from plaque, this can contribute to decay as
well as cause discomfort. Denture wearers also are likely to
experience discomfort because saliva is normally needed to form a
seal between dentures and soft gum tissues.
   _ Don't overcompensate for the natural decline of taste buds by
adding extra salt and sugar to foods.
   _ Take care of your dentures. Daily hygiene continues to be
important, since plaque and calculus form on dentures as they do on
natural teeth, causing irritation to the gum tissue and often
leading to oral lesions under dentures. Dentures should be rinsed
after meals and brushed once a day. Ms. Brangan recommends using a
non-abrasive cleaner and a toothbrush, cleaning the outer surfaces
with the flat portion of the brush and inner surfaces with the tip.
The tip also works well for cleaning clasps of partial dentures, she
says. Finish by thoroughly rinsing.
   _ Avoid long-term or severe sun exposure or excessive use of
tobacco or alcohol, since all contribute to possible cancers.
  
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890821-0192 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-21-89 0200EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--Mature:Memory     08-21 0314</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Mature: Memory,0320</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Mature Years: Memory Aids</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The older person who has trouble remembering
simple things like the route to a friend's house or a store in his
neighborhood can use basic navigation principles to overcome the
problem, say researchers at the Catholic University of America.
   Consciously using landmark identification the same way as ships
or hikers can help the older person keep track of the way, according
to Paula Darby Lipman of Rockville, Md., a recent Ph.D. graduate.
Ms. Lipman and James E. Youniss, CUA professor, organized a study to
determine how people of various ages remembered routes as part of
their research on age-related memory function. They ``walked''
members of their study groups through slides representing trips
through neighborhoods.
   ``Older persons tended to make a lot more personal associations
with the routes. Younger persons looked strictly for ways to
remember the routes. When I interviewed the oldest subjects, they
often mentioned the flowers in the trees, the condition of the
neighborhood, or the season,'' says Ms. Lipman.
   She says that older people may have wanted to make the
identifying task more meaningful or personal to offset the burden of
coping with all the information presented. But her study confirmed
that those who concentrated on landmarks at turns were best able to
recreate the routes from unordered slides.
   ``There's so much information you can get from any route. It's
just that some of it is more important. Picking out the information
that will help in remembering turns is easier than trying to
remember all the landmarks in sequential order,'' she says.
   The study supports a widely held theory about aging and memory _
that for many people, short-term memory decreases with age. Though
some seem to use the landmark strategy naturally, others can learn
the technique with a conscious effort, Ms. Lipman says.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890821-0193 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-21-89 0201EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--Mature:HouseCalls     08-21 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Mature: House Calls,0352</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Mature Years: House Calls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   That comforting amenity of memory, the
doctor's house call, still exists.
   Dr. James Mold, for one, still makes house calls to elderly
patients and says he finds them useful and, in fact, enjoyable.
   ``There are a variety of reasons physicians still make them,''
says Mold, assistant professor of family medicine and director of
the geriatrics program at the University of Oklahoma Health Sciences
Center. ``One reason I make house calls is that they allow me to get
to know patients in a way I can't during a regular office call.''
   Mold says that the home setting often alerts him to problems like
overuse of medication or alcohol abuse _ things he might miss during
an office appointment.
   ``With geriatric patients, how they function is often much more
important than diagnosing disease,'' he says. ``The place where
people function is in their home, so it's crucial in some cases that
you actually see what the person is dealing with.''
   Mold says the home setting is more relaxing and reassuring to the
patient, and he often can get a more accurate blood pressure reading.
   But the negative side has to be considered, too, he says. The
doctor can't rely on staff and equipment backup that he has at his
office. There also is the cost, which isn't covered by fees.
   Despite these drawbacks, he predicts that a doctors will make
more house calls in the future, owing to the greater number of older
people and to the interest in home health care to shorten hospital
stays. Doctors probably will be working closely with home care
agencies, he says.
   Patients who are too frail to make trips to the office or don't
have transportation shouldn't hesitate to ask their doctors to come
to them, he adds.
   ``Personally, I find house calls very enjoyable. I feel more
comfortable, and the patients feel more comfortable,'' he says.
``People are appreciative when I take the time to come out, and
everyone likes to be appreciated.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
