<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--Mature:Caregivers     08-21 0247</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Mature: Caregivers,0253</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Mature Years: Caregivers' Guide</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Organizing caregiving in a businesslike way can defuse emotional
tension when you find yourself responsible for the care of an aging
parent or relative, says JoanEllen Foyder, author of ``The Family
Caregiver's Guide.''
   Foyder, of Yonkers, N.Y., is a former shopping mall management
executive who cared for her mother through a difficult Parkinson's
disease illness. That the responsibility fell on her as the closest
female relative was typical, since the majority of caregivers are
women, regardless of the number of male relatives.
   What wasn't typical was her response. ``Once I realized it was
sink or swim, I took it on as a business assignment,'' she says. She
organized charts, schedules and plotted ways to involve other
members of the family and even visitors.
   These are incorporated in her book, which the publishers say is
the first guide on the subject for non-professionals.
   She advises the caregiver to avoid the martyr role and to speak
up for her own needs. By giving copies of a care schedule to other
members of the family, they will become aware of just how many hours
each task takes and the size of the burden she's handling.
   She should ask for on-site help from each member of the family or
money to pay for professional help to give the caregiver respite. A
written family agreement will defuse many feelings of guilt or
resentment about the responsibilities, she says.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
