<HEAD>For release Thursday, Aug. 24, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Illinois Laws Protect Elderly, Restore Tax Exemption</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bills restoring a $1,000 income-tax
exemption to the disabled and elderly and strengthening protections
for senior citizens have been signed into law by Gov. James R.
Thompson.
   The tax measure, which will be worth $30 per taxpaer beginning in
the 1990 tax year, restores an exemption erased by federal tax
reform. Until 1987, both state and federal law allowed blind and
elderly taxpayers to claim an extra personal exemption on their
income taxes. Elimination of that tax break on the federal level
also erased it for Illinois taxpayers, since state income tax
calculations are based on the federal tax return.
   Other bills will establish an ombudsman in the state Department
on Aging as an advocate for nursing home residents; extend
eligibility of some low-income elderly for a program that pays for
heart and diabetes drugs; and create felony offenses for neglect or
financial exploitation of an elderly or disabled person to aid
prosecutors in punishing con artists who prey on the elderly.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Days Inns Announces 2nd Annual Senior Power Job Fair</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 600 companies accepted applications from
some of 5,000 older Americans who attended the first Senior Power
national job fair in May at 64 Days brand hotels in 26 states, Days
Inns of America says.
   Heartened by that success, the company expects more than 1,000
companies to participate in Senior Power 1990, to be held at more
than 100 hotels on May 5, 1990. There is no fee for the recruiting
employers or the senior citizens.
   ``Senior Power 1989 was an unprecedented success,'' Days Inns
President Michael A. Leven said in a statement. The company created
the job fairs as a way to involve its franchised hotels in hiring
older workers.
   Days Inns said almost all of the 634 employers at the fairs were
in the service industry. They included Kelly Services, Wendy's, K
mart Corp., Sears Roebuck &amp; Co. and McDonald's; local employers
included banks, schools, retail outlets, museums, libraries,
restaurants, hotels and hospitals.
   Days Inns said it has found older workers to be more reliable,
more loyal and more productive than many of their younger
counterparts. Where turnover in the hotel industry averages 105
percent a year, Days Inns has seen a decrease, and turnover among
the older workers is less than 1 percent.
   In addition, it said, tardiness and absenteeism are virtually
nonexistent and health insurance costs have not increased.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Hotel Assn. Offers Tips, Help Finding Jobs in Lodging</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rapid growth in the lodging industry has meant
a boom in job opportunities, according to the American Hotel &amp; Motel
Association, which offers a free booklet to answer questions for
those interested in employment.
   ``Employers have learned that older people and the handicapped
are productive, reliable workers and just as capable of learning new
skills as the young,'' association President Elaine Grossinger Etess
said in a statement.
   ``If you're 50 and over, you may have a job advantange and you
can work part-time, flex-time or full time on your own convenient
schedule,'' said Etess, who has offered to help forward resumes or
letters outlining people's experience to hotels or motels in their
states.
   Write to Elaine Grossinger Etess, American Hotel &amp; Motel
Association, 1201 New York Ave. N.W., Washington, D.C. 20005. For a
free copy of ``Answers to Important Questions About Jobs in Hotels
and Motels,'' send a self-addressed stamped envelope.
</TEXT>
