<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumer prices rose 0.2 percent in July,
markedly slower than the steep acceleration earlier in the year,
according to the Labor Department.
   While retail prices were up 5.9 percent for the year's first
half, the moderation actually began in June, when prices also rose
just 0.2 percent.
   Private analysts and the White House said Friday the two-month
softening was a sign the economy had moved beyond the worst
inflationary period.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unisys Corp. says it would cut more than
6,000 jobs _ or up to 8 percent of the computer company's worldwide
workforce _ by the end of 1990 under a restructuring plan.
   The plan announced Friday represents an acknowledgement by the
hard-driving chairman of Unisys, W. Michael Blumenthal, that the
growth plans of the nation's third-largest computer maker were
overly ambitious.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unsafe landings occurred on two Eastern Airlines
flights recently because of inexperienced pilots hired to replace
strikers, the Air Line Pilots Association contends.
   But both Eastern and the federal agency responsible for air
safety disputed the claims Friday.
   The union representing pilots at most major U.S. airlines said
the incidents involved ``hard landings'' at airports in Atlanta and
Chicago. The airplanes were damaged in both cases but there were no
injuries, the pilots union said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government will strengthen its inspection
force for dealing with generic drugs _ adding $18 million for more
field inspectors _ as part of a plan to cope with burgeoning
revelations of fraud in the industry, sources have said.
   The Department of Health and Human Services also will seek
legislation allowing the Food and Drug Administration to remove
drugs from the market if fraud is proven to have occurred in the
substances' approval, the sources said Friday. FDA officials have
argued that they have no legal power to halt the sales of drugs in
such cases.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Warner Communications Inc. and Chris-Craft
Industries Inc. have taken a big step toward disentangling their
corporate ties, announcing settlement of several legal disputes that
have blocked the separation.
   Under the settlement announced Friday, it was agreed that
Warner's interest in Chris-Craft's BHC Communications Inc. would be
distributed to Warner stockholders _ who include Chris-Craft _ as
part of the package of cash and securities comprising the second
part of Time's tender offer for Warner.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president of Rite Aid Corp pleaded innocent
to charges of bribing an Ohio Pharmacy Board member and of
possession of criminal tools.
   Martin L. Grass, 35, entered the plea Friday in Cuyahoga County
Common Pleas Court before Judge Jose A. Villanueva. Grass is free on
$100,000 bond.
   Shiremanstown, Pa.-based Rite Aid, the nation's largest retail
pharmacy chain, released a three-page statement calling the
indictment against Grass and the company ``bizarre.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorneys say they have reached a settlement of the
wrongful death lawsuit filed against the widow of Arthur Kane, who
killed a Merrill Lynch manager and himself after the 1987 stock
market crash.
   Kane, hurt badly financially by ``Black Monday,'' walked into the
Merrill Lynch &amp; Co. office in Miami on Oct. 26, 1987, one week after
the crash, killing office manager Jose Argilagos and paralyzing his
broker, Lloyd Kolokoff.
   Attorneys R.W. ``Buddy'' Payne and Frank Areces, representing
Argilagos, announced Friday that the case was settled. However a
statement from their office said Dade County Circuit Judge Martin
Greenbaum ordered the amount of damages not be disclosed.
</TEXT>
