<FIRST>r f PM-Prime-Whitney     08-21 0217</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Prime-Whitney,0225</SECOND>
<HEAD>Whitney Completes Tender Offer for Prime</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   J.H. Whitney &amp; Co., the nation's oldest venture
capital firm, says it has completed its cash tender offer for Prime
Computer Inc.
   Whitney said Sunday its DR Acquisition Corp. accepted for payment
49,520,864 shares of Prime common stock at $20 cash each. The offer
expired at midnight Friday.
   The shares represent about 79 percent of Prime's outstanding
shares on a fully diluted basis. Whitney intends to exchange notes
with a face value of $22 per share for the remainder of Prime's
shares. Analysts expect the notes to trade at a substantial discount
from face value.
   In June, Whitney agreed to buy Prime, which has posted losses the
past three quarters, in a friendly merger valued at about $1.25
billion. But earlier this month the deal was amended to lower the
purchase price to about $1.1 billion after Whitney said it had
trouble obtaining financing for the original offer.
   Prime, a minicomputer maker based in suburban Natick, had been
searching for a ``white knight,'' or friendly suitor, to ward off a
$1.13 billion hostile bid from MAI Basic Four of Tustin, Calif.
   The merger will mean the largest single investment ever for
Whitney, a private New York firm founded in 1946 by industrialist
John Hay Whitney.
