<FILEID>AP-NR-08-21-89 0756EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-CleanerDiesel     08-21 0443</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cleaner Diesel,0460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Navistar Reveals Prototype for Smokeless Engine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Trucks equipped with Navistar's new ``smokeless''
diesel engine will leave cleaner air in their wake instead of the
characteristic black smoke of their predecessors, officials of the
truck-maker say.
   ``This is a diesel for the 21st century. This prototype model
already meets the toughest 1994 state and federal pollution
standards for diesel,'' said Vice President John Horne of
Chicago-based Navistar International Corp.
   The International '94 Smokeless Diesel also significantly reduces
emissions of major pollutants, company officials said Friday.
   Trucks equipped with the engine probably will not reach the
market until 1994 due to testing and fuel requirements, the company
said.
   Diesel engines commonly are favored by commercial operators
because they give better fuel economy, require less maintenance,
last longer and produce fewer pollutants than gasoline engines.
   A major drawback is the smoke they emit, federal regulators say.
   The smokeless diesel's development comes at a time when car and
truck makers around the world are working to meet new state and
federal emission guidelines.
   By 1994, the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency will require
that all diesel makers reduce particle emissions by 90 percent from
1985 standards, and cut carbon monoxide and nitrogen oxide levels.
   Navistar's new engine will solve the problem by using a new type
of catalytic converter to reduce the amount of minute particles
released to the environment, Navistar officials said.
   The development of low-sulfur fuel also will prevent decay of the
converter, said officials of the company, the nation's leading
producer of medium- and heavy-duty trucks.
   Emission-control requirements will be so stringent by 1994 that
manufacturers will virtually have to produce a smokeless engine,
said Navistar spokesman Bill Greenhill.
   Officials of Ford Motor Co., the second leading manufacturer of
trucks, said they haven't announced plans for meeting the standards,
but expect to follow similar techniques.
   ``I would expect that we would do the same kinds of things
they're doing,'' said Ford spokesman John Emmert from Detroit. ``I
know we're all in the same boat and we're all going to have to meet
those standards.''
   A fleet of trucks equipped with 94 of Navistar's new engines will
begin open-road testing next year in Southern California, and the
company plans to begin widespread circulation of the engine in 1994,
Horne said in a news release.
   He said trucks with the new engine would not reach the market
until then because federal law requires that the catalytic converter
be tested for 150,000 miles.
   ``The other major reason is that the low-sulfur fuel needed to
allow the use of catalytic converters will not be widely available
until Oct. 1, 1993,'' he said.
</TEXT>
