<HEAD>Dollar Steady, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar was steady today in early European
trading calmed by a lack of upcoming major U.S. economic news. Gold
prices were lower.
   Foreign exchange dealers said they expected the U.S. currency to
trade within a relatively narrow range for the rest of the session,
with an underlying upward trend.
   They also predicted range-trading over the next few days in the
absence of any major U.S. economic indicators. The next noteworthy
announcement is the revision of second quarter U.S. gross national
product figures next Monday.
   In London, the dollar fell against the British pound. One pound
cost $1.5685, more expensive for buyers than Friday's late $1.5655.
