<HEAD>Dollar Off Against Yen, Stocks Hit Record High</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar moved slightly lower today against
the Japanese yen in Tokyo while the main index on the Tokyo Stock
Exchange rose to another record high.
   The dollar closed at 143.35 yen, down 0.17 yen from Friday's
close of 143.52 yen. It opened lower at 143.13 yen and ranged
between 142.95 and 143.40 yen during the day.
   On the stock market, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected
issues gained 77.69 points, or 0.22 percent, ending the day at
35,140.83, another high. It had lost 26.97 points on Friday.
   Dealers said the index's rebound in Tokyo followed gains in the
Dow Jones industrial average of 30 major issues in New York Friday.
   A Nomura Securities dealer said ``The (Tokyo) market was lacking
fresh market-affecting news to encourage buying.''
   Market players bought issues of the companies whose business
performances during the first six months of the fiscal 1989 are
expected to be good, the dealer said, speaking on condition of
anonymity. Among the winners were Sony, he said.
   Most Japanese companies report their half-yearly account
settlements in September.
   Meanwhile, currency dealings were very quiet in the absence of
market-affecting news, said Kimio Kobori, a Bank of Tokyo trader.
   ``Position adjustments were the only thing that was moving the
currency rates,'' he said.
   The dollar opened lower in Tokyo following losses in New York due
to position adjustments and profit-taking, he said.
