<DOCNO> AP890821-0217 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-21-89 1002EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-BAT     08-21 0460</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BAT,0478</SECOND>
<HEAD>BAT Profit Up 21 Percent, Issues Defense Document Against Hoylake
Bid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   BAT Industries PLC today reported a 21 percent gain
in its six-month earnings and sharply attacked financier James
Goldsmith's $21 billion hostile bid for the British conglomerate.
   BAT issued a response to a letter Goldsmith sent Sunday to BAT
Chairman Patrick Sheehy. Goldsmith had requested a meeting to
negotiate the terms of his all-securities bid, which values BAT at
13.4 billion pounds.
   A BAT spokesman said the company has no interest in talking with
Goldsmith or his partners, British banker Jacob Rothschild and
Australian entrepreneur Kerry Packer, who have formed Hoylake
Investment Ltd. to try to take over BAT.
   The takeover of the British conglomerate would be the world's
second largest, after the $24.53 billion acquisition of RJR Nabisco
Inc. by Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &amp; Co.
   Hoylake has argued that BAT shareholders would get far better
value if BAT's assets were ``unbundled.'' Hoylake has said it would
sell BAT's non-tobacco businesses, which include financial services,
retailing and paper.
   In his letter, Goldsmith said all aspects of the Hoylake offer
were open to negotiation, a possible indication the group was
willing to offer some cash.
   BAT stock was up 6 pence at 819 pence a share at midmorning on
London's Stock Exchange.
   The conglomerate said its earnings in the six months ending June
30 totaled 489 million pounds, or 32.07 pence per share, compared
with 404 million pounds, or 26.74 pence, in the same period a year
ago.
   Sales rose 23 percent to 10 billion pounds from 8.13 billion
pounds.
   BAT does not release quarterly results. It is not required to
under British law.
   The company's financial services segment turned in the best
performance. Operating profit surged to 398 million pounds from 177
million pounds.
   BAT's results included a first-time contribution from Farmers
Insurance Group Inc., the Los Angeles-based insurance company the
conglomerate acquired last year for $5.2 billion.
   BAT said its tobacco business performed well, contributing 404
million pounds to operating profit, compared with 361 million pounds
a year ago.
   The company's tobacco brands include Kent and Kool. It also owns
the Saks Fifth Avenue and Marshall Field's stores.
   BAT termed the Hoylake bid highly unattractive, saying it
consisted of a package of securities of ``dubious value.'' It
asserted that even Hoylake admitted it ``may be impossible to sell''
the debt instruments it is offering for BAT stock.
   The company said Hoylake's proposal to acquire BAT rests on a
``bewildering array of interlocking companies, most of whom are
resident in tax havens. Its vastly complex structure is designed to
add an enormous amount of money to the already substantial fortunes
of Goldsmith, Rothschild and Packer at the expense of the
shareholders of BAT.''
</TEXT>
