<FILEID>AP-NR-08-21-89 1039EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-RigCount     08-21 0322</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Rig Count,0334</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rig Count Climbs 45 to Total 903</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of working oil and gas rigs in the
country rose by 45 to total 903 last week, Baker Hughes Inc.
reported.
   The steep increase partly was due to areas drying out from the
heavy rains brought on by Hurricane Chantal several weeks ago, said
Ike Kerridge, vice president of stockholder relations and economist
for Baker Hughes.
   The increase, however, was somewhat anticipated, he said.
   ``All the surveys done said there would be more drilling in the
second half of the year. I wouldn't be surprised if we didn't have a
steady increase for the remainder of the year.''
   In Texas, which accounted for more than half of the total rig
increase, the drilling activity was focused the east and north
central portions of the state, Kerridge said.
   A year ago, the count totaled 937, Baker Hughes said Monday.
   The company's rig count _ the widely watched industry index of
drilling activity _ reflects the number of rigs actively exploring
for oil as of last Friday, not the number of rigs actively producing
oil.
   Houston-based Hughes Tool Co., an oil toolmaker company that
merged with Baker International Corp. of Orange, Calif., has kept
track of the rig count since 1940.
   In December 1981, at the height of the oil boom, the rig count
reached a peak of 4,500. But oil prices plunged to less than $10 per
42-gallon barrel in the summer of 1986, prompting a collapse in the
rig count that bottomed out at 663 _ the lowest since Hughes began
compiling figures.
   Among major oil producing states, Texas had the biggest gain with
27 followed by Ohio, six; Kansas and Wyoming, three each; California
and Pennsylvania, two each; and Michigan, one.
   North Dakota posted a loss of two and Colorado and Louisiana lost
one each. New Mexico and Oklahoma saw no change from last week.
</TEXT>
