<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet11am     08-21 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street 11am,0305</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market declined slightly today in a
quiet late-summer session.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials slipped 4.36 to 2,683.61
by 11 a.m. on Wall Street.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by about 7 to 6 in nationwide trading
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 529 up, 617 down and
559 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 38.44 million shares at
midmorning.
   Interest rates fell in the credit markets this morning. Prices of
long-term government bonds rose about $5 for each $1,000 in face
value, lowering their yields to the 8.10 percent-8.16 percent range.
   But analysts said many traders remained skeptical that rates were
headed much lower in the immediate future.
   The Federal Reserve is generally believed to be holding off on
any further moves to relax its credit policy until it can see more
evidence that inflation has been successfully restrained.
   The Dow Jones industrial average remains within striking distance
of the closing high of 2,722.42 it reached two years ago this week.
However, brokers note that it has been stalled in that area for the
past several sessions.
   Among actively traded blue chips, Philip Morris rose ] to 156~;
Ford Motor was up \ at 51|; International Business Machines dropped
[ to 115, and American Telephone &amp; Telegraph was unchanged at 39{.
   Lyphomed jumped 7~ to 30] as the most active issue in the
over-the-counter market. The company said Fujisawa Pharmaceutical,
which owns about 30 percent of its stock, proposed to acquire the
rest for $31 a share.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks lost
.11 to 192.53. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was up .27 at 379.45.
</TEXT>
