<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   08-21 0255</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0264</SECOND>
<HEAD>Weekend Rain Pressures Grain, Soybean Prices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices opened slightly
lower today on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   A series of rainstorms over the weekend were generally viewed as
good for the crops but bad for prices. Some analysts, however, said
the corn and beans would need even more rain this week in advance of
what appeared to be a return to the steamier days of August.
   Supporting prices as well were expectations that a U.S.
Department of Agriculture report due out after the close will show
the condition of crops in the field has declined in recent days.
   On the open, wheat was 1} cents to 3} cents lower, with the
contract for delivery in September at $3.90{ cents a bushel; corn
was 2{ cents to 3\ cents lower, with September at $2.32\ cents a
bushel; oats were 1\ cents lower, with September at $1.37 a bushel;
and soybeans were 4{ cents lower to 7\ cents higher, with August at
$6.23 a bushel.
   Livestock and pork futures prices were mostly lower on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .15 cent to 1.02 cents lower, with September at
74.45 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .10 cent to .55 cent lower,
with August at 84.25 cents a pound; live hogs were .22 cent to .72
cent lower, with October at 40.55 cents a pound; and frozen pork
bellies were .17 cent to 1.22 cents lower, with August at 27 cents a
pound.
</TEXT>
