<FILEID>AP-NR-08-21-89 1223EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Britain-Ford     08-21 0169</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Ford,0177</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ford Wants 24-Hour Assembly At European Plants</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. hopes to introduce 24-hour assembly
based on three shifts at the company's European plants within a
decade, a Ford spokesman said Monday.
   While 24-hour assembly is common at U.S. auto and truck plants,
it is only just being introduced by other companies in Europe,
analysts say.
   The company ``would like to see those changes within the next 10
years,'' the spokesman said, adding that there were no plans to
change working practices at present.
   British press reports Monday said Ford also hoped to introduce a
production system based on more autonomous groups of workers
operating in a highly automated environment.
   The spokesman, who was not identified in accordance with British
practice declined to comment on any hoped-for changes to work
organization.
   The spokesman said Ford has held talks with local unions, who are
concerned about plant closings that could come as a result of
round-the-clock production. He declined to give any further details.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
