<FILEID>AP-NR-08-21-89 1207EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-HawaiianAirlines-Sale     08-21 0393</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hawaiian Airlines-Sale,0405</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ueberroth in Group Buying Hawaiian Airlines Parent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An investment group that includes former baseball
commissioner Peter V. Ueberroth is buying the financially struggling
parent of Hawaiian Airlines, company officials said.
   HAL Inc. said Sunday its board of directors unanimously accepted
a tender offer of $22 a share from the group headed by J. Thomas
Talbot, a former airline executive from California. The group plans
to obtain at least 51 percent of the company's stock, making its
offer worth around $22 million.
   HAL stock, boosted in recent months by takeover rumors, has been
trading far above the $22 offered by the Talbot group, closing at
$31.62{ a share Friday on the American Stock Exchange. The shares
were trading at the same level this morning after a temporary halt.
   Earlier this month, rumors circulated that Delta Air Lines was
interested in acquiring HAL, to ward off a takeover itself and to
gain access to Hawaiian Airlines' South Pacific and Japanese routes.
The rumors were denied by HAL.
   But HAL sustained a loss of $13 million in the first half of this
year and has lost a total of $30.6 million over the past 2{ years.
   ``I thought the other (stock) price was probably an inflated
one,'' said Louis Marckesano, an airline analyst with Janney
Montgomery Scott Inc. in Philadelphia. ``I think maybe this brings
it down to earth a little bit.''
   Last spring, Ueberroth and Talbot headed a group which made a
$464 million bid for strikebound Eastern Airlines in partnership
with its three unions. But the takeover agreement between Ueberroth
and Frank Lorenzo, chairman of Eastern's parent Texas Air Corp.,
later fell apart over the unions' demand that Lorenzo be removed
from daily control of the airline.
   The group buying HAL also includes Ueberroth's brother John.
   John Magoon Jr., HAL's chairman and chief executive officer, owns
56.9 percent of the company's 1.9 million outstanding shares of
common stock.
   Hawaiian Airlines, Hawaii's largest interisland airline, also
serves Los Angeles; San Francisco; Seattle; Anchorage, Alaska; Las
Vegas, Nev.; Australia; New Zealand and other South Pacific points.
   The 60-year-old airline's fleet of 31 planes carried 5.5 million
passengers in 1988.
   The tender offer is subject to a number of conditions, including
a satisfactory agreement with the company's unions, financing and
receipt of the required approvals from government agencies, HAL said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
