<FIRST>u f AM-WangRestructuring     08-21 0436</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wang Restructuring,0450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wang Announces Debt Restructuring, An Wang Says Company Has Money
It Needs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOWELL, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wang Laboratories Inc. announced Monday it
had successfully restructured its credit agreement with banks and
will make loan repayments it suspended last week.
   Wang said its bank lenders had agreed to raise the computer
maker's line of credit by $100 million, to a total of $575 million.
In exchange, the previously unsecured line of credit will be secured
by the entire company's assets excluding inventory, which puts the
banks in line behind the bondholders in case of a liquidation.
   The deal also delays the payback for a $125 million portion of
the credit line that was to become due on Sept. 30. Payments for
that loan will begin on July 15, 1990.
   Wang is hoping to raise $175 million for working capital by
selling assets such as a factory in Scotland, its credit and leasing
subsidiary, and possibly its headquarters, which it would then lease
back.
   The agreement with the banks requires that any money raised
beyond that $175 million go toward paying off its fiscal 1990 bank
obligations, ahead of time if possible.
   ``The company believes that this debt restructuring, together
with the completion of the $175 million of additional secured
financings, will provide the company with the financing required to
meet its business plan,'' An Wang, founder and chief executive
officer of the company, said in a brief statement.
   Wang began renegotiating its lending agreements with banks after
posting record losses of $424 million in fiscal 1989, which ended
June 30. The company also announced earlier this month that
Frederick Wang, Wang's eldest son, was stepping aside as president
of the company.
   Wang said the company continues to explore sale of certain
portions of the business, including domestic and international
leasing subsidiaries. He also said the search for a new president
``is proceeding rapidly.''
   Wang Labs startled investors last week when it suspended payments
on some $209 million in debt while negotiating for new credit terms.
   Wang fell into technical default on its credit agreements on June
30 after it posted a record $424 million annual loss.
   Wang and its lenders _ led by Bank of Boston _ signed the new
credit agreement after a weekend of intensive bargaining.
   Wang's eight lender banks are Bank of Boston, Chase Manhattan,
First Chicago, Baybanks, Bank of America, Harris Bank, Mellon Bank
and Chemical Bank.
   As of June 30 _ the last report available _ Wang had borrowed a
total of $209.1 million, but how much of that came from the credit
line was not reported separately.
</TEXT>
