<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     08-21 0202</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Futures Prices Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices rose in quiet trading Monday
mainly on technical factors.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the September contract for
West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude oil,
climbed 28 cents to finish at $19.08 per 42-gallon barrel.
   Energy analysts said the September contract got a slight boost
from last-minute buying before the contract expires on Tuesday.
Contracts for later delivery rose between 14 cents and 21 cents.
   Among refined products traded on the exchange, unleaded regular
gasoline for September delivery closed 0.09 cent higher at 52.82
cents a gallon. Domestic heating oil for delivery in September rose
0.86 cent to 51.89 cents a gallon. Other contract months also posted
gains.
   Traders said declining U.S. production has helped keep prices
firm despite a global surplus of crude oil and sluggish demand.
   ``The market can support these prices because domestic production
is going down,'' said Linda Simard, energy broker at Drexel Burnham
Lambert.
   The market is awaiting new production data by the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries and beyond that to the next scheduled
meeting of the oil group's monitoring committee on Sept. 23, Ms.
Simard said.
</TEXT>
