<FIRST>r f AM-SteelProduction     08-21 0166</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Steel Production,0171</SECOND>
<HEAD>Weekly Steel Production Slips 2.1 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Domestic raw steel production in the week
ending Aug. 19 totaled 1,773,000 tons, down 2.1 percent from the
previous week, when the industry produced 1,811,000 tons, the
American Iron and Steel Institute said Monday.
   Steelmakers operated at 79.8 percent of their production capacity
last week, down from 81.5 percent the previous week, the AISI said
in Washington, D.C.
   A year earlier, the industry produced 1,836,000 tons, or 86.1
percent of capacity.
   Adjusted year-to-date production totals 64,360,000 tons, or 87.7
percent of capacity, up 1.2 percent from 63.604,000 tons, or 89.6
percent of capacity during the comparable 1988 period.
   Production by districts was: North East Coast, 212,000 tons
compared with 239,000 in the previous week; Pittsburgh 176,000, down
from 186,000; Youngstown 113,000, down from 116,000; Lake Erie
district, 149,000, down from 150,000; Detroit 164,000, up from
161,000; Chicago, 492,000, unchanged; Midwest 153,000, up from
144,000; Southern 217,000, down from 226,000; and Western 97,000,
unchanged.
