<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     08-21 0679</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0703</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cocoa Prices Plunge on Surplus Supplies, Disagreement Over Price
Support</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Cocoa futures prices plunged to life-of-contract lows Monday
following indications that two major producers would no longer back
current price-support levels.
   On other markets, soybeans weathered early pressure and made a
dramatic turnaround on heavy professional buying and copper finished
higher.
   Cocoa prices slipped as low as $69 before settling $46 to $57
lower on the New York Coffee, Sugar and Cocoa Exchange, with the
contract for delivery at $1,108 a metric ton.
   Computer-programmed selling greased the slide, but traders found
no shortage of bad news Monday.
   The world's leading cocoa producer, Ivory Coast, suggested the
price-support level set by the International Cocoa Organization may
be nearly 10 percent too high. Malaysia, the fourth-leading producer
and considered by many a crucial player in any ICCO pact, reiterated
it would not join the organization until it sorts out ``domestic
problems.''
   ``The market was very demoralized. It's clear there's much cocoa
already out there, and the 1989-90 crop is in very good shape,''
said Arthur Stevenson, who tracks cocoa for Prudential-Bache
Securities Inc., New York. ``And matters could be further
complicated if there is continued disagreement over what price can
be defended.''
   Grain futures mostly were lower but soybean prices were sharply
higher on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Traders credited heavy professional buying, led by Refco Inc. and
Rosenthal-Collins in lots of 2 million bushels each, with sparking
the turnaround in soybeans.
   Soybean prices drifted downward at the opening after weekend rain
brightened prospects for the crop. But after prices held firmer than
expected, buyers stepped in and began the upward move.
   ``People who sold the market on the weekend rains might have been
surprised,'' said Vic Lespinasse, a trader with Dean Witter Reynolds
Inc., Chicago. ``But we're headed back for more traditional August
weather and the crops are going to need more than the rain in the
forecast today and tomorrow.''
   Wheat was \ cent to 3} cents lower, with the contract for
delivery in September at $3.90\ a bushel; corn was { cent lower to \
cent higher, with September at $2.34} a bushel; oats were unchanged
to 1 cent higher, with September at $1.38} a bushel; and soybeans
were 4 cents to 12\ cents higher, with August at $6.28 a bushel.
   Copper resumed its recent rally Monday, following Friday's
interruption of a runup that had covered seven consecutive sessions.
The rally had been linked to production problems, among them ongoing
strikes by miners in Canada and Peru and many analysts attributed
Friday's brief decline the result of profit-taking.
   On Monday, prices were supported partly by reports that Mexico
had closed a state-run mining operation because of bankruptcy. Some
analysts suggested the government tried to pre-empt miners there
from going on strike.
   Copper settled .65 cent to 1.55 cents higher on the Comex, with
August at 125.45 cents a pound.
   Precious metals didn't fare as well. Gold was 30 cents to 70
cents higher, with August at $368.40 a troy ounce; silver was 1.1
cents to 1.2 cents lower, with August at 522.7 cents a troy ounce.
Platinum, traded on the New York Mercantile Exchange, was $1.60 to
$1.90 higher, with September at $485.40 a troy ounce.
   Livestock and pork futures declined on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange.
   Live cattle were .52 cent to .75 cent lower, with September at
74.10 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .10 cent to .45 cent lower,
with August at 84.12 cents a pound; live hogs were .52 cent lower to
unchanged, with October at 40.67 cents a pound; and frozen pork
bellies were .37 cent to 1.45 cents lower, with August at 26.80
cents a pound.
   Petroleum futures were higher on the New York Merc.
   Crude oil climbed 14 cents to 28 cents, with September at $19.08
a barrel; heating oil was .26 cent to .92 cent higher, with
September at 51.89 cents a gallon; and unleaded gasoline was .09
cent to .75 cent higher, with September at 52.82 cents a gallon.
</TEXT>
