<FILEID>AP-NR-08-21-89 1840EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Lucky-AlphaBeta     08-21 0603</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lucky-Alpha Beta,0619</SECOND>
<HEAD>O'Connor Issues Stay of Lucky-Alpha Beta Merger</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The $2.5 billion merger of the Lucky and Alpha
Beta supermarket chains in California was blocked Monday by Supreme
Court Justice Sandra Day O'Connor, apparently at least until early
October.
   O'Connor issued an order halting the merger at the request of
state Attorney General John Van de Kamp, who contends that the
reduced competition would cost California shoppers $400 million a
year.
   The chains, which have a total of 550 stores, were to have
combined their operations under the Lucky banner. An appeals court
order blocking the merger was to have expired Monday, though the
process of consolidation would have taken several months.
   O'Connor's order, which was not accompanied by a written opinion,
forbids the merger until the full Supreme Court decides whether to
grant a hearing on Van de Kamp's appeal.
   The court reconvenes Oct. 2 and is not likely to take up the
issue until then. If the court grants a hearing, an action that
requires votes from four of the nine justices, the stay will be
extended until the court rules in the case, O'Connor said.
   ``This order means that a merger threatening California shoppers
with hundreds of millions of dollars in higher grocery bills will
not take place until the United States Supreme Court can review
it,'' Van de Kamp said in a statement. He said he anticipates court
action in early October.
   Chief Assistant Attorney General Andrea Ordin said O'Connor's
order apparently does not require Van de Kamp to post a $16.3
million bond that a federal judge had earlier required as a
condition of the appeal. Van de Kamp had said he would drop the
appeal if the bond were required.
   ``I feel it does show that we have raised a very significant
issue: whether the remedy of divestiture, keeping the two entities
apart or being permitted to separate the two entities, is
available,'' Ms. Ordin said of O'Connor's order.
   Troy D'Ambrosio, spokesman for American Stores Co., Alpha Beta's
parent, declined comment.
   American Stores bought Lucky in June 1988 and predicted that
increased efficiency from the consolidation would save California
customers $50 million to $60 million a year. Lucky is the state's
largest grocery chain, Alpha Beta the fourth largest.
   The Federal Trade Commission approved the merger. But Van de
Kamp, in a suit claiming violation of federal antitrust law,
contended that the merged chain would dominate the marketplace in
many areas and lead to higher prices.
   U.S. District Judge David Kenyon of Los Angeles issued a
preliminary injunction last September ordering separate operation of
the chains, finding a likelihood of reduced competition.
   The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals said this March that there
was evidence to support Kenyon's finding but overruled his
injunction against the merger, saying it was too late to undo the
merger once the FTC had approved it.
   Kenyon then required Van de Kamp to post a $16.3 million bond in
order to block the merger while appealing to the Supreme Court,
saying the money was needed to cover American Stores' losses from a
delay of the merger.
   Van de Kamp disputed the company's claim of losses and also
argued that he should be exempt from the bond because he was suing
on behalf of the state's consumers.
   The appeals court did not lift the bond requirement, however, in
an order last Thursday that said the merger could proceed Monday.
Van de Kamp appealed to O'Connor, who handles emergency appeals from
9th Circuit rulings, and she intervened Monday before American
Stores could begin final action on the merger.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
