<FILEID>AP-NR-08-21-89 1856EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-HawaiianAir-Ueberroth 1stLd-Writethru f0Eds:CORRECTSEger'sfirstnameothBuyingHawaiianAirlines
08-21 0923</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hawaiian Air-Ueberroth, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0207,0951</SECOND>
<HEAD>Group Including Ueberroth Buying Hawaiian Airlines</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: INSERTS new grafs 7-10 to UPDATE with comment from Talbot; picks
up 7th graf pvs bg'ng, HAL denied ...; SUBS grafs 13-14 pvs to edit to
conform; picks up 15th graf pvs bg'ng, After graduating ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE ELLIOTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defeated in a high-profile attempt to buy Eastern
Airlines, former baseball commissioner Peter V. Ueberroth has turned
his attention to another financially struggling carrier.
   Ueberroth, whose first job after college was with a small airline
in Hawaii, is part of an investment group that has agreed to buy HAL
Inc., the parent of Hawaiian Airlines. The sports figure has gained
a reputation in professional baseball and the Olympics for turning
problem enterprises into moneymakers.
   HAL said Sunday its board of directors unanimously accepted a
tender offer of $22 a share from the group headed by J. Thomas
Talbot, a former airline executive from California.
   The group, which also includes Ueberroth's brother John, plans to
obtain at least 51 percent of HAL's stock. At $22 a share, the group
could purchase a majority of the company's 1.95 million outstanding
shares of common stock for about $21.9 million.
   HAL stock, boosted in recent months by takeover rumors, plunged
on the American Stock Exchange from its Friday closing of $31.62{ a
share to $25.25 a share Monday.
   ``I thought the other (stock) price was probably an inflated
one,'' said Louis Marckesano, an airline analyst with Janney
Montgomery Scott Inc. in Philadelphia. ``I think maybe this brings
it down to earth a little bit.''
   Talbot, reached at a Honolulu hotel, said his group plans to
improve Hawaiian Airlines' service with an infusion of capital in
the form of better planes and equipment.
   ``The company has built up a strong base, first with its 60 years
in the interisland markets and now reaching out to the mainland,''
Talbot said. ``We think the employees who have been here for years
are very strong.''
   Talbot said his group was attracted by Hawaiian's established
routes in the Pacific Basin, which he called a booming air travel
market.
   Talbot said he and Ueberroth, who was on the mainland, would hold
a news conference next week to discuss their plans for the airline.
   HAL denied rumors earlier this month that Delta Air Lines was
interested in acquiring it to ward off a takeover itself and gain
access fo Hawaiian Airlines' South Pacific and Japanese routes.
   HAL sustained a loss of $13 million in the first half of this
year and has lost a total of $30.6 million over the past 2{ years.
   Honolulu stockbroker Randy Havre of J.B. Havre Securities Inc.
said the $22-a-share offer was reasonable for long-term investors
and even was paying shareholders a premium on the stock's value,
which he estimated to be between $15 and $20 a share.
   ``The bottom line is the employees are going to win on this
because they're getting new management which will reduce the
instability caused by financial losses over the past few years,''
Havre said.
   He attributed HAL's consistent losses to the high cost of
maintaining its aging aircraft.
   HAL spokesman Keoni Wagner said he did not know how great a role
Ueberroth would play in the company. There were reports Monday that
he could become co-chairman with John Magoon Jr., HAL's current
chairman and chief executive officer.
   Ueberroth was unavailable for comment Monday on the takeover bid.
   Last spring, Ueberroth and Talbot headed a group which made a
$464 million bid for strikebound Eastern in partnership with its
three unions. The deal later fell apart over the unions' demand that
Frank Lorenzo, chairman of Eastern's parent Texas Air Corp., be
removed from daily control of the airline.
   After graduating from San Jose State College in California in
1959, Ueberroth worked for Trans International Airlines in Hawaii as
an operations manager and vice president through 1962.
   HAL completed a deal last year giving a subsidiary of Japan Air
Lines a 20 percent ownership stake and infusing almost $20 million
into Hawaiian Airlines.
   In its June 26 issue, Forbes magazine blasted the airline in an
article entitled ``What's Hawaiian for `Rotten Management?'''
   ``How do you flirt with bankruptcy in a business that is
indispensable during an unprecedented boom?'' the article read.
``You get swell-headed, expand stupidly, manage poorly, neglect
maintenance, delay and cancel flights and then plunge into a ruinous
price war trying to get a market share.''
   The magazine charged that Magoon ``has managed to run the state's
leading carrier almost into the ground.''
   Magoon owns 56.9 percent of HAL's common stock.
   HAL called the Forbes article superficial and subjective.
   Hawaiian Airlines, Hawaii's largest interisland airline, also
serves Los Angeles; San Francisco; Seattle; Anchorage, Alaska; Las
Vegas, Nev.; Australia; New Zealand and other South Pacific points.
   The 60-year-old airline's fleet of 31 planes carried 5.5 million
passengers in 1988.
   The tender offer is subject to a number of conditions, including
a satisfactory agreement with the company's unions, financing and
receipt of the required approvals from government agencies, HAL said.
   Lindsey Pollock, Hawaiian's senior vice president of marketing,
said HAL would call a shareholders meeting for next week for a vote
on the offer.
   Hawaiian's major interisland competitor is Aloha Airlines, which
had no immediate comment on the purchase, according to Aloha
spokeswoman Stephanie Ackerman.
   Hawaiian consistently has ranked among the nation's leaders in
consumer complaints compiled by the Department of Transportation for
problems with overbooking, reservations, ticketing, fares, refunds,
baggage handling and customer service.
</TEXT>
