<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-MAIBasic     08-21 0287</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-MAI Basic,0295</SECOND>
<HEAD>Computer Maker Reports Loss Due To Failed Takeover Bid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUSTIN, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   MAI Basic Four Inc. reported a quarterly
loss Monday of $46.2 million, including nearly $40 million in
unusual charges related to its failed takeover bid for Prime
Computer Inc. and a reorganization.
   The Tustin-based manufacturer of mid-size business computers said
earlier that it expected the loss for the quarter ended June 30,
which contrasted with a profit of $6.8 million, or 45 cents a share,
for the same period last year.
   Revenues for the period, which is the company's fiscal third
quarter, declined 23.4 percent to $86 million from $112.3 million in
the 1988 quarter.
   On Aug. 4, Natick, Mass.-based Prime accepted a buyout offer of
$1.2 billion from J.H. Whitney &amp; Co., a venture capital firm. MAI
Basic Four tried to buy all or part of Prime for nearly nine months.
Recently it offered $525 million for Prime's minicomputer unit.
   MAI, which is controlled by investor Bennett LeBow, attributed
the quarterly revenue decline primarily to lost business and
deferred buying decisions related to the tender offer. MAI put its
cost from the offer at $25 million and said a reorganization
announced subsequently would cost $14.2 million.
   MAI's president and chief executive officer, William Weksel, said
the takeover attempt coincided with a decline in the mid-range
computer business. He predicted a return to profitability by the
first quarter of its fiscal year 1990.
   For the first nine months of its fiscal year, the company
reported a net loss of $38.3 million compared with net income of
$18.7 million, or $1.25 per share, for the same period last year.
Revenue fell from $302.9 million to $298.4 million for the nine
months.
</TEXT>
