<FIRST>r f BC-UAL-FlightAttendants     08-21 0286</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-UAL-Flight Attendants,0297</SECOND>
<HEAD>Attendants Union Urges UAL To Carefully Weigh Sale</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top official of the Association of Flight
Attendants on Monday urged UAL Corp., parent of United Airlines, to
weigh carefully the interests of the company and its employees
before it considers selling it.
   ``Corporate raiders and arbitrageurs and others with only
short-term interests in mind are pressing for the board to hastily
choose to auction United Airlines to the highest bidder,'' Patricia
A. Friend, president of the UAL Master Executive Council of the AFA,
wrote to members of the UAL board.
   ``We urge each of you to continue to resist that pressure and to
consider carefully the interests of the airline and all of its
constituencies.''
   In her letter, Ms. Friend also called on Chicago-based UAL to
resume contract negotiations with the attendants union. Talks were
suspended last week.
   Los Angeles financier Marvin Davis has offered to buy UAL, owner
of the nation's second-largest airline, setting off a buying spree
in the company's stock, which soared $97 in two weeks and closed at
$273.75 Monday.
   Last week, Davis sweetened his proposal to $275 a share, or $6.19
billion.
   The company's directors have delayed a decision on his bid, but
confirmed reports they had been contacted by other potential buyers
and that their financial advisers had met with an unspecified
employee group.
   UAL spokesman Rob Doughty said the company would not comment on
Ms. Friend's letter, and he refused to say if the employee group
that financial advisers had met with last week was the United unit
of the Air Line Pilots Association.
   ALPA made a bid to buy the company in 1987. The offer was
rejected by the company's board.
</TEXT>
